ld''<ref>Gilbert: ''Argent, on a chevron gules three roses of the field''. These are the ancient arms of the family, as evidenced on monuments in Marldon Church 1496 and 1530 and in Churston Ferrers Church c.1575 (Source: Burke's Landed Gentry, 1937, p.886). In the 1620 Heraldic Visitation of Devon by [[William Camden]], Clarenceux King of Arms, the following arms were allowed to Raleigh Gilbert (1584-1634) of Compton: ''Ermine, on a chevron sable three roses argent''. (Source: Burke's Landed Gentry, 1937, p.886). The family's arms are very confused, for example as given in Vivian, p.405: ''Or, on a chevron sable three roses of the field leaved proper a bordure gules''. Pole, p.484, gives: ''Argent, on a chevron sable three roses of the field''</ref>\n|[[Compton Castle|Compton]], [[Marldon]]; [[Sandridge, Stoke Gabriel|Sandridge]], [[Stoke Gabriel]]; [[Greenway Estate|Greenway]], [[Churston Ferrers]]; [[Bovey Tracey]]; ([[Bodmin Priory]], Cornwall)\n|-\n|[[Edward Giles|Giles]]\n|[[File:GilesArms.png|70px]]\n|''Per chevron argent and azure, a lion rampant counterchanged collared or''\n|[[Bowden, Ashprington]]; [[Sharpham, Ashprington]]; Dean Court, [[Dean Prior]]\n|-\n|[[John Glanville (judge)|Glanville]]\n|[[File:GlanvilleArms.png|70px]]\n|''Azure, three saltires or''\n|Holwell; Kilworthy, Tavistock\n|-\n|Godwyn/Goodwyn\n|[[File:GodwynArms.png|70px]]\n|''Or, on a fess between six lion's heads erased gules an annulet of the field''\n|Clistwill, [[Plymtree]]; [[Great Torrington|Torrington]]\n|-\n|Goodridge\n|[[File:GoodridgeArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a fess sable in chief three cross crosslets fitch\u00e9e of the last''\n|[[Totnes]]\n|-\n|Gould\n|[[File:GouldArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Per saltire azure and or a lion rampant counterchanged''\n|[[Downes, Crediton]]; [[Floyer Hayes]]; [[Lew Trenchard]]\n|-\n|Gourney\n|[[File:GourneyArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a cross engrailed gules in the first quarter a cinquefoil vert''\n|[[Townstal]]; [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]]\n|-\n|Gove\n|[[File:GoveArms.png|70px]]\n|''Azure, a cross lozengy (argent and sable?) between four eagles displayed sable''\n|[[Woodbury, Devon|Woodbury]]\n|-\n|Greenwood\n|[[File:GreenwoodArms.png|70px]]\n|''Paly of six argent and sable, on a bend gules three escallops or''\n|[[Great Torrington|Torrington]]\n|-\n|Grylls\n|[[File:GryllsArms.png|70px]]\n|''Or, three bendlets enhanced gules ''\n|[[Tavistock]]\n|}\n\n===H===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Escutcheon !! Blazon !! Seat, parish\n|-\n|[[George Hakewill|Hakewill]]\n|[[File:HakewillArms.png|70px]]\n|''Or, a bend between six trefoils slipped purpure''\n|Exeter\n|-\n|[[John Hales (bishop of Coventry and Lichfield)|Hals]]\n|[[File:HalsArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a fess between three griffin's heads erased sable''\n|[[Kenedon]], [[Sherford (near Kingsbridge)|Sherford]]; Efford, [[Eggbuckland|Egg Buckland]]\n|-\n|Hamlyn\n|[[File:HamlynArms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, a lion rampant ermine crowned or''\n|[[Widecombe]]; [[Buckfastleigh]]; [[Woolfardisworthy, Torridge|Woolfardisworthy]]; [[Clovelly Court|Clovelly]]\n|-\n|Hancock\n|[[File:HancockArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Gules, on a chief argent three cocks of the field''\n|[[Manor of Combe Martin|Combe Martin]]; [[Mount Radford, Exeter]]\n|-\n|Harewood<ref>Henry Harewood (d.1631) by his will donated \u00a3100 as the \"Harewood Gift\", a charity for the poor of South Molton (Report of the Commissioners Appointed ...: To Inquire Concerning Charities ..., 1825, pp.125-6 [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=t4JPAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA125&lpg=PA125&dq=harewood+south+molton&source=bl&ots=rGnZIfnbpq&sig=kRUeDE2z5exh1qfET6lxCcsrsyc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZxbXouOvUAhVJDMAKHbVUCE8Q6AEIQTAE#v=onepage&q=harewood%20south%20molton&f=false])</ref>\n|[[File:HarewoodArms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, on a chief argent three hart's heads erased of the field''\n|[[South Molton]]\n|-\n|Harlewyn\n|[[File:HarlewynArms.png|70px]]\n|''Azure, a fess argent in base three apples of the last''\n|[[Sidmouth]]\n|-\n|[[Harpur-Crewe baronets|Harper]]\n|[[File:HarperArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a lion rampant a bordure engrailed sable a crescent for difference''\n|[[Berry Narbor]]; ([[Swarkestone Hall Pavilion|Swarkestone Hall]], [[Derbyshire]])\n|-\n|Harris (of [[Radford, Plymstock|Radford]])\n|[[File:Harris OfRadford Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, three crescents argent''\n|[[Radford, Plymstock|Radford]], [[Plymstock]]\n|-\n|[[Sir Arthur Harris, 1st Baronet, of Stowford|Harris]] (of [[Hayne, Stowford|Hayne]])\n|[[File:HarrisArms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, three crescents argent a bordure of the last''\n|[[Hayne, Stowford|Hayne]], [[Stowford]]\n|-\n|[[Edward Harris (Irish judge)|Harris]] (of Cornworthy)\n|[[File:Harris OfCornworthy Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, an antelope salient argent armed and crined or''\n|[[Cornworthy Priory]], [[Cornworthy]]\n|-\n|[[Marquess of Bristol|Harvey]]\n|[[File:HerveyArms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, on a bend argent three trefoils slipped vert''\n|[[Aylesbeare]]\n|-\n|Hatch\n|[[File:Hatch arms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Gules, two demi-lions passant guardant in pale or''\n|Hatch/Hacche, [[South Molton]]; Aller, South Molton; [[Woolleigh, Beaford|Woolleigh]], [[Beaford]]\n|-\n|Haydon\n|[[File:HaydonArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Argent, three bars gemels azure on a chief gules a fess dansett\u00e9e or''\n|[[Cadhay]], [[Ottery St Mary]]; Ebford, [[Woodbury, Devon|Woodbury]]\n|-\n|[[Sir Thomas Hele, 1st Baronet|Hele]]\n|[[File:HeleArms FusilsInBend.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, five fusils in bend argent on each an ermine spot''<ref>Pole, p.487; as seen on monument of [[Elize Hele]] (1560\u20131635) in [[Bovey Tracey]] Church</ref>\n|Hele, [[Cornwood]]; [[Flete House|Flete]], [[Holbeton]]; [[Wembury]]\n|-\n|Helman\n|[[File:HelmanArms.png|70px]]\n|''Vert, a chevron argent gutt\u00e9e de sang between three pheons or''\n|Furland\n|-\n|Hext\n|[[File:HextArms.png|70px]]\n|''Or, a tower triple-turreted between three battle axes sable''\n|[[Kingston, Devon|Kingston]]; Kingston, [[Staverton, Devon|Staverton]] (?)<ref>The family of Hext resided at a place named \"Kingston\", which although [[William Pole (antiquary)|Pole]] (d.1635) suggests (almost as a ''[[post scriptum]]'') is Kingston in the parish of Staverton (''\"At Kingston their also dwelled Thomas Hext in King Edw 4 tyme\"'' ([[William Pole (antiquary)|Pole, Sir William]] (d.1635), Collections Towards a Description of the County of Devon, [[Sir John de la Pole, 6th Baronet|Sir John-William de la Pole]] (ed.), London, 1791, p.277), cannot be reconciled with the well documented contemporaneous tenure of Kingston, Staverton, by the Barnhous family, whose heiress is known to have married John Rowe of Totnes. (During the reign of King Edward IV (1461-1483) \"Kingston\" was the seat of Thomas Hext, ([[William Pole (antiquary)|Pole, Sir William]] (d.1635), Collections Towards a Description of the County of Devon, [[Sir John de la Pole, 6th Baronet|Sir John-William de la Pole]] (ed.), London, 1791, p.277; Vivian, p.484, pedigree of ''Hext of Kingston'') one of whose daughters, Agnes Hext, married Sir [[Lewis Pollard]] (Vivian, p.598, pedigree of Pollard) (c.1465-1526) of [[Grilstone, Bishop's Nympton|Grilstone]] in the parish of [[Bishop's Nympton]], Devon, [[Justice of the Common Pleas]] from 1514 to 1526 ([[William George Hoskins|Hoskins, W.G.]], A New Survey of England: Devon, London, 1959 (first published 1954), p.338) and a [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Totnes (UK Parliament constituency)|Totnes]] in 1491) There is however a parish and village named [[Kingston, Devon|Kingston]] in South Devon, about 14 miles south-west of Kingston, Staverton, and Thomas Hext \"of Kingston\", the first member of the family recorded in the [[Heraldic Visitations]] of Devon, married a member of the [[Earl Fortescue|Fortescue family]] of [[Whympston, Modbury]], about 2 1/2 miles north-west of the village of Kingston.</ref>\n|-\n|Hill \n|[[File:Hill OfShilston Devon Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chevron between three water bougets sable ''\n|Shilston, Modbury<ref>Today, see Shilston Barton or Shilstone near Modbury. Sir Robert Hill jCP of Shilston and Houndstone, the father of Robert Hill [[Sheriff of Devon]] was kinsman  to Sir John Hill jKB of Hill's Court, Exeter and Houndstone, the father of Robert Hill of Spaxton MP</ref>\n|-\n|Hill\n|[[File:HillOfPlymouthArms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, a chevron ermine between three garbs or''\n|[[Plymouth]]; [[Cotleigh]]\n|-\n|Hillersdon\n|[[File:HillersdonArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, on a chevron sable three bull's heads cabossed of the field''\n|[[Hillersdon House|Hillersdon]], [[Cullompton]]; [[Membland]], [[Holbeton]]\n|-\n|[[William Hockmore|Hockmore]]\n|[[File:HockmoreArms.png|70px]]\n|''Per chevron sable and or, in chief two pairs of reaping hooks endorsed and entwined blades azure handles of the second in base a moorcock of the first combed and wattled gules''\n|[[Buckland Baron]], [[Combeinteignhead|Combe-in-Teignhead]]<ref>In the parish of Combe-in-Teignhead per Lysons, Magna Britannia, Vol.6, p.135</ref>\n|-\n|[[John Hody|Hody]]\n|[[File:Hody (of Stowell) Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a fess per fess indented vert and sable between two cotises counterchanged of the fess''<ref>Burke's General Armory, 1884, p.515; Pole, p.488; the blazon in Vivian, p.490, appears confused, producing an image thus[[:File:HodyArms.png]]</ref>\n|[[Nethway, Brixham|Nethway]],<ref>Pole, p.282-3; Risdon, p.160</ref> [[Brixham]]; ([[Pilsdon]], Dorset)<ref>Sir [[John Hody]] (d.1441) of Pilsdon in Dorset and Stowell, Wiveliscombe, Somerset, Chief Justice of the King's Bench, married Margaret Cole, heiress of Nethway (Pole, pp.282-3)</ref>\n|-\n|Holbeame\n|[[File:HolbeameArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chevron enarched sable''\n|Holbeame, [[West Ogwell]]; Bawcombe, [[Ugborough]](?)\n|-\n|[[Robert de Holland, 1st Baron Holand|Holland]]<ref>This family was descended from [[Robert de Holland, 1st Baron Holand]] (c. 1283 \u2013 1328), son of Sir Robert de Holland of Upholland, Lancashire