llets) hauriant argent  ''\n*Mille of Mille:  ''Ermine, a mill-rind sable ''\n*Michell of [[Talaton]]:  ''Per fess gules and sable, a chevron between three swans argent ''\n*Mohun of [[Mohuns Ottery]], [[Luppitt]]:  ''Gules, a maunch ermine the hand argent holding a fleur-de-lys or ''\n*Molton of [[Pinhoe]]:  ''Chequy or and sable ''\n*Molford of Cadley ([[Cadeleigh]]):  ''Sable, a fess ermine between three swans argent ''\n*Molford:  ''Sable, a fess between three swans argent ''\n*[[Ralph de Monthermer, 1st Baron Monthermer|Monthermer]] of [[Stokenham]]:  ''Or, an eagle displayed vert beaked and membered gules ''\n*[[Simon Montagu, 1st Baron Montagu|Montacut]] of [[Wonford]]:  '' Argent, three fusils in fess gules ''\n*[[John Montagu, 1st Baron Montagu|Montacute]] of  [[Stokenham]]:  ''Argent, three fusils in fess gules a bordure sable''\n\n==See also==\n*[[Flag of Devon]]\n*[[Cornish heraldry]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{Cite book |editor-last=Vivian |editor-first=Lt.Col. J.L. |year=1895 |title=The Visitations of the County of Devon: Comprising the Heralds' Visitations of 1531, 1564 & 1620 |location=Exeter |ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:Devon heraldry]]\n[[Category:History of Devon]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Powderham Castle, 2009.jpg|thumb|The arms of [[House of Courtenay|Courtenay]] on display above [[Powderham Castle]] in Devon in 2015, a seat of that family since the 14th century]]\n[[File:Fortescue BannerOfArms FilleighChurch Devon.PNG|thumb|Fortescue [[banner of arms]] in the Fortescue Chapel of St Paul's Church, [[Filleigh]], Devon. The Fortescue family ([[Earl Fortescue]]) were lords of the manor of Filleigh, in which parish is situated their former seat, [[Castle Hill, Filleigh|Castle Hill]]. The last Fortescue to own Castle Hill was Lady Margaret Fortescue (1923-2013), eldest daughter and co-heiress of [[Hugh Fortescue, 5th Earl Fortescue]] (1888-1958), although now owned by her daughter Eleanor, Countess of Arran (n\u00e9e van Cutsem) who lives there with her husband [[Arthur Gore, 9th Earl of Arran]]]]\nThe [[landed gentry]] and [[nobility]] of [[Devonshire]], like the rest of the English and European gentry, bore [[heraldry|heraldic arms]] from the start of the age of heraldry ''circa'' 1200-1215. The fashion for the display of heraldry ceased about the end of the [[Victorian era]] (1901) by which time most of the ancient armigerous families of Devonshire had died out, moved away or parted with their landed estates.<ref>For a discussion of the disappearance of the old gentry families of Devon, see [[Sabine Baring-Gould]], ''Old Country Life'', first published 1889, 5th ed., 1894, pp.7-22, ''Old County Families''[https://archive.org/details/oldcountrylife00bari]</ref> \n\nToday a very few ancient families remain in the county represented by direct male descendants, most notably [[Earl of Devon|Courtenay]] of [[Manor of Powderham|Powderham]], Fulford of [[Great Fulford|Fulford]],  Kelly of Kelly, Cruwys of [[Cruwys Morchard]], [[Baron Clifford|Clifford]] of [[Chudleigh]], [[Acland Baronets|Acland]] of [[Killerton]] and [[Broadclyst]], [[Wrey Baronets|Wrey]] of [[Tawstock]], etc. A few ancient Devon estates are still owned by descendants via female lines, for example [[Castle Hill, Filleigh]], [[Manor of Molland|Molland]], [[Incledon, Braunton]], [[Hall, Bishop's Tawton]], [[Newnham Park]], etc. In most cases the laws of English heraldry preclude the transmission of paternal armorials via a female heiress (other than in the form of [[Quartering (heraldry)|quartering]]), thus most of these inheritors via female lines, generally deriving from the same pool of high-status English armigerous families, bring their own paternal heraldry, possibly previously foreign to Devon, to the estates inherited. \n\nFor example, the Irish arms of Gore ([[Earl of Arran (Ireland)|Earl of Arran]]) are now associated with [[Castle Hill, Filleigh]], until 1958 the seat of the last male representative of the [[Earl Fortescue|Fortescue family]] which originated in Devon in the 12th century. In a few cases however, male heirs via female lines have been required by the legator to seek royal licence to adopt his own arms and surname, otherwise destined to disappearance, in lieu of the legatees own. This was the case with the families most notably of [[Mark Rolle|Rolle]], [[Basset family|Basset]], [[Stucley Baronets|Stucley]], [[Bradfield House|Walrond]], etc.\n\n{{Compact ToC |pre1=Standard sources |pre2=List of Devon arms |prebreak=yes |custom1=Blazons by Sir William Pole  |notes=yes|seealso=yes|x=|z=}}\n\n==Standard sources==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2016}}\nThe standard sources for students of the '''heraldry of Devon''' are as follows:\n\n===Documents===\n*[[Heraldic visitation|Heraldic Visitations]] of Devon: [[John Lambrick Vivian|Vivian, Lt.Col. J.L.]], (Ed.) The Visitations of the County of Devon: Comprising the Heralds' Visitations of 1531, 1564 & 1620, Exeter, 1895.\n*[[William Pole (antiquary)|Pole, Sir William]] (d.1635), Collections Towards a Description of the County of Devon, [[Sir John de la Pole, 6th Baronet|Sir John-William de la Pole]] (ed.), London, 1791:\n**\"The Armes of such nobles and gentlemen which have anciently dwelled & had lands in Devonshire\", pp.&nbsp;444\u2013467;\n**\"An alphabet of the armes of the gentlemen of Devonshire as well of those being as of those which have bine\", pp.&nbsp;467\u2013510;\n*The Notebook of [[Tristram Risdon]] (d.1640)[https://archive.org/stream/notebookoftristr00risdrich/notebookoftristr00risdrich_djvu.txt]\n*[[Samuel Lysons|Lysons, Samuel]] and [[Daniel Lysons (antiquarian)|Lysons, Daniel]],  [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=50555 Magna Britannia, Volume 6: ''Devonshire'', London, 1822]:\n**Ancient Families, of which the principal Branch is extinct, or removed, since 1620, yet some of the Descendants remain in the County.\n**Families known, or supposed, to be extinct since 1620, or removed out of the County.\n*[[John Prince (biographer)|Prince, John]], (1643\u20131723) The Worthies of Devon, 1810 edition, \"Arms, Crests and Mottoes of the Families treated of in this Work\", blazons pp.&nbsp;779\u201385 & plates I-V following: \"Arms\" (monochrome depictions of 145 shields)\n*[[Sabine Baring-Gould|Baring-Gould, Sabine]] & Twigge, Robert, ''An Armory of the Western Counties (Devon and Cornwall): From the Unpublished Manuscripts of the XVI Century'', published by J.G. Commin, 1898 [https://archive.org/stream/anarmorywestern00twiggoog#page/n4/mode/2up]\n*[[George Carew, 1st Earl of Totnes|Carew, Sir George]] (1555-1629) (created in 1626 [[Earl of Totnes]]), ''Carew's Scroll of Arms 1588, Collected from Churches in Devonshire etc., with Additions from Joseph Holland's Collection of Arms 1579'', Exeter, 1901. ( See also: Devon & Cornwall Notes and Queries, Vol. 1, pt. 2)\n*Colby, Rev. Frederick T., ''The Heraldry of Exeter''[http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archiveDS/archiveDownload?t=arch-1132-1/dissemination/pdf/030/030_235_263.pdf]; See also: Westcote, Thomas, ''View of Devonshire'', Chap. XV [https://archive.org/details/aviewdevonshire00westgoog/page/n167 <!-- quote=blundell paly of five gules and argent. -->], list of arms in [[Exeter Guildhall]]\n*Izacke, Richard & Samuel, ''A Perfect Catalogue of all the Sheriffs of the County of Devon with their Several Coats of Armory Described from the Beginning of the Reign of King Henry the Second Annoq. Dom. 1155''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Q29bAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA262&lpg=PA262&dq=horton+arms+bends+engrailed+canton&source=bl&ots=_WnsQ4X5Zh&sig=ACfU3U1L_jVQiGfE70vqb8gk_gUTxavnGg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjgw57Js5TnAhXWWhUIHd0YA1kQ6AEwAXoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=horton%20arms%20bends%20engrailed%20canton&f=false]. Also lists arms of corporations of Exeter.\n\n===Observation===\n{{Original research|section|date=December 2016}}\nObservation of surviving monuments in parish churches and mansion houses. As for the arms of Courtenay: \"the stamp of whose almost princely authority may be extensively recognised throughout the county\" (Davidson).<ref>Quoted by [[William Henry Hamilton Rogers|Rogers, William Henry Hamilton]], Memorials of the West, Historical and Descriptive, Collected on the Borderland of Somerset, Dorset and Devon, Exeter, 1888, p.351 [https://archive.org/stream/memorialsofwesth00roge#page/n415/mode/2up]</ref> Frequently discrepancies between these sources exist. Painted monuments in parish churches often have been restored, in some cases several times over the centuries, and the arms depicted may not be as originally painted. Heraldry sculpted in relief on stone is liable to wear and crumbling, especially when placed in the favourite location, exposed to the elements for centuries, on the porch or gatehouse of the family mansion. Ancient [[monumental brass]]es do not show tinctures but otherwise provide lasting records of heraldry. Stained glass depictions are optimal sources as they include tinctures, but ancient survivals are rare. Mural monuments placed high up on walls generally survive vandalism of past ages whilst paintings of arms on escutcheons sculpted in stone on mediaeval [[chest tomb]]s have rarely survived and often were \"scraped\" clean of all decoration in the 17th century. Heraldic monuments displaying a family's arms are generally found in the church of the parish in which is situated their seat, but the paternal arms may also be found in remoter parish churches where a daughter of the family has married into a family resident there. In such a case the arms are shown [[Impalement (heraldry)|impaled]] by the arms of her husband. Clearly the greatest problems in tracing heraldry relate to long extinct families. A few ancient Devon families survive, such as the Fortescues, and a flag showing the Fortescue arms still flies above [[Castle Hill, Filleigh|Castle Hill]] in 2013. There is no shortage of surviving examples of the arms of the Chichesters and Rolles, but surviving heraldry of the ancient Courtenay Earls of Devon seated at Tiverton Castle is rare, although frequently shown as [[Quartering (heraldry)|quarterings]] in the arms of related families.\n\n==List of Devon arms==\nThe following [[Heraldry|armorials]] are listed in the [[Heraldic visitation|Heraldic Visitations]] of Devon, 1531, 1564 & 1620:{{sfn|Vivian|1895}}\n{{Expand list|date=May 2013}}\n\n===A===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Escutcheon !! Blazon !! Seat, parish\n|-\n|Abbott\n|[[File:AbbottArms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, a cross voided between four eagles displayed or''\n|[[Hartland Abbey]]; [[Luffincott]]\n|-\n|Acland\n|[[File:Arms of Acland.svg|70px]]\n|''Chequy argent and sable, a fesse gules''\n|[[Acland, Landkey|Acland Barton]], [[Landkey]]; [[Holnicote]], Somerset; [[Killerton]], Devon; [[Fremington House]], [[Fremington, Devon|Fremington]]; [[Hawkridge, Chittlehampton]]; [[Combe, Goodleigh]]; Sprydon, [[Broadclyst]]\n|-\n|[[Nicholas Adams (died 1584)|Adams]]\n|[[File:AdamsOfTunstallDevonArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Or, a lion rampant between six crosses crosslet within a bordure engrailed sable''\n|[[Townstal]], [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]]; [[Bowden, Ashprington]](?); (Charlton Adam, Ilchester, Somerset)\n|-\n|Addington\n|[[File:AddingtonArms.png|70px]]\n|'' Per pale ermine and ermines, on a chevron between three fleurs-de-lys four lozenges all counterchanged''\n|Leigh\n|-\n|Aleyn\n|[[File:AleynArms.png|70px]]\n|''Per bend rompu argent and sable, six martlets counterchanged''\n|[[Bampton, Devon|Bampton]]\n|-\n|Amadas\n|[[File:AmadasArms.png|70px]]\n|''Azure, a chevron ermine between three oaken slips acorned proper''\n|[[Plymouth]]\n|-\n|[[Griffith Ameredith|Amerideth]]\n|[[File:AmeridethArms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, a lion rampant regardant or''\n|Pole,<ref>Pole, p.287; [[Richard Polwhele|Polwhele, Richard]], ''History of Devonshire'', 3 Vols., Vol.3, London, 1793, p.478</ref> [[Slapton, Devon|Slapton]]\n|-\n|Amory\n|[[File:AmoryOfWhitechapelDevonArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Barry nebul\u00e9 of six argent and gules, over all a bend azure''\n|[[Whitechapel, Bishops Nympton]]\n|-\n|Arscott\n|[[File:ArscottArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Per chevron azure and ermine in chief two buck's heads cabossed or''\n|Arscott, [[Holsworthy, Devon|Holsworthy]];<ref>Hoskins, p.411</ref> Dunsland, [[Bradford, Devon|Bradford]]; [[Tetcott]]; [[Annery, Monkleigh]]\n|-\n|Ashe/Aysshe/Esse\n|[[File:Esse of Sowton Devon Arms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Argent, two chevrons sable''\n|[[Sowton]], ''alias'' Clist Fomeson/Somson\n|-\n|Atwill\n|[[File:AtwillArms.png|70px]]\n|'' Argent, a chevron sable over all a pile counterchanged''\n|[[Mamhead]]; [[Walkhampton]]\n|-\n|Ayre\n|[[File:AyreArms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, on a bend between six crosses form\u00e9e fitch\u00e9e argent three mullets sable''\n|Wotton, [[Atherington, Devon|Atherington]]\n|-\n|Ayshford\n|[[File:AyshfordArms.jpg|70px]]\n|''Argent, between two chevrons sable three ashen keys vert''\n|Ayshford, [[Burlescombe]]\n|-\n|[[Babington family|Babington]]\n|[[File:COA of Babington.svg|70px]]\n|''Argent, ten torteaux in chief a label of three points azure''\n|[[Ottery St Mary]]\n|}\n\n===B===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Escutcheon !! Blazon !! Seat, parish\n|-\n|Badcocke\n|[[File:BadcockeArms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, on a pale argent three cocks gules''\n|[[Shebbear, Devon|Shebbear]]\n|-\n|Bagg\n|[[File:BaggArms.png|70px]]\n|''Lozengy argent and gules, on a chief or three cinquefoils azure''\n|[[Plymouth]]; [[Saltram House|Saltram]], [[Plympton St Mary]]\n|-\n|[[Peter Ball (MP)|Ball]]\n|[[File:BallArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chevron gules between three [[Shell (projectile)|fire balls]] proper''<ref>As seen in 19th c. stained glass window in Mamhead Church. Blazoned with chevron sable and with difference of a martlet, per Vivian, p.35</ref>\n|[[Mamhead]]\n|-\n|[[Baron Poltimore|Bampfylde/Bampfield]]\n|[[File:Arms of Bampfylde of Poltimore.svg|70px]]\n|''Or, on a bend gules three mullets argent''\n|[[Poltimore House|Poltimore]]; [[North Molton]]; [[Warleigh, Tamerton Foliot]]; Bampfield House, [[Exeter]]\n|-\n|Barby\n|[[File:BarbyArms.png|70px]]\n|'' Argent, a chevron between three garbs or''\n|[[Washfield]]\n|-\n|Barkley\n|[[File:Barkley OfOkenburyDevon Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, a fess ermine between three cinquefoils argent''<ref>Barkley arms identical to Potter arms, see Vivian pp.43,612. Escallops in place of cinqufoils per Pole, p.469</ref>\n|Okenbury, [[Ringmore]]\n|-\n|Barry\n|[[File:Barry arms.svg|70px]]\n|''Barry of six argent and gules''\n|Winscott, [[St Giles in the Wood]]\n|-\n|Bartlett\n|[[File:Bartlett (of Ludbrooke) arms.svg|70px]]\n|''Ermine, on a pale nebul\u00e9e azure three sinister gloves pendent tasselated argent the whole between two flaunches of the second each charged with two crescents palewise of the third''\n|Ludbrooke, [[Ermington, Devon|Ermington]]\n|-\n|[[Basset family|Basset]]\n|[[File:Arms of Basset.svg|70px]]\n|''Barry wavy of six or and gules''\n|[[Whitechapel, Bishops Nympton]]; [[Umberleigh]]; [[Heanton Punchardon]]; [[Watermouth Castle]]\n|-\n|Bastard\n|[[File:BastardArms.png|70px]]\n|''Or, a chevron azure''\n|[[Efford]], [[Egg Buckland]]; Garston, [[West Alvington]]; [[Kitley]], [[Yealmpton]]; [[Sharpham, Ashprington]]; [[Lyneham, Yealmpton]]; Buckland Court, [[Buckland-in-the-Moor]]\n|-\n|Battishill\n|[[File:BattishillArms.png|70px]]\n|''Azure, a cross-crosslet in saltire between four owls argent legged and beaked or''\n|South Tawton; Drewsteignton; Spreyton\n|-\n|[[Richard Beaple|Beaple]]\n|[[File:BeapleArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Gules, a bend vairy between six escallops argent''\n|[[Barnstaple]]; [[Knowstone]];\n|-\n|Beaumont\n|[[File:Beaumont (of Shirwell) Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Barry vair and gules''\n|[[Youlston Park|Youlston]], [[Shirwell]]; Gittisham\n|-\n|Bellew\n|[[File:BellewArms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable fretty or''\n|[[Stockleigh English]]; [[Ash Barton Estate|Ash]], [[Braunton]]\n|-\n|[[Ambrose Bellot|Bellot