illiam]] (d.1635), Collections Towards a Description of the County of Devon, [[Sir John de la Pole, 6th Baronet|Sir John-William de la Pole]] (ed.), London, 1791, p.277; Vivian, p.484, pedigree of ''Hext of Kingston'') one of whose daughters, Agnes Hext, married Sir [[Lewis Pollard]] (Vivian, p.598, pedigree of Pollard) (c.1465-1526) of [[Grilstone, Bishop's Nympton|Grilstone]] in the parish of [[Bishop's Nympton]], Devon, [[Justice of the Common Pleas]] from 1514 to 1526 ([[William George Hoskins|Hoskins, W.G.]], A New Survey of England: Devon, London, 1959 (first published 1954), p.338) and a [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Totnes (UK Parliament constituency)|Totnes]] in 1491) There is however a parish and village named [[Kingston, Devon|Kingston]] in South Devon, about 14 miles south-west of Kingston, Staverton, and Thomas Hext \"of Kingston\", the first member of the family recorded in the [[Heraldic Visitations]] of Devon, married a member of the [[Earl Fortescue|Fortescue family]] of [[Whympston, Modbury]], about 2 1/2 miles north-west of the village of Kingston.</ref>\n|-\n|Hill \n|[[File:Hill OfShilston Devon Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chevron between three water bougets sable ''\n|Shilston, Modbury<ref>Today, see Shilston Barton or Shilstone near Modbury. Sir Robert Hill jCP of Shilston and Houndstone, the father of Robert Hill [[Sheriff of Devon]] was kinsman  to Sir John Hill jKB of Hill's Court, Exeter and Houndstone, the father of Robert Hill of Spaxton MP</ref>\n|-\n|Hill\n|[[File:HillOfPlymouthArms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, a chevron ermine between three garbs or''\n|[[Plymouth]]; [[Cotleigh]]\n|-\n|Hillersdon\n|[[File:HillersdonArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, on a chevron sable three bull's heads cabossed of the field''\n|[[Hillersdon House|Hillersdon]], [[Cullompton]]; [[Membland]], [[Holbeton]]\n|-\n|[[William Hockmore|Hockmore]]\n|[[File:HockmoreArms.png|70px]]\n|''Per chevron sable and or, in chief two pairs of reaping hooks endorsed and entwined blades azure handles of the second in base a moorcock of the first combed and wattled gules''\n|[[Buckland Baron]], [[Combeinteignhead|Combe-in-Teignhead]]<ref>In the parish of Combe-in-Teignhead per Lysons, Magna Britannia, Vol.6, p.135</ref>\n|-\n|[[John Hody|Hody]]\n|[[File:Hody (of Stowell) Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a fess per fess indented vert and sable between two cotises counterchanged of the fess''<ref>Burke's General Armory, 1884, p.515; Pole, p.488; the blazon in Vivian, p.490, appears confused, producing an image thus[[:File:HodyArms.png]]</ref>\n|[[Nethway, Brixham|Nethway]],<ref>Pole, p.282-3; Risdon, p.160</ref> [[Brixham]]; ([[Pilsdon]], Dorset)<ref>Sir [[John Hody]] (d.1441) of Pilsdon in Dorset and Stowell, Wiveliscombe, Somerset, Chief Justice of the King's Bench, married Margaret Cole, heiress of Nethway (Pole, pp.282-3)</ref>\n|-\n|Holbeame\n|[[File:HolbeameArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chevron enarched sable''\n|Holbeame, [[West Ogwell]]; Bawcombe, [[Ugborough]](?)\n|-\n|[[Robert de Holland, 1st Baron Holand|Holland]]<ref>This family was descended from [[Robert de Holland, 1st Baron Holand]] (c. 1283 \u2013 1328), son of Sir Robert de Holland of Upholland, Lancashire (See Vivian, p.475)</ref>\n|[[File:Holland OfWeare Devon Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Azure sem\u00e9e-de-lys argent, a lion rampant of the second''\n|[[Countess Wear]]; Upcott, [[Sheepwash, Devon|Sheepwash]]\n|-\n|Holway of Waton<ref>Not to be confused with arms of Holway of Holway, Tor Bryan, Devon (see Pole, p.488)</ref>\n|[[File:Holway OfWaton Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, two swords in saltire hilts and pommels in chief the dexter surmounted by the sinister''\n|Waton (''alias'' Wadeton, Wayton, etc.), [[Stoke Gabriel]]<ref>Risdon, pp.157-8; Pole, p.284</ref>\n|-\n|Hooker ''alias'' Vowell\n|[[File:HookerAliasVowellArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Or, a fess vair between two lions passant guardant sable''\n|St Mary Major, [[Exeter]]\n|-\n|Hore\n|[[File:HoreArms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, an eagle double-headed displayed argent a bordure engrailed of the last''\n|[[Chagford]]\n|-\n|Howper/[[Nicholas Hooper (1654-1731)|Hooper]]\n|[[File:Hooper Arms OfFullabrook Braunton Devon.PNG|70px]]\n|''Gyronny of eight or and ermine, over all a castle triple-towered sable''\n|[[Musbury]]; Fullabrook, [[Braunton]]; [[Raleigh, Pilton]]\n|-\n|Howpill\n|[[File:HowpillArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, on a pale gules three lion's faces or''\n|Exeter, [[St Mary Arches Church, Exeter|St Mary Arches]] (?)\n|-\n|[[Joseph Hunkin (Governor of Scilly)|Hunkin]]\n|[[File:HunkinArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a mascle sable over all a fess of the last''\n|Gatherleigh, [[Lifton, Devon|Lifton]]\n|-\n|Hunt<ref>Thomas Hunt (d.1548) was thrice [[Mayor of Exeter]] (Vivian, p.494)</ref>\n|[[File:HuntOfChudleighArms.png|70px]]\n|''Azure, on a bend between two water bougets or three leopard's faces gules''\n|[[Hams, Chudleigh]]<ref>For Hams as the seat of Hunt see: Jones, Mary, History of Chudleigh, 1852</ref>\n|}\n\n===I===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Escutcheon !! Blazon !! Seat, parish\n|-\n|[[Benjamin Incledon|Incledon]]\n|[[File:IncledonArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chevron engrailed between three tuns sable fire issuing from the bung hole proper''\n|[[Incledon, Braunton]]; [[Buckland, Braunton]]; [[Colleton, Chulmleigh]]; [[Pilton House, Pilton]]; [[Yeotown, Goodleigh]]\n|-\n|Inglett\n|[[File:InglettArms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, a bend argent between three escallops or''\n|[[Alwington]]; [[Lamerton]]\n|-\n|Isack\n|[[File:IsackArms.png|70px]]\n|''Per pale azure and purpure, a cross flory or between four lambs argent''<ref>Vivian, p.502, p.502, footnote, as appears on the Risdon monument in Westdown Church, Devon also in St Giles-in-the-Wood Church, Devon</ref>\n|Boreat, [[Atherington, Devon|Atherington]]\n|}\n\n===J===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Escutcheon !! Blazon !! Seat, parish\n|-\n|Jarvys\n|[[File:JarvysArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, six ostrich feathers sable, three, two and one''\n|Stralling<ref>\"Stralling\" (Vivian, p.504), location unknown; ? Stalling Thorne in the parish of Huntsham ?</ref>\n|-\n|[[John Jewel|Jewell]]\n|[[File:JewellArms.png|70px]]\n|''Or, on a chevron azure between three gillyflowers gules stalked and leaved vert a maiden's head of the first ducally crowned of the third on a chief sable a hawk's lure double stringed between two falcons argent beaked and legged of the first''\n|Bowden, [[Berry Narbor]]\n|}\n\n===K===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Escutcheon !! Blazon !! Seat, parish\n|-\n|[[John Kelland|Kellond]]\n|[[File:KellondArms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, a fess argent in chief three fleurs-de-lys of the last''\n|[[Painsford, Ashprington|Painsford]], [[Ashprington]]\n|-\n|Kelloway\n|[[File:KellowayArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, two grozing irons in saltire sable between four Kelway pears proper''<ref>Vivian, p.510 adds ''a bordure engrailed of the second''. No such border is visible in any of the many depictions of the Kelloway arms surviving in the churches of Dolton, Iddisleigh, and Dowland; However, the bordure does appear in the Kelloway arms shown in Branscombe Church, Devon, on the Mural monument to Joan Tregarthin (d.1583) widow successively of John Kelloway of Cornwall and John Wadham (d.1578) of Merifield, Ilton, Somerset and Edge, Branscombe. See File:JoanTregarthinMonument BranscombeChurch Devon.PNG</ref>\n|[[Stafford Barton|Stowford/Stafford]], [[Dolton, Devon|Dolton]]\n|-\n|Kelly\n|[[File:KellyArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chevron between three billets gules''\n|[[Kelly House, Devon|Kelly]]\n|-\n|[[George Kendall (theologian)|Kendall]]\n|[[File:KendallArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chevron between three dolphins naiant embowed sable''\n|[[Kingsbridge]]; [[Cofton]], nr. [[Dawlish]]\n|-\n|[[John Kirkham (1472-1529)|Kirkham]]\n|[[File:KirkhamArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, three lions rampant gules a bordure engrailed sable''\n|[[Blagdon, Paignton]]; Bidwell, [[Newton St Cyres]]<ref>Vivian, p.517</ref>\n|-\n|Knapman