riel]]; Beenleigh,<ref>\"Bingley\" or \"Bindley\" (Vivian, p.609)</ref> Harberton Ford, [[Harberton]]\n|-\n|[[John Popham (judge)|Popham]]\n|[[File:PophamArms3.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, on a chief gules two stag's heads cabosed or''\n|[[Lynton]]; ([[Huntworth]] in Somerset; [[Popham, Hampshire|Popham]] in Hampshire; [[Littlecote, Wiltshire|Littlecote]] in Wiltshire)\n|-\n|Pote\n|[[File:PoteArms.png|70px]]\n|''Azure, a chevron engrailed cotised argent between three doves of the second''\n|[[Clawton]]\n|-\n|Potter<ref>Hugh Potter (1596-1661/2) (eldest son and heir of Tobias Potter of Iddesleigh) was a lawyer of [[Lincoln's Inn]] and a member of the household of the [[Earl of Northumberland]] (Vivian, p.612)</ref>\n|[[File:Barkley OfOkenburyDevon Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, a fess ermine between three cinquefoils argent''<ref>Potter arms identical to Barkley arms, see Vivian pp.43,612</ref>\n|[[Iddesleigh]]\n|-\n|Preston<ref>The Preston family of Devon was a junior branch of the ''de Preston'' family which during the reign of King Henry II (1154-1189) was seated at Preston Richard and Preston Patrick in Westmorland. On 1 April 1644  George Preston (of same ancient descent, same arms) was created a baronet \"of Furness in the County of Lancaster\". (Burke, Bernard, ''Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Extinct and Dormant Baronetcies ...'', 2nd ed, 1844, pp.424 et seq [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=j3Q-AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA427&lpg=PA427&dq=preston+baronets+westmorland&source=bl&ots=CRWW82cJXc&sig=ywGeXG7EYaSBeECMx9Kc2sVvBTk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHk-XdutbQAhVrJcAKHQu6BeA4ChDoAQgfMAE#v=onepage&q=preston%20baronets%20westmorland&f=false])</ref>\n|[[File:PrestonArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, two bars gules on a canton of the last a cinquefoil or''\n|[[Upottery]]\n|-\n|Prestwood\n|[[File:PrestwoodArms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, a lion rampant between two flaunches or''\n|[[Exeter]]\n|-\n|[[Prideaux baronets|Prideaux]]\n|[[File:PrideauxArms2.PNG|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chevron sable in chief a label of three points gules''\n|[[Orcheton, Modbury]]; Adeston, [[Holbeton]]; [[Thuborough, Sutcombe]]; [[Soldon, Holsworthy]]; [[Netherton, Farway]]; [[Ashburton, Devon|Ashburton]]; [[Nutwell]], [[Woodbury, Devon|Woodbury]]; [[Ford Abbey]], [[Thorncombe]]; (also [[Prideaux Place]], [[Padstow]] and [[Prideaux Castle]], [[Luxulyan]], Cornwall)\n|-\n|Prouse\n|[[File:ProuseArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Sable, three lions rampant argent''\n|[[Gidleigh Castle]]; [[Chagford]]; [[Lustleigh]]; [[Barnstaple]]; [[Tiverton, Devon|Tiverton]]\n|-\n|Prouse<ref>Members of this family include Richard Prouse (d.1608), [[Mayor of Exeter]], and his son John Prouse (d.1624/5), Mayor of Exeter in 1620, whose memorial exists in Exeter Cathedral (Vivian, p.628, \"MI\")</ref>\n|[[File:Prouse ofExeter Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Ermine, three lions rampant argent''\n|[[Exeter]]\n|-\n|Prust\n|[[File:PrustArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Gules, on a chief argent two estoiles sable''\n|Thorry, [[Hartland, Devon|Hartland]]; Gorven, [[Hartland, Devon|Hartland]]; [[Annery, Monkleigh]]\n|-\n|Prye\n|[[File:ArmsOfPrye OfHorwellColebrooke Devon.PNG|70px]]\n|''Ermine, a chevron sable a chief azure fretty or''<ref>per Pole, Sir William (d.1635), Collections Towards a Description of the County of Devon, Sir John-William de la Pole (ed.), London, 1791, p.498. Alternatively: ''Ermine, a chevron gules a chief azure fretty or'' (per Vivian,  p.631, pedigree of Prye of Horwell). These arms are visible on the monument to John Wrey (d.1597) in Tawstock Church, Devon. John Wrey's son Edmond Wrey married Katherine Prye, daughter of Roger Prye of Horwell (Vivian, p.631)</ref>\n|Horwell, [[Colebrooke, Devon|Colebrooke]]\n|-\n|Pyne<ref>This family was the heir of Coffin of Portledge, Alwington, Devon, and in 1796 assumed the additional surname and arms of Coffin, resulting in the name Pine-Coffin (Vivian, p.211)</ref>\n|[[File:Pyne OfEastDown Devon Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, a chevron ermine between three pine apples or''\n|[[East Down, Devon|East Down]]; [[Portledge Manor|Portledge]], [[Alwington]]\n|}\n\n===Q===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Escutcheon !! Blazon !! Seat, parish\n|-\n|[[John Quicke (1724-1776)|Quicke]]\n|[[File:QuickeArms.svg|70px]]\n|''Sable, a chevron vaire or and of the first between three griffin's heads erased of the second''\n|Newton House, [[Newton St Cyres]]; Sherwood,<ref>[[Rosemary Lauder|Lauder, Rosemary]], Devon Families, Tiverton, 2002, p.129, sold by Savilles estate agent February 2017, \u00a31.5M [https://search.savills.com/property-detail/gbetrsexs120254#/r/detail/GBETRSEXS120254]</ref> [[Newton St Cyres]]\n|}\n\n===R===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Escutcheon !! Blazon !! Seat, parish\n|-\n|[[Nicholas Radford|Radford]]\n|[[File:RadfordArms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, three lampagoes passant coward in pale argent''\n|[[Upcott, Cheriton Fitzpaine]]; Okeford; Rockbeare\n|-\n|Raleigh\n|[[File:Arms of Raleigh.svg|70px]]\n|''Gules crusilly or, a bend vair'' or ''Gules, a bend vair between six cross-crosslets or''\n|[[Raleigh, Pilton]]\n|-\n|[[Walter Raleigh|Raleigh]]\n|[[File:Raleigh OfFardell Arms.svg|70px]]\n|''Gules, five fusils conjoined in bend argent''<ref>Raleigh of Fardel arms per [[William Pole (antiquary)|Pole, Sir William]] (d.1635), Collections Towards a Description of the County of Devon, [[Sir John de la Pole, 6th Baronet|Sir John-William de la Pole]] (ed.), London, 1791, p.499; Pedigree given in Vivian (pp.638-9) with same descent as Raleigh of Pilton, but with wrong arms</ref>\n|[[Fardel, Cornwood]]; [[Colaton Raleigh]];<ref>Vivian, p.638</ref> Smallridge, [[Axminster]];<ref>Pole, p.321</ref> ([[Nettlecombe, Somerset|Nettlecombe Raleigh]], Somerset)\n|-\n|Randall\n|[[File:RandallArms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, three demi-lions rampant erased argent''\n|[[Kentisbury]]\n|-\n|Rede\n|[[File:RedeArms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, on a bend nebul\u00e9e argent three [[shoveler]]s sable''\n|[[Wembury]]\n|-\n|Reynell\n|[[File:ReynellArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Argent, masonry sable a chief indented of the second''\n|[[Forde House|Forde]], [[Wolborough]]; [[East Ogwell]]\n|-\n|Rider\n|[[File:RiderArms.png|70px]]\n|''Azure, three crescents or''\n|[[Bere Ferrers]]\n|-\n|[[Earl of Londonderry|Ridgeway]]\n|[[File:RidgewayArms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, a pair of wings conjoined and elevated argent''\n|[[Tor Mohun]]; [[Abbotskerswell|Abbots Carswell]]\n|-\n|[[Tristram Risdon|Risdon]]\n|[[File:RisdonArms FieldArgent.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, three birdbolts sable''\n|Winscott, [[St Giles in the Wood]]; [[Bableigh, Parkham]]\n|-\n|Roache\n|[[File:RoacheArms.png|70px]]\n|''Azure, three [[Common roach|roaches]] naiant in pale argent''\n|[[Welcombe]]<ref>[[Welcombe]] is a parish near [[Hartland, Devon|Hartland]] in North Devon, near the Cornish border. Other estates named \"Welcombe\" are listed in Pole, which may have been the residence of this family, with a very brief pedigree in Vivian, p.651 with no mention of parish. However, mention is made of [[Week St Mary]] (in Cornwall), 13 miles south of Welcombe near Hartland, and the Roache family originated in \"Lesawnte\" ([[Lezant]]?, Cornwall. Lysons, Magna Britannia, Cornwall, Extinct Gentry, states: \"Roche or De la Rupe of Roche \u2014 traced to the reign of Richard I. Hals says, that this family became extinct, in the male line, in 1357; that Sir William Blundell, husband of the heiress, took the name of Roche, which continued till the reign of Henry VIII., when the last of the family left four daughters, three of whom married Fortescue, Penkevil, and Boscawen. The Roches had married heiresses of Trevelyan and Page, and a coheiress of Durant. Arms of Roche: \u2014 Sab. three roaches, two, one, nayant, Argent.\" The Devon family used a crescent as the [[Difference (heraldry)|difference]] of a second son. The name was thus [[List of Latinized names|Latinized]] to ''de (la) Rupe'' (Lat: rupes-is, \"rock\") \"from the rock\", inspired by the French word ''la roche, le rocher'', \"rock\", from degraded Latin ''rocca'', recorded in use 980 AD (Larousse Lexis, Paris, 1979, p.1654) from which the English word \"rock\" (Collins Dict)</ref>\n|-\n|[[Baron Rolle|Rolle]]\n|[[File:RolleArms.png|70px]]\n|''Or, on a fesse dancette between three billets azure each charged with a lion rampant of the first three bezants''\n|[[Stevenstone]], [[St Giles in the Wood]]; [[Bicton, Devon|Bicton]]; [[Hudscott]], [[Chittlehampton]]; [[Beam, Great Torrington]]; [[Heanton Satchville, Petrockstowe]]; Buckfast Place, [[Exeter Cathedral|Cathedral Close]], [[St Martin's Church, Exeter|St Martin's]], Exeter<ref>[[Townhouse (Great Britain)|townhouse]] of [[George Rolle]] (d.1552), where he died, comprising \"messuage, garden and curtilage\". It was [[Feudal land tenure in England|held]] from the crown in [[burgage]], worth 30 shillings. Details of Buckfast Place from his [[inquisition post mortem]] quoted in Byrne, Muriel St. Clare, (ed.) The Lisle Letters, 6 vols, University of Chicago Press, Chicago & London, 1981, vol.1, Appendix 25, p.414. This house, later known as the \"Abbot's Lodge\", was destroyed in 1942 during [[World War II]] bombing. It had been the townhouse of the Abbot of [[Buckfast Abbey]], which Abbey and much of its lands, apparently excluding the Abbot's Lodge, had been acquired following the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries]] by Sir [[Thomas Denys]] (c.1477-1561) of [[Holcombe Burnell]], whose eventual heir (by coincidence) was the Rolle family. It was at the Abbot's Lodge that the Grand Duke of Tuscany was entertained by Sir John Rolle in 1669 and it remained in the Rolle family until 1737 when it was sold to the Rev. John Heskett.(Source:[http://demolition-exeter.blogspot.co.uk/2010/09/town-house-of-abbots-of-buckfast.html]) A photograph of the arms of Sir Henry Rolle (1545-1625) in this building taken shortly before its destruction survives in: ''Devon Notes & Queries, Vol.9, 1916-17, pp.97-9: \"Armorial Bearings at the Abbot's Lodge\", The Close, Exeter''. Image see: [[:File:SirHenryRolle (1545-1625) 1602Arms AbbotsLodge CathedralClose Exeter.jpg]]</ref>\n|-\n|Roope\n|[[File:Roope OfEastAllington Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a lion rampant per fess gules and vert between seven pheons azure''\n|Horswell, [[South Milton]]; [[East Allington]]; Bidwell, [[Newton St Cyres]]<ref>Vivian, p.517, inherited from Roope by Kirkham</ref>\n|-\n|Roope<ref>Monuments to the Roope family of Townstal exist in St Clement's Church, Dartmouth and in St Petrox's Church, Dartmouth (Pevsner, pp.324,322)</ref>\n|[[File:RoopeArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a lion rampant gules an orle of nine pheons azure''\n|[[Townstal]] \n|-\n|Rowcliffe\n|[[File:RowcliffeArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, on a chevron between three lion's heads erased gules a chess-rook or''\n|[[Yarnscombe]]\n|-\n|[[Nicholas Rowe (writer)|Rowe]]\n|[[File:Rowe (OfLamerton) Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, three paschal lambs or staff cross and banners argent''\n|[[Lamerton]]\n|-\n|Rowe\n|[[File:Rowe (of Kingston, Staverton) arms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, on a chevron azure between three trefoils slipped per pale gules and vert three bezants''\n|[[Kingston, Staverton]]; Bearton, [[Manor of Broad Hempston|Broad Hempston]]<ref>[[Daniel Lysons (antiquarian)|Lysons, Daniel]] & [[Samuel Lysons|Lysons, Samuel]], Magna Britannia, Vol.6, ''Devonshire'', London, 1822 [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/magna-britannia/vol6/pp250-272]</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===S===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Escutcheon !! Blazon !! Seat, parish\n|-\n|[[Peter Sainthill|Sainthill]]\n|[[File:SainthillArms.png|70px]]\n|''Or, on a fess engrailed azure between three leopard's faces gules three bezants each charged with a fleur-de-lys of the second on a pile in chief of the second three demi-fleurs-de-lys attached to the top and sides of the first''\n|[[Bradninch]]\n|-\n|Salisbury\n|[[File:Salisbury (of Barnstaple) Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, a lion rampant crowned or between three crescents argent''\n|Barnstaple\n|-\n|Sanford\n|[[File:SanfordArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chevron between three martlets sable''\n|Exeter\n|-\n|Savery\n|[[File:SaveryArms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, a fess vair between three unicorn's heads couped or''\n|[[Shilston, Modbury]]; Willing, [[Rattery]]; [[Slade, Cornwood|Slade]], [[Cornwood]]\n|-\n|Searle\n|[[File:SearleArms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, on a chevron between three trefoils argent as many pellets''\n|\"''Gotford in the parish of Holford in the hundred of Hemiock''\";<ref>No such parish as \"Holford\" appears to exist. This seat (called ''Goddeford'' by Pole, p.201 and ''Godeford'' by Risdon, p.41) is possibly one of two places: Gosford (today Gosford Farm) near the hamlet of Taleford, about 2 miles SE of Awliscombe; Godford, about 1/4 mile NW of Awliscombe. Awliscombe was in the [[Hundred of Hemyock]]</ref> [[Awliscombe]]\n|-\n|Seccombe ''alias'' Thorne<ref>These are the arms of Thorne of Thorne in the parish of Holsworthy, Devon, with difference of a bordure engrailed, with additional difference of a crescent for a second son. The family was descended from Degorie Thorne (second son of John Thorne of Thorne) who (circa 15th c.) married Margaret Seccombe, daughter and heiress of Thomas Seccombe of Seccombe, Devon</ref>\n|[[File:Seccombe aliasThorne Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a fess gules between three lions rampant sable a bordure engrailed of the last a crescent for difference''\n|Weston, [[North Petherwin]]; Webworthy, [[North Petherwin]] \n|-\n|Segar\n|[[File:SegarArms.png|70px]]\n|''Azure, a cross moline argent''\n|[[Highweek]], [[Kingsteignton]]\n|-\n|Servington\n|[[File:ServingtonArms.png|70px]]\n|''Ermine, on a chief azure three buck's heads cabossed or''\n|[[Tavistock]]; ([[Longford Castle|Longford]], Wiltshire)\n|-\n|Seward\n|[[File:SewardArms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, on a fess or between two chevrons ermine three leopard's faces azure''\n|[[Stoke-in-Teignhead]]\n|-\n|[[Sir Edward Seymour, 1st Baronet|Seymour]]\n|[[File:COA of Seymour.svg|70px]]\n|''Gules, two wings conjoined in lure or''\n|[[Berry Pomeroy]]; [[Stover, Teigngrace]];\n|-\n|Shapcott\n|[[File:ShapcottArms MollandChurch Devon.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, (a chevron or<ref>As depicted in stained glass in east window of Shute Church, Devon, impaled by arms of Pole of Shute, representing the marriage of Sir Courtenay Pole, 2nd Baronet (1619-1695) and Urith Shapcott, daughter of Thomas Shapcott of Shapcott in the parish of Knowstone, Devon. Elsewhere the arms are shown with a chevron ''or'' (Barnstaple Church on Tucker monument), or without chevron (in Knowstone Church and in Molland Church). (Pole {{harv|Vivian|1895|pp=603}}, Shapcott {{harv|Vivian|1895|pp=677}}, blazoned with chevron or)</ref> between) three dovecotes argent''\n|Shapcott, [[Knowstone]]\n|-\n|Shapleigh<ref>John Shapleigh (d.1628) of Totnes was Mayor of Dartmouth and twice Mayor of Totnes. His monument is in St Saviour's Church, Dartmouth (Vivian, p.678, \"MI\"). No connection is known to [[John Shapleigh (died 1414)]] of Exeter, MP, father of [[John Shapleigh (fl. 1414\u20131427)]], of Exeter, MP</ref>\n|[[File:ShapleighArms.png|70px]]\n|''Vert, a chevron argent betyeen three escallops or''\n|[[Totnes]]; [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]]\n|-\n|Sharpe<ref>William Sharpe (fl.1620) of Tiverton (3rd son of Robert Sharpe, a merchant in the City of London, by his wife Jeliane Mallory, eldest daughter and co-heiress of Sir Richard Mallory, [[Lord Mayor of London]] in 1564) married Alice Woolton, a daughter of [[John Woolton]], [[Bishop of Exeter]]. (Vivian, p.679)</ref>\n|[[File:SharpeArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, three falcon's heads erased sable a bordure engrailed azure''\n|[[Tiverton, Devon|Tiverton]]\n|-\n|Sherman\n|[[File:ShermanArms.svg|70px]]\n|''Or, a lion rampant sable between three holly leaves vert''\n|[[Knightstone, Ottery St Mary|Knightstone]],<ref>Risdon, p.46; [[Nikolaus Pevsner|Pevsner, Nikolaus]] & Cherry, Bridget, The Buildings of England: Devon, London, 2004, p.529; Vivian, p.680; [[William Henry Hamilton Rogers|Rogers, William Henry Hamilton]], ''The Dorset chapel and Knightstone; Bonville and Sherman; Ottery St. Mary'', Notes and Queries for Somerset anmd Dorset, Vol.7, 1901, pp.187-91,235-43,322. Reprinted in his ''Archaeological Papers Relating to the Counties of Somerset, Wilts, Hants and Devon'', 1902</ref> [[Ottery St Mary]]\n|-\n|Shorte\n|[[File:ShorteArms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, a griffin segreant or a chief ermine''\n|[[Newton St Cyres]]\n|-\n|Simonds\n|[[File:SimondsArms.png|70px]]\n|''Per fess dancet\u00e9e gules and argent, a pale counterchanged three trefoils one and two slipped of the first''\n|Exeter\n|-\n|Skerrit\n|[[File:SkerritArms.png|70px]]\n|''Or, a chief indented sable''\n|[[Whitchurch, Devon|Whitchurch]]\n|-\n|Skinner\n|[[File:SkinnerArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chief azure sem\u00e9e-de-lys of the first''\n|[[Cowley, Devon|Cowley]]\n|-\n|Slader\n|[[File:SladerArms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, a chevron ermine between three horse's heads erased argent''\n|Bath, [[North Tawton]]\n|-\n|[[Nicholas Slanning|Slanning]]\n|[[File:SlanningArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, two pales engrailed gules over all on a bend azure three griffin's heads or''\n|Ley, [[Plympton St Mary]];<ref>Ley in the parish of Plympton St Mary, per [[John Prince (biographer)|Prince, John]], (1643\u20131723) The Worthies of Devon, 1810 edition, London, pp.713, 715-6 (note 1)</ref> [[Bickleigh, South Hams|Bickleigh (South Hams)]]; [[Maristow]], [[Tamerton Foliot]]\n|-\n|Slowley\n|[[File:SlowleyArms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, a chevron between three bats displayed or ''\n|Sloley, [[Shirwell]]; [[Fremington, Devon|Fremington]]\n|-\n|[[George Smith (MP for Exeter)|Smith]] (of Exeter)\n|[[File:Smith OfExeter Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, a fess cotised between three [[martlet]]s or''<ref>[[William Pole (antiquary)|Pole, Sir William]] (d.1635), Collections Towards a Description of the County of Devon, Sir John-William de la Pole (ed.), London, 1791, p.502. As seen on 1714 mural monument to Sir [