xham|Lupton]], [[Brixham]]\n|}\n\n===V===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Escutcheon !! Blazon !! Seat, parish\n|-\n|Velly<ref>Arms as visible on monument (transcript Chope, R. Pearse, ''The Book of Hartland'', Torquay, 1940, p.144) in Hartland Church to John Velly (1617-1694), during the Civil War a Captain-Lieutenant to Sir Robert Cary (1610\u20131675), lord of the nearby [[manor of Clovelly]], a Gentleman of the Privy Chamber to King Charles II, whose mural monument survives in Clovelly Church</ref>\n|[[File:VellyArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chevron between three castles or''\n|Higher Velly, [[Hartland, Devon|Hartland]]; Galsham, [[Hartland, Devon|Hartland]];<ref>Seats per Chope, R.Pearse, The Book of Hartland, Torquay, 1940, pp.144, 198</ref>\n|-\n|Venner\n|[[File:VennerArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Gules, three bends or a chief per fess ermine and argent''<ref>Vivian, p.746</ref>\n|[[Hudscott]], [[Chittlehampton]]\n|-\n|Voysey\n|[[File:VoyseyArms.png|70px]]\n|''Or, a cross sable in the first quarter a crescent of the last a bordure gules''\n|[[Townstal]] ([[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]])\n|}\n\n===W===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Escutcheon !! Blazon !! Seat, parish\n|-\n|Waddon\n|[[File:WaddonArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a lion rampant gules debruised with a bend sable charged with three cross crosslets fitch\u00e9e of the field''\n|[[Plymouth]]\n|-\n|Wadham\n|[[File:WadhamArms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, a chevron between three roses argent''\n|[[Edge, Branscombe|Edge]], [[Branscombe, Devon|Branscombe]]; [[Wadham, Knowstone|Wadham]], [[Knowstone]]; ([[Merryfield, Ilton|Merryfield]], [[Ilton]]; Somerset)\n|-\n|Wakeman<ref>Arms granted in 1616 to Rev. Robert Wakeman (1576-1629), Doctor of Divinity, Parson of Beer Ferrers and Charleton in Devon, Fellow of Balliol College, Oxford in 1596, Prebendary of Exeter Cathedral 1616 (Wakeman, Robert, P., ''Wakeman Genealogy 1630-1899'', Meriden, Connecticut, 1900, p35 [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sdIGAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=waKEMAN+Flyford+Flavell&source=bl&ots=3I5IFZ45VT&sig=L1gLqxk9IUPsV11k1FtaFZm7sto&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwikqJeyjcbWAhUCM8AKHcFeBWAQ6AEIQzAF#v=onepage&q=waKEMAN%20Flyford%20Flavell&f=false])</ref>\n|[[File:Wakeman (OfBereFerrers) Arms.svg|70px]]\n|''Argent, on a cross sable a ducal coronet or encircled with clouds proper rayon\u00e9e or''\n|[[Bere Ferrers]]; [[Charleton]]\n|-\n|Wakeman\n|[[File:Wakeman OfExeter Arms.svg|70px]]\n|''Vert, a saltire wavy ermine''\n|Exeter\n|-\n|Walrond\n|[[File:WalrondArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, three bull's heads cabossed sable armed or''\n|[[Bradfield, Uffculme]]; Bovey House, [[Beer, Devon|Beer]]\n|-\n|Walter\n|[[File:Walter (of Ashbury) Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Azure, a griffin segreant or a bordure ermine''\n|[[Ashbury, Devon|Ashbury]]\n|-\n|Waltham<ref>Richard Waltham (1560-1632) of Trehill, was [[Recorder of Exeter]] 1628-32. His elder brother Jeffrie Waltham (1558-1626) of Exeter, was [[Mayor of Exeter]] in 1613 and 1626 and was married to Katherin Duck, a sister of [[Nicholas Duck]] (1570-1628), [[Recorder of Exeter]] (Vivian, pp.772;309); Their aunt Katherin Waltham was the mother of the Devon historian [[Thomas Westcote]] (c.1567-c.1637). (Vivian, pp.772;778)</ref>\n|[[File:WalthamArms.svg|70px]]\n|''Sable, a chevron between three suns in glory argent''\n|Trehill, [[Kenn, Devon|Kenn]]; Exeter\n|-\n|Waye\n|[[File:Waye (of Torrington) Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Gules, a chevron or between three lucies hauriant argent''\n|[[Great Torrington|Torrington]]; Marsh,<ref>Pole, p.506, who blazons the arms as ''Gules, a chevron between three fishes naiant argent'', thus with chevron ''argent'' not ''or'' and with the unnamed fish ''naiant'' not ''hauriant''. These arms of Waye of Marsh are however sculpted (without tinctures) quartered by Kirkham of Blagdon in the 16th century Kirkham Chantry of Paignton Church, and show a chevron with fish ''hauriant'', as per Vivian's blazon. Nicholas Kirkham (d.1516) of Blagdon married Jane Waye, daughter and heiress of Robert Waye of Marsh (Vivian, p.516, pedigree of Kirkham). These are similar to the arms displayed in Exeter Guildhall, Devon, of \"John Waye, Sheriff (of Exeter) 1541\", shown as ''Gules, three lucies hauriant in fess argent''. They should be distinguished from the completely different arms of Way of St Giles-in-the-Wood, near Great Torrington in Devon, often called \"de Via\" (i.e. literally \"from the way\") arms, apparently later adopted by the Pollard family of Way and also by the Davie family (Davy baronets) of Creedy, Devon, which claim their original surname as ''de Via''.</ref> [[Newton St Cyres]]<ref>Marsh in parish of Newton St Cyres per [[John Prince (biographer)|Prince, John]], (1643\u20131723) The Worthies of Devon, 1810 edition, London, p.554</ref>\n|-\n|Weare/Treawin<ref>Arms of \"Treawin of Weare Giffard\" per Pole, p.505; Arms of \"Weare of Clyst Honiton\" per Vivian, p.774. Quartered by Fortescue of Weare Giffard and Filleigh, see monumental brass in Filleigh Church of [[Richard Fortescue]] (c. 1517\u20131570)</ref>\n|[[File:WeareArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, on a bend vert between six crosses crosslet fitch\u00e9e gules three crosiers or''\n|[[Clyst Honiton]]\n|-\n|Webbe\n|[[File:WebbeArms.png|70px]]\n|''Or, a plain cross sable in the first quarter an eagle displayed of the second''\n|St Petrock, [[Exeter]]; St Mary Major, [[Exeter]]\n|-\n|Webber\n|[[File:WebberArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Gules, on a chevron engrailed argent between three [[Roundel|plates]] three annulets of the first''\n|[[Incledon, Braunton]]; [[Buckland, Braunton]]\n|-\n|[[Thomas Westcote|Westcott]]\n|[[File:WestcottArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a bend cotised sable a bordure gules bezant\u00e9e''\n|Raddon, [[Shobrooke]]\n|-\n|Weston\n|[[File:Weston OfColytonDevon Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, on a chevron sable three leopard's faces or''\n|Heath Hayne,<ref>[[William Henry Hamilton Rogers]], ''Memorials of the West, Historical and Descriptive, Collected on the Borderland of Somerset, Dorset and Devon'', Exeter, 1888, pp.226-7</ref> [[Colyton, Devon|Colyton]]\n|-\n|[[John Whiddon|Whiddon]]\n|[[File:WhiddonArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chevron between three spearheads gules''\n|[[Whiddon, Chagford]]; [[Sidbury]]\n|-\n|White\n|[[File:WhiteArms.svg|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chevron between three wolf's heads erased sable''\n|\"Diray\"\n|-\n|Whitlock\n|[[File:WhitlockArms.png|70px]]\n|''Per fess or and sable, a bend wavy between two padlocks counterchanged''\n|[[Warkleigh]]\n|-\n|Wichalse\n|[[File:WichalseArms.png|70px]]\n|''Per fess argent and sable, six crescents in pale counterchanged''\n|[[Barnstaple]]\n|-\n|Willesford\n|[[File:WillesfordArms.svg|70px]]\n|''Azure, a chevron ermine between three leopard's faces or''\n|[[Tavistock]]\n|-\n|[[Baron Willoughby de Eresby|Willoughby]]\n|[[File:Willoughby OfPayhembury Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Quarterly 1 & 4: Sable, a cross engrailed or'' (Ufford); 2 & 3: ''Gules, a cross moline argent (Bec of Eresby); all within a bordure gobon\u00e9e of the second and azure''\n|[[Manor of Molland|Molland Champson]], [[Manor of Molland|Molland Bottreaux]]; Leyhill,<ref>[[Todd Gray (Devon Historian)|Gray, Todd]], (ed.), ''Devon Household Accounts, 1627\u201359'', Devon and Cornwall Record Society, Part I, 1995, p.xxxvii ''The Willougby Family and the Accounts of Leyhill''</ref> [[Payhembury]]\n|-\n|Wise\n|[[File:WiseArms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable, three chevronels ermine''\n|[[Sydenham House, Devon|Sydenham]], [[Marystow]]; [[Mount Wise, Plymouth|Mount Wise]], [[Stoke Damerel]]\n|-\n|Withie<ref>John Withie of Berry Narbor married Joane Jewel, a sister of [[John Jewel]] (1522-1571), [[Bishop of Salisbury]], born at Bowden in the parish of Berry Narbor (Vivian, pp.814, 505)</ref>\n|[[File:WithieArms.svg|70px]]\n|''Per pale ermine and or, a lion salient gules''\n|[[Berry Narbor]]\n|-\n|Wolcot\n|[[File:WolcotArms.png|70px]]\n|''Per pale azure and gules, on a cross fleury or five martlets sable a chief of the third charged with a fleur-de-lys between two annulets of the second''\n|Wolcot, [[Thrushelton]]<ref>Vivian, p.793: ''Wolecot in parochia de Thrustelton''</ref>\n|-\n|Wollocombe (see also Woollcombe)\n|[[File:WollocombeArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, three bars gules''\n|[[Woolacombe|Wollocombe]], [[Mortehoe]]; Combe (''alias'' Over Wollocombe<ref>Pole, p.394</ref>), [[Roborough, Torridge|Roborough]]\n|-\n|Wood\n|[[File:Wood (OfOrchard Lew Trenchard Devon) Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Sable sem\u00e9e of cross-crosslets or, three leopard's faces of the last''\n|Orchard,<ref>Re Orchard, see: Pevsner, Nikolaus & Cherry, Bridget, The Buildings of England: Devon, London, 2004, pp.535,613, who places it in parish of Thrushelton (near Lew Trenchard). The Visitations are clear this family resided in the parish of Lew Trenchard, and various monuments of the family exist in that parish church (\"MI\" per Vivian, p.799).</ref> [[Lew Trenchard]]\n|-\n|[[Sir Matthew Wood, 1st Baronet|Woode]]\n|[[File:Woode (OfHarston) Arms.svg|70px]]\n|''Argent, on a mount in base proper an oak tree vert fructed or''\n|[[Hareston, Brixton|Hareston]], [[Brixton, Devon|Brixton]]\n|-\n|Woodley\n|[[File:WoodleyArms.svg|70px]]\n|''Sable, a chevron between three owls argent''\n|Halshanger, [[Ilsington]]\n|-\n|Woodrouffe<ref>James Woodrouffe (d.1609) of Barnstaple was [[Mayor of Barnstaple]] in 1605 (Vivian, p.802; Lamplugh, Lois, Barnstaple: Town on the Taw,  South Molton, 2002, p.156). His first wife was Jone Worth, a daughter of Pawle Worth, thrice Mayor of Barnstaple in 1577, 1592 and 1603, who signed a letted dated 8 April 1588 concerning the town's objection to having been ordered by the Privy Council to provide an excessive number of ships to meet the Spanish Armada. (Lamplugh, pp.50,156)</ref>\n|[[File:WoodrouffeArms.svg|70px]]\n|''Gules, on a chevron argent three buck's heads erased sable a chief per fess nebul\u00e9e of the third and second''\n|[[Barnstaple]]; [[Uffculme]]\n|-\n|Woollcombe (see also Wollocombe)\n||[[File:WollocombeArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, three bars gules''\n|Pitton, [[Yealmpton]]; [[Ashbury, Devon|Ashbury]]\n|-\n|Worth (Wrothe)\n|[[File:WorthArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Argent, an eagle with two heads displayed sable beaked and legged or''<ref>Blazon per Pole, p.509; These arms are visible on several escutcheons in Washfield Church. The arms are blazoned incorrectly as ''beaked and legged gules'' in Vivian, p.805, pedigree of Worth</ref>\n|Worth, [[Washfield]], near [[Tiverton, Devon|Tiverton]]; [[Calstock]], [[Cornwall]]\n|-\n|Wotton\n|[[File:Wotton OfInglebourne Devon Arms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a cross engrailed between four mullets sable''\n|Inglebourne,<ref>Following the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries]] during the reign of King Henry VIII (1509-1547) John Wotton purchased the estate of Inglebourne from the crown, previously a possession of Buckfastleigh Abbey (Risdon, p.165)</ref> [[Harberton]]\n|-\n|Wyatt<ref>Phillip Wyatt (d.1592) was steward and Town Clerk of Barnstaple, near Braunton. He had several sons, of whom Adam Wyatt (d.1611) was Town Clerk of Barnstaple from 1586 and left a detailed diary which provides valuable information on the town at this period. The identity of the diarist as Adam Wyatt was made by the Devon historian [[Todd Gray (historian)|Todd Gray]], although traditionally the diarist was thought to have been his brother Philip Wyatt (d.1608) (Lamplugh, Lois, ''Barnstaple: Town on the Taw'', South Molton, 2002, p.45). Their elder brother Hugh Wyatt of Shillingford, married Lady Mary Bourchier, a daughter of [[John Bourchier, 2nd Earl of Bath]] (1499-1561), of nearby Tawstock Court, a highly influential figure in Barnstaple. Another brother, Thomas Wyatt, married Margaret Risdon, an aunt of [[Tristram Risdon]] (d.1640) the Devon historian. (Vivian, pp.823, 107, 648). Pole, p.508, gives the arms of \"Wiatt of Shillingford\" slightly differently as: ''Azure, a chief gules over-all a horse-brake (barnacle) argent''</ref>\n|[[File:WyattArms.svg|70px]]\n|''Per pale gules and azure, a pair of barnacles argent''\n|[[Braunton]]\n|-\n|[[Roger Wyke|Wykes/Weekes]]\n|[[File:WykesArms.png|70px]]\n|''Ermine, three battle-axes sable''\n|[[North Wyke]], [[South Tawton]]; Bindon, [[Axminster]];<ref>The Bindon branch of Wyke used their maternal arms of Burnell, having inherited that estate from an heiress of that family (Pole, p.243; Woodger, L.S., biography of ''Wyke, Roger (d.c.1467), of Bindon in Axmouth, Devon'', published in ''[[History of Parliament]]: House of Commons 1386-1421, ed. J.S. Roskell, L. Clark, C. Rawcliffe., 1993 [http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1386-1421/member/wyke-roger-1467])</ref> [[Honeychurch]]\n|-\n|Wyvell\n|[[File:WyvellArms.svg|70px]]\n|''Argent, three mullets between two bars sable a bordure engrailed gules''<ref>Pole, Sir William (d.1635), Collections Towards a Description of the County of Devon, Sir John-William de la Pole (ed.), London, 1791, p.507</ref> \n|[[Crediton]]\n|}\n\n===Y===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Escutcheon !! Blazon !! Seat, parish\n|-\n|[[Edward Yarde|Yard]]\n|[[File:YardArms.png|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chevron gules between three water bougets sable''<ref>Arms inherited from the Bushel family of Bradley/Teignwick (Pole, p.472)</ref>\n|Yarde, [[Malborough]];<ref>[[Todd Gray (Devon Historian)|Gray, Todd]] & Rowe, Margery (Eds.), Travels in Georgian Devon: The Illustrated Journals of The Reverend [[John Swete]], 1789-1800, 4 vols., Tiverton, 1999, Vol 2, p.164; Pevsner, p.556</ref> [[Teignwick]], [[Kingsteignton]]; [[Bradley (house)|Bradley]], [[Kingsteignton]]; [[Whiteway, Kingsteignton]];<ref>Swete, Vol.2, p.164</ref> [[Churston Court]], [[Churston Ferrers]]; [[Sharpham, Ashprington]]\n|-\n|Yeo\n|[[File:YeoArms.PNG|70px]]\n|''Argent, a chevron sable between three [[Northern shoveler|shovelers]] azure''<ref>Per research conducted by Sheila Yeo of the Yeo Society [http://www.yeosociety.com/heraldry/yeo%20evidence.htm], based on stained glass depictions of Yeo arms in churches of Petrockstowe (Yeo of Heanton Satchville) and Hatherleigh (Yeo of Hatherleigh) both in Devon. The ducks are described as of various breeds by different sources. Heraldic sources give contradictory tinctures: ''Argent, a chevron between three shovelers sable'' (Vivian, Lt.Col. J.L., (Ed.) The Visitations of the County of Devon: Comprising the Heralds' Visitations of 1531, 1564 & 1620, Exeter, 1895, p.834) and ''Argent, a chevron between three mallards azure'' ([[William Pole (antiquary)|Pole, Sir William]] (d.1635), Collections Towards a Description of the County of Devon, Sir John-William de la Pole (ed.), London, 1791, p.510)</ref>\n|[[Heanton Satchville, Petrockstowe]]; [[Huish, Devon|Huish]]; [[Hatherleigh]]; [[Manor of Fremington|Fremington]]\n|-\n|[[Sir John Yonge, 1st Baronet|Yonge]]\n|[[File:YongeArms.png|70px]]\n|''Ermine, on a bend cotised sable three griffin's heads erased or''\n|[[Great House, Colyton|Great House]], [[Colyton, Devon|Colyton]]; [[Escot, Talaton|Escot]], [[Talaton]]; [[Mohuns Ottery]], [[Luppitt]]\n|-\n|Yonge<ref>The return made in 1620 to the heralds was signed by Robert Yonge (d.1636) of Colebrooke, 4th son of Thomas Younge of [[Sturminster Newton]] in Dorset. Robert's nephew was Thomas Yonge (of Child, Ockford) who married Bridget Seymer, a sister of Sir Robert Seymer (d.1624) of Hanford in Dorset, a Teller in the King's Exchequer, knighted at Greenwich Palace on 19 February 1619 (Burke, John, ''A Genealogical and Heraldic Dictionary of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain and Ireland'', Vol. 2 (M-Z), London, 1846, p.1216 [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FlI4AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1216&lpg=PA1216&dq=Seymour+Hanford+Dorset&source=bl&ots=UjT-Ig7fWb&sig=T6v5O5oxZ6p0GRP-vabwhSPmdDU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwig4JPPzarXAhXCNhoKHSaeBWY4ChDoAQhOMAg#v=onepage&q=Seymour%20Hanford%20Dorset&f=false])</ref>\n|[[File:Yonge (OfColebrooke) Arms.svg|70px]]\n|''Per fess sable and argent, three lions rampant guardant counterchanged''\n|Landsend,<ref>[http://forebears.co.uk/england/devon/colebrooke Kelly's Directory of Devon, 1902]</ref>[[Colebrooke, Devon|Colebrooke]]\n|}\n\n==Blazons by Sir William Pole==\nThe following blazons, with spellings corrected and modernised, but listed in original semi-alphabetical order, were recorded by Sir William Pole:<ref>[[William Pole (antiquary)|Pole, Sir William]] (d.1635), Collections Towards a Description of the County of Devon, Sir John-William de la Pole (ed.), London, 1791, pp.467-510</ref>\n{{Expand list|date=September 2014}}\n===A===\n*[[File:AbbottArms.png|25px]]Abbot, of [[Hartland, Devon|Hartland]]:''Sable,<ref>Field ''or'' per Pole, but ''sable'' per Vivian, p.1 and as seen in a stained glass window in Hartland Church, see [[:File:AbbottArms HartlandChurch Devon.xcf]]</ref> a cross voided between four eaglets displayed or''\n*[[File:AdestonArms.png|25px]]Adiston, of Adeston: ''Argent, a fess between three pellets''\n*[[File:AffetonArms.PNG|25px]]Affeton, of [[Manor of Affeton|Affeton]]: ''Argent, a chevron engrailed between three fleurs-de-lys sable''\n*[[File:AclandArms.svg|25px]]Acland, of [[Acland, Landkey|Acland]]: ''Barry argent and sable, two pales counterchanged a fess gules over all''\n*[[File:Arms AlabasterOfBicton Devon.svg|25px]]Alabaster, of [[Bicton, Devon|Bicton]]: ''Azure, three cross-bows bent or''\n*Alley, [[Bishop of Exeter]]: ''Azure, a pale engrailed between two lions rampant ermine crowned or''\n*Ameredith, of Pole: ''Argent, a lion rampant sable collared and chained gules''\n*Aller, of [[Aller, South Molton|Aller]]: ''Argent, three parrots vert 2 and 1 beaked and membered gules''\n*[[File:Shield of Arms of the Lord Arundell of Wardour.svg|25px]]Arundell, of Yewton: ''Sable, six swallows (martlets) argent 3,2,1''\n*Arundell of Hempston Arundell: ''Argent, six swallows sable, 3,2,1''\n*Ank of Anke: ''Gules, two bars three annulets in chief argent''\n*[[File:AyshfordArms.jpg|25px]]Ayshford of Ayshford, Burlescombe: ''Argent, three ash crops vert between two chevrons sable''\n*Ashlegh of Ashlegh: ''...a pheon...''\n*Ashton of Ashton: ''Vert, three bends argent''\n*Ashthorp of Sampford Peverell: ''...a bend...''\n*[[File:AmadasArms.png|25px]]Amidas/Amadas of Plymouth: ''Azure, a chevron argent between three acorn stalks and leaves or''<ref>''three oaken slips acorned proper '', Vivian, p.12</ref>\n*Appleton: ''Or a chevron sable between three apples vert''\n*Ashenden of Dartmouth: ''Argent, a lion rampant gules collared or''\n*Atcomb of Atcombe: ''Sable, three wings argent''\n*[[File:AtwillArms.png|25px]]Atwill of Exeter: ''Argent, a chevron sable a pile in point counterchanged''\n*Appeldor: ''Gules, a fess undee argent''\n*Atwill: ''Argent, a fess three piles in chief''\n*Atway: ''... on a chief three lion's heads erased over-all a bend''\n*[[File:ArchdekneArms.svg|25px]]Archdeacon/Archdekne of Haccombe: ''Argent, three chevrons sable''\n*[[File:AudleyArms GulesFrettyOr.svg|25px]]Audleigh of Tawstock, (feudal) baron of Barnstaple and Dartington: ''Gules fretty or''\n*Avenell of Shepewas (Sheepwash): ''Three spread-eaglets'' (''Three eagles displayed'')\n*Avenell of Loxbere: ''Argent, five fusils in fess sable between two barrulets gules''\n*Auncell: ''Ermine, a fess sable between a demi-lion in chief and three fusils in base 2 and 1 gules''\n*[[File:ArscottArms.PNG|25px]]Arscott of Dunsland: ''Ermine, on a chief azure two buck's heads cabossed or''\n*Atwill: ''Argent, three leopard's faces azure''\n*Atwood: ''Sable semee of acorns or, a lion rampant argent''\n\n===B===\n*Basset of [[Stevenstone]] and Beaupire: ''Argent, a chevron azure between three bugle horns sable''\n*Bathe or Bathon, of Colbrooke: ''Ermine, a bend gules''\n*Bastard of Efford: ''Or, a chevron azure''\n*Basset of Umberleigh: ''Barry und\u00e9e of six or and gules''\n*Batten of Dunsland: ''Argent, three battle axes erect azure''\n*Batten of Exeter: ''Argent, a chevron between three battle axes erect azure''\n*Bawceyn of 