{"title_page": "Political positions of Joe Biden", "text_new": "{{short description|Policies of US politician Joe Biden}}\n{{Joe Biden series}}\n\n[[Joe Biden]] served as the [[Vice President of the United States]] from 2009 to 2017 and in the [[United States Senate]] from 1973 until 2009. He made his [[Joe Biden 2008 presidential campaign|second run]] for [[President of the United States]] in the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 presidential election]] as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], later being announced as Democratic presidential nominee [[Barack Obama]]'s [[running mate]] on August 23, 2008 and elected Vice President on November 4, 2008. On April 25, 2019, Biden announced his [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|third run]] for President of the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/25/us/politics/joe-biden-2020-announcement.html|title=Joe Biden Announces 2020 Run for President, After Months of Hesitation|last=Burns|first=Alexander|date=2019-04-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-12|last2=Martin|first2=Jonathan|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nBiden announced support for a [[public health insurance option]] that would allow Americans to buy into Medicare.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/2020-candidate-joe-biden-backs-medicare-all-policy-you-all-should-have-choice-1409332|title=2020 CANDIDATE JOE BIDEN BACKS MEDICARE PUBLIC OPTION: 'YOU ALL SHOULD HAVE A CHOICE'|website=Newsweek News|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19|date=April 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.advisory.com/daily-briefing/2019/04/30/biden-public-option | title=Biden just weighed in on 'Medicare for All'}}</ref>\n\nBiden has supported [[Campaign finance reform in the United States|campaign finance reform]] including the McCain-Feingold [[Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act]] and banning contributions of issue ads and gifts;<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden on Government Reform|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/joe_biden.htm#Government_Reform|work=Joe Biden on the Issues|publisher=OnTheIssues.org|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> the 1994 [[Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden on Crime|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/joe_biden.htm#Crime|work=Joe Biden on the Issues|publisher=OnTheIssues.org|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]];<ref>{{cite news|last=Biden|first=Joe|title=Assessing the Recovery Act: 'The best is yet to come'|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/op-ed-vice-president-joe-biden-todays-usa-today|accessdate=5 April 2013|newspaper=USA Today|date=February 17, 2010}}</ref><ref name=pbs27jan11>{{cite news|last=Biden|first=Joe|title=Biden: Mubarak Is Not a Dictator, But People Have a Right to Protest|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/politics/jan-june11/biden_01-27.html|accessdate=5 April 2013|newspaper=PBS Newshour|date=January 27, 2011}}</ref> [[tax credit]]s for students;<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden on Education|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/joe_biden.htm#Education|work=Joe Biden on the Issues|publisher=OnTheIssues.org|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> [[Carbon emission trading|carbon emissions cap and trade]];<ref name=energyandoil>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden on Energy & Oil Reform|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/joe_biden.htm#Energy_+_Oil|work=Joe Biden on the Issues|publisher=OnTheIssues.org|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> the increased [[infrastructure]] spending proposed by the Obama administration;<ref name=pbs27jan11/> [[Public transport|mass transit]], supporting [[Amtrak]], bus, and subway subsidies for decades;<ref>{{cite news|last=Hockenberry|first=John|title=Vice President Joe Biden pushes mass transit spending|url=http://www.thetakeaway.org/2009/apr/23/amtrak-joes-new-portfolio/|accessdate=5 April 2013|newspaper=The TakeAway|date=April 23, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130719151247/http://www.thetakeaway.org/2009/apr/23/amtrak-joes-new-portfolio/|archivedate=July 19, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[renewable energy]] subsidies;<ref name=energyandoil/> [[Public Service Loan Forgiveness (PSLF)|student loan forgiveness]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Ensuring That Student Loans are Affordable|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/issues/education/higher-education/ensuring-that-student-loans-are-affordable|work=Issue Fact Sheet|publisher=The White House|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref>{{dead link|date=April 2020}} increased [[progressive tax|taxation of the wealthy]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden on Tax Reform|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/joe_biden.htm#Tax_Reform|work=Joe Biden on the Issues|publisher=OnTheIssues.org|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> and expanding upon the Affordable Care Act, rather than establishing a Medicare for All system. He supports [[Decriminalization of non-medical cannabis in the United States|decriminalizing cannabis]] on a Federal level and supports a state's right to [[Legalization of cannabis|legalize]] it on a state level,<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden supports decriminalizing marijuana, stops short of calling for legalization|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/16/politics/joe-biden-marijuana-decriminalization/index.html|publisher=cnn.com|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref> and prefers the reduced military spending proposed in the Obama administration's fiscal year 2014 budget.<ref>{{cite web|last=Biden|first=Joe|title=Statement by Vice President Biden On the Bipartisan Debt Talks|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2011/06/23/statement-vice-president-biden-bipartisan-debt-talks|work=Press Release|publisher=The White House|accessdate=6 April 2013|date=June 23, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hellman|first=Chris|title=Competing Visions: President Obama, Rep. Paul Ryan, Sen. Patty Murray, and House Progressives Release Budget Proposals for 2014|url=http://nationalpriorities.org/en/analysis/2013/budget-proposals-2014/|publisher=National Priorities Project|accessdate=3 June 2013|author2=Mattea Kramer|date=April 10, 2013}}</ref> Biden has been publicly in favor of legalizing same-sex marriage since 2012 when he preempted Obama on the subject,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/henrygomez/joe-biden-gay-marriage-equality|title=Marriage Equality Is Joe Biden\u2019s Legacy. He Had To Evolve To Get There.|work=BuzzFeed News|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en}}</ref> and also supports [[abortion rights]], stating that ''[[Roe v. Wade]]'' is the \"law of the land\".<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/10/29/joe-biden-denied-communion/2494025001/|title=Catholic priest says he denied Joe Biden Holy Communion at Mass in South Carolina because of abortion views|author=William Cummings|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=October 19, 2019|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Lifetime ratings==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable floatcenter\"\n|+ Joe Biden's lifetime ratings<ref name=\"Joe Biden, Jr.'s Ratings and Endorsements\">{{Cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Vote Smart}}</ref><ref>[{{cite web|url=http://scorecard.lcv.org/sites/scorecard.lcv.org/files/LCV_Scorecard_2008.pdf |title=LCV Scorecard 2008]}}</ref><ref>[{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2008/08/obama-veep-wa-1/ |title=Obama VP Pick Joe Biden: Good on Civil Liberties, Friendly to Hollywood]|first=Sarah Lai|last=Stirland|date=August 23, 2008|via=wired.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://acuratings.conservative.org/acu-federal-legislative-ratings/?year1=2008&chamber=13&state1=21&sortable=1 |title=ACU Ratings|website=ACU Ratings| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708151908/http://acuratings.conservative.org/acu-federal-legislative-ratings/?year1=2008&chamber=13&state1=21&sortable=1 |archive-date=July 8, 2019 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n! Date\n! Organization\n! Advocacy\n! Lifetime rating\n|-\n| 2008 || [[Alliance for Retired Americans]] || Retirees || 96%\n|-\n| 2008 || [[American Civil Liberties Union]] || [[Civil liberties]] || 86%\n|-\n| 1995 ||[[American Conservative Union]]||[[Conservatism]]|| 13%\n|-\n| 2008 || American Conservative Union ||Conservatism|| 12.67%\n|-\n| 2008-2009 || [[American Federation of Labor and Congress of Industrial Organizations]] || [[Industrial unionism|Unionism]] || 86%\n|-\n| 2008 || [[American Federation of State, County & Municipal Employees]] || [[Public-sector trade union]]s || 86%\n|-\n| 1988-2008 || [[Brady Campaign to Prevent Gun Violence]] || Gun violence prevention || 96%\n|-\n| 2008 || [[Council for Citizens Against Government Waste]] || [[Fiscal conservatism]] || 22%\n|-\n| 2001-2002 || [[Information Technology Industry Council]] || [[Information and communications technology]] || 73%\n|-\n| 2008 || [[League of Conservation Voters]] || [[Environmentalism]] || 83%\n|-\n| 1989-2013 || [[NumbersUSA]] || [[Anti-immigration]] || 21%\n|-\n| 1993-2014 || [[The Lugar Center]] || [[Government operations]] || 58%\n|-\n| 2008 || [[United States Chamber of Commerce]] || [[Business]] || 36%\n|-\n|2002\n|[[National Rifle Association]]\n|[[Gun Rights|Gun rights]]\n|8%<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Vote Smart|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n|-\n|2020\n|National Rifle Association\n|Gun rights\n|D-<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/major-gun-safety-group-endorses-joe-bidens-presidential-69479272|title=Major gun safety groups endorse Joe Biden's presidential bid|last=Jaffe|first=Alexandra|date=March 9, 2020|website=ABC News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Social issues==\n===Affirmative action===\nBiden has supported [[Affirmative action in the United States|affirmative action]] policies.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/18/us/politics/18biden.html Biden\u2019s Record on Race Is Scuffed by 3 Episodes]</ref>\n\n===Capital punishment===\nSince June 20, 2019, Biden opposes capital punishment. Biden supports legislation to eliminate the capital punishment at the federal level, and incentivize states to abolish capital punishment. He supports individuals on death row instead serving life sentences without probation or parole.<ref>[https://joebiden.com/Justice/ Justice]</ref><ref>[https://www.politico.com/story/2019/06/20/joe-biden-death-penalty-1371932 Biden appears to be softening his stance on the death penalty]</ref> Prior to July 20, 2019, he had supported capital punishment. He originally wrote the [[Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act of 1994]]. The Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act of 1994 included Title VI, the Federal Death Penalty Act, creating 60 new death penalty offenses under 41 federal capital statutes,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Federal Death Penalty Act of 1994|url=http://www.justice.gov/usao/eousa/foia_reading_room/usam/title9/crm00069.htm|work=Office of the United States Attorneys|publisher=Department of Justice|accessdate=17 May 2013}}</ref> for crimes related to acts of [[terrorism]], [[murder]] of a federal law enforcement officer, [[civil rights]]-related murders, [[drive-by shooting]]s resulting in death, the use of [[weapons of mass destruction]] resulting in death, and [[carjacking]]s resulting in death. However, he voted against limiting appeals in capital cases and also opposed rejecting racial statistics in death penalty appeals.\n\n===Crime===\nBiden wrote the [[Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act]], which deployed more police officers, increased prison sentences, and built more prisons.  The bill created a financial incentive for jailing people and keeping them there for longer periods of time which had a disproportionate impact on minorities.<ref name=usatoday09302015 />\n\n===Drugs===\nBiden earned a reputation for being a \"drug warrior\", leading efforts in the [[war on drugs]].<ref name=\"RollingStoneDrugs\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-features/joe-biden-weed-war-drugs-candidate-2020-827319/|title=Why Weed Advocates Aren't Happy About Joe Biden's Candidacy|last=Dickson|first=E. J.|date=2019-04-25|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref> During the 1980s [[Crack epidemic in the United States|crack epidemic]] when both Democrats and Republicans were \"tough on crime\", Biden was the head of the [[Senate Judiciary Committee]] that passed numerous punitive measures against drug offenders. In 1986, Biden sponsored and co-wrote the [[Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986|Anti-Drug Abuse Act]] which caused a large disparity between the sentencing of [[crack cocaine]] and [[Cocaine|powder cocaine]] users. Black drug users were more likely than whites to use crack and hence were incarcerated in larger numbers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/4/25/18282870/joe-biden-criminal-justice-war-on-drugs-mass-incarceration|title=Joe Biden didn't just support the war on drugs. He wrote much of the legislation behind it.|last=Lopez|first=German|date=2019-04-25|website=Vox|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/99th-congress/senate-bill/2878|title=S.2878 - 99th Congress (1985-1986): Anti Drug Abuse Act of 1986|last=Dole|first=Robert J.|date=1986-10-17|website=[[congress.gov]]|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref> In 1982, he advocated for the creation of a [[drug czar]], a government official overseeing all anti-drug operations. This led to the establishment of the [[Office of National Drug Control Policy]] by the [[Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988]].<ref name=\"RollingStoneDrugs\"/>\n\nBiden favored increased funding for anti-drug efforts. He frequently criticized President Reagan in this regard,<ref name=\"incarceration\">{{cite news |last1=Stein |first1=David |title=The Untold Story: Joe Biden Pushed Ronald Reagan To Ramp Up Incarceration \u2014 Not The Other Way Around |url=https://theintercept.com/2019/09/17/the-untold-story-joe-biden-pushed-ronald-reagan-to-ramp-up-incarceration-not-the-other-way-around/ |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |work=The Intercept |date=September 17, 2019}}</ref> stating in 1982 that the administration's \"commitment is minuscule in terms of dollars\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Maitland |first1=Leslie |title=U.S. Plans A New Drive On Narcotics |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/10/09/us/us-plans-a-new-drive-on-narcotics.html |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=October 9, 1982}}</ref> He also criticized President George H. W. Bush's anti-drug strategy as \"not tough enough, bold enough or imaginative enough\",<ref name=\"marijuana\">{{cite news |last1=Jaeger |first1=Kyle |title=Where Presidential Candidate Joe Biden Stands On Marijuana |url=https://www.marijuanamoment.net/where-presidential-candidate-joe-biden-stands-on-marijuana/ |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |work=Marijuana Moment |date=April 25, 2019}}</ref> stating that \"what we need is another D-Day, not another Vietnam, not a limited war, fought on the cheap\".<ref name=\"incarceration\" />\n\nBiden advocated for increased use of [[Civil forfeiture in the United States|civil asset forfeiture]] by law enforcement agencies.<ref name=\"marijuana\" /> Biden played a key part in the passage of the Comprehensive Forfeiture Act in 1983, partnering with [[Strom Thurmond]], a conservative Republican. A ''Washington Post'' article described Biden's role in the negotiations: \"He got the Democrats to agree to strengthen forfeiture laws and allow judges to hold more defendants without bail; he persuaded the Republicans to drop such controversial provisions as a federal death penalty, and he made sure Thurmond got most of the credit. Civil liberties groups said the measure could have been far worse without Biden.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=[[Howard Kurtz]]|title=Sen Biden May Try to Talk His Way Into the White House|date=July 28, 1986|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1986/07/28/sen-biden-may-try-to-talk-his-way-into-the-white-house/a19e4497-0d36-4536-95b7-abb38cc17888/|newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Biden supported increased penalties against those caught selling drugs within 1,000&nbsp;feet of schools.<ref name=\"OTI2008\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/2008/Joe_Biden_Drugs.htm|title=Joe Biden on Drugs|website=ontheissues.org|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref> \n\nIn the early 2000s, Biden was critical of [[rave]]s, describing most of them as \"havens\" for use of [[MDMA|ecstasy]] and other illegal drugs.<ref name=Montgomery>David Montgomery, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/2002/07/18/ravers-against-the-machine/d5f8d828-ce3c-471f-a06a-26055a1a8ada/ Ravers Against the Machine], ''Washington Post'' (July 18, 2002).</ref> He was the sponsor of the bipartisan [[Reducing Americans' Vulnerability to Ecstasy Act|Reducing Americans' Vulnerability to Ecstasy (RAVE) Act]] in 2002; the bill's successor, the [[Illicit Drug Anti-Proliferation Act]], was later enacted as part of a [[PROTECT Act|broader 2003 crime bill]] that became law.<ref name=Montgomery/><ref name=Anderson2003>Nick Anderson, [https://web.archive.org/web/20200416045136/https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2003-apr-17-na-rave17-story.html Rave Crackdown Targets Drugs, Not Music, Biden Says], ''Los Angeles Times'' (April 17, 2003).</ref> The legislation, an expansion of the existing 1986 federal anti-\"[[crack house]]\" statute, provided for civil and criminal penalties for event promoters and property owners/managers who [[knowingly]] allowed their property to be used for sale or consumption of drugs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lopez |first1=German |title=How the war on drugs made raves more dangerous |url=https://www.vox.com/2014/10/3/6880715/RAVE-Act-joe-biden-molly-mdma-ecstasy-party-drugs-risks |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |work=Vox |date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> The legislation was opposed by the [[American Civil Liberties Union|ACLU]] and [[electronic dance music]] enthusiasts who viewed it as overly broad.<ref name=Anderson2003/><ref>[https://www.foxnews.com/story/anti-drug-provision-in-amber-alert-concerns-some-businesses Associated Press: Anti-Drug Provision in Amber Alert Concerns Some Businesses], Associated Press (April 30, 2003).</ref>  Responding to criticism, Biden said that the statute would not target law-abiding promoters, saying on the Senate floor: \"The reason I introduced this bill was not to ban dancing, kill 'the rave scene' or silence electronic music&mdash;all things of which I have been accused. In no way is this bill aimed at stifling any type of music or expression. It is only trying to deter illicit drug use and protect kids.\"<ref name=Anderson2003/> Although the law has been rarely used, advocates such as [[Drug Policy Alliance]] and [[DanceSafe]] argue that it discourages event producers from engaging in [[harm reduction]] efforts, and have sought to clarify the law.<ref>[https://www.drugpolicy.org/blog/vice-president-biden-fix-your-rave-act-law-and-save-lives Vice President Biden: Fix Your RAVE Act Law and Save Lives], Drug Policy Alliance (June 14, 2016).</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2008 Democratic Party presidential debates and forums|2007 Democratic primary]] debate at [[Howard University]], Biden acknowledged the consequences of the drug laws he authored and supported in the 1980s. He said there is a need to close the disparity in punishment between crack and powder cocaine users and a \"diversion out of the [[American prison system|prison system]]\" and into treatment.<ref name=\"OTI2008\"/> In 2010, Biden supported the [[Fair Sentencing Act]] which aimed to reduce the disparity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/111th-congress/senate-bill/1789|title=S.1789 - 111th Congress (2009-2010): Fair Sentencing Act of 2010|last=Durbin|first=Richard J.|date=2010-08-03|website=congress.gov|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref>\n\nBiden has a history of opposing [[Legality of cannabis|marijuana legalization]]. As a young senator in 1974 he opposed legalization in contrast to his other more liberal views.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/1974/06/01/joe-biden-kitty-kelley-1974-profile-death-and-the-all-american-boy/|title=Death and the All-American Boy {{!}} Washingtonian (DC)|date=1974-06-01|website=Washingtonian|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref> In 2010 he maintained this position, stating: \"I still believe it's a [[Gateway drug effect|gateway drug]]. I've spent a lot of my life as chairman of the Judiciary Committee dealing with this. I think it would be a mistake to legalize.\"<ref name=\"marijuana\" /> In a 2014 interview, Biden said \"I think the idea of focusing significant resources on interdicting or convicting people for smoking marijuana is a waste of our resources\" but said \"Our policy for our Administration is still not legalization.\"<ref>{{Cite web|author=Zeke J. Miller|url=https://time.com/5330/marijuana-legalization-joe-biden-pot/|title=Vice President Joe Biden Not High on Marijuana Legalization|website=Time|date=February 6, 2014}}</ref> In 2019 a spokesperson for the Biden campaign stopped short of endorsing federal legalization, but said that Biden supports decriminalizing cannabis, expunging prior criminal convictions, allowing states to legalize without federal interference, and [[Removal of cannabis from Schedule I of the Controlled Substances Act|reclassifying cannabis as a Schedule II drug]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Saenz |first1=Arlette |title=Joe Biden supports decriminalizing marijuana, stops short of calling for legalization |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/16/politics/joe-biden-marijuana-decriminalization/index.html |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |work=CNN |date=May 16, 2019}}</ref> On February 6, 2020, Biden's campaign stated his position hasn't changed, and that while Biden would support reclassification, he still would not support lifting the federal ban on marijuana.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/06/joe-biden-legalize-marijuana-111642|title=oe Biden kinda, sorta, almost endorses legalizing marijuana|publisher=Politico|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs Vice President, Biden actively engaged with Central American leaders on issues of drug cartels, drug trafficking, and migration to the U.S. caused by insecurity and drug violence. (See [[Political positions of Joe Biden#Central America|Central America]] below.)\n\n===Education===\nBiden was a major author of the [[Gun-Free School Zones Act of 1990]]<ref name=EdWeek>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.edweek.org/edweek/campaign-k-12/2019/05/Biden-Education-Plan-Title-!.html|newspaper=Education Week|title=Joe Biden's Education Plan: Triple Title I to Boost Teacher Pay and Student Supports|author=Evie Blad|date=May 28, 2019}}</ref> and voted in favor of the [[Improving America's Schools Act of 1994]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/103rd-congress/house-bill/6/all-actions|publisher=Congress.gov|title=H.R.6 - Improving America's Schools Act of 1994, 103rd Congress (1993-1994)}}</ref> He voted in favor of the 2001 [[No Child Left Behind Act]], but in 2007 called for the legislation to be scrapped or overhauled.<ref name=2007Transcript>{{cite news|title=Part I: CNN/YouTube Democratic presidential debate transcript |url=https://www.cnn.com/2007/POLITICS/07/23/debate.transcript/index.html|publisher=CNN |date=July 24, 2007}}</ref> He supports [[class size]] reductions and investment in [[early childhood education]].<ref name=2007Transcript/> During his 2020 presidential campaign, Biden has proposed tripling [[Elementary and Secondary Education Act#Title I|Title I]] funds (which go to low-income schools) to pay for increases in student supports and teacher salaries; doubling the number of school [[School counselor|guidance counselors]], [[school psychologists|psychologists]], [[school social worker|social workers]], and [[school nurses|nurses]]; providing for [[universal prekindergarten]], and fully funding the [[Individuals with Disabilities Education Act]] within a decade.<ref name=EdWeek/> Biden also supports federal infrastructure legislation providing funding for school buildings; allowing high school students to use [[Pell Grant]]s for [[dual enrollment]]; and expanding [[career education|career]] and [[technical education]] through school/[[community college]]/employer partnerships.<ref name=EdWeek/> Biden opposes federal funding for [[for-profit school|for-profit]] [[Charter schools in the United States|charter schools]].<ref name=Glueck/> Biden's plans have been praised by the [[National Education Association]] and [[American Federation of Teachers]],<ref name=Glueck>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden Debuts Education Plan, Then Touts It to Teachers' Union|author=Katie Glueck|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/28/us/politics/biden-education-plan-2020.html|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 28, 2019}}</ref> the major U.S. teachers' unions, which both endorsed Biden in 2020.<ref name=StraussAFT>{{cite web|author=Valerie Strauss|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2020/03/22/aft-countrys-second-largest-teachers-union-endorses-biden-democratic-presidential-nominee/|title=AFT, country's second-largest teachers union, endorses Biden as Democratic presidential nominee|date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=StraussNEA>{{cite web|author=Valerie Strauss|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2020/03/15/national-education-association-nations-largest-union-endorses-joe-biden-president/|newspaper=Washington Post|date=March 15, 2020|title=National Education Association, nation\u2019s largest union, endorses Joe Biden for president}}</ref>  The NEA calling Biden \"a tireless advocate for students, educators, and strong public schools.\"<ref name=StraussNEA/>\n\n===Gun policy===\nThroughout his career, Biden has supported [[gun control]] measures.<ref name=TIME08>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden on Gun Control|website=Time|date=2008|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1849140_1849287_1849789,00.html}}</ref> Although he voted for the 1986 [[Firearm Owners Protection Act]], a bill supported by the [[National Rifle Association]] (NRA) that passed the Senate 79&ndash;15, Biden also authored the 1993 [[federal assault weapons ban]], and is a longtime supporter of [[universal background checks]], and received \"F\" ratings from the NRA while he was in Congress.<ref name=\"NBC News\">{{cite web | title=Biden Voted with NRA When Senate and Nation were Very Different|publisher=NBC News|date=April 24, 2019|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/biden-voted-nra-when-senate-nation-were-very-different-n997311|author=Alex Seitz-Wald}}</ref> \n\nBiden supported the 1993 [[Brady Handgun Violence Prevention Act]], which established five-day waiting periods for handgun purchases and background checks.<ref name=\"NYT93\">{{cite web | title=Senate Roll-Call on the Brady Bill|website=The New York Times|date=November 21, 1993|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/21/us/senate-roll-call-on-the-brady-bill.html}}</ref> He had a central role in the passage of the [[Federal Assault Weapons Ban]] of 1994, which banned the  manufacture, transfer, or possession of certain firearms classified as [[assault weapon]]s (with a [[grandfather clause]] excepting guns owned prior to its implementation).<ref name=\"NPR13\">{{cite web|title=Key Player In '94 Assault Weapons Ban: 'It's Going To Be Much More Difficult' Now|publisher=NPR|date=January 18, 2013|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/itsallpolitics/2013/01/29/169551103/banning-assault-weapons-now-much-more-difficult-than-94-aides-say|work=Morning Edition}}</ref> After the ban expired in 2004, Biden voted in favor of renewing it in a 2007 Senate vote.<ref name=TIME08/> The Obama/Biden administration also unsuccessfully pressed for renewal of the ban.<ref name=\"NPR13\"/> Biden voted against the [[Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act]] (PLCAA) of 2005, which immunizes firearm manufacturers from lawsuits based on gun violence.<ref name=\"TIME08\"/>\n\nAfter the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School massacre]] in 2012, Obama named Biden to lead a task force on gun violence and community safety; the administration proposed [[universal background checks]], resumption of [[Dickey Amendment|public health research on gun violence]], reinstatement of the federal assault weapons ban, but proposals requiring legislative action were killed in the Republican-controlled Congress.<ref>Alan Yuhas & Nicky Woolf, [https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/dec/04/what-happened-president-obama-joe-biden-plan-reduce-gun-violence-sandy-hook-san-bernardino What happened to President Obama's plan to reduce gun violence?], ''The Guardian'' (December 4, 2015).</ref><ref name=UPI2020>[https://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2019/12/14/Joe-Biden-announces-gun-safety-plan-on-anniversary-of-Sandy-Hook-shooting/9761576345302/ Joe Biden announces gun safety plan on anniversary of Sandy Hook shooting], UPI (December 14, 2019).</ref><ref>Matt Viser & Felicia Sonmez, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/joe-biden-releases-gun-plan-that-would-reinstate-assault-weapons-ban-and-establish-a-voluntary-buyback-program/2019/10/01/53d10e28-e4ac-11e9-a6e8-8759c5c7f608_story.html Joe Biden releases gun plan that would reinstate assault weapons ban and establish a voluntary buyback program], ''Washington Post'' (October 1, 2019).</ref> During his 2020 presidential campaign, Biden's proposals on gun violence include universal background checks for gun sales, repeal of PLCAA, reinstatement of the assault weapons ban and a [[High-capacity magazine ban|ban on high-capacity magazines]], and incentives for states to adopt [[red flag law]]s.<ref name=UPI2020/>\n\n===Homeland security===\nAfter the [[Oklahoma City bombing]] on April 19, 1995, a domestic terrorist bomb attack that destroyed the [[Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building]], Biden drafted [[Omnibus Counterterrorism Act of 1995|anti-terrorist legislation]], which was ultimately defeated<!-- This is not the case. \u2018\u2018The Omnibus Counterterrorism Act of 1995\u2019\u2019 was read in the Senate of the United States (twice) on February 10, 1995. This was nearly two months prior to the Oklahoma City bombing which took place April 19, 1995. This was drafted prior to this domestic attack. It was later found to be unconstitutional and invaded upon civil liberties. However, it served as a foundation of the formation of the Patriot Act of 2001. -->. He later claimed publicly on several occasions that the [[Patriot Act|USA PATRIOT Act]], which eased restrictions on the [[Executive (government)|Executive branch]] in the surveillance and detention of those suspected of terrorism or facilitating it, was essentially a duplicate of the [[Omnibus Counterterrorism Act of 1995|anti-terrorist legislation]] he had drafted years earlier.<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://www.tnr.com/article/politics/rhetorical-question | title = Rhetorical Question | journal = The New Republic | author=Michael Crowley | date = October 22, 2001 | accessdate =August 25, 2008}}</ref> Biden supported the PATRIOT Act but voted to limit [[Telephone tapping|wiretapping]] on the bill. He supports implementing the [[9/11 Commission]]'s recommendations to fight terrorists but voted to preserve [[habeas corpus]] rights to the alleged terror suspects serving in [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay]]. In the 1990s, he voted in favor of 36 vetoed military projects and supports efforts to prevent [[nuclear proliferation]]. He was given a 60% approval rating from the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) reflecting a mixed voting record on [[civil rights]] issues. During a debate on November 15, 2007, Biden clarified the PATRIOT Act's effect and his continued support for it and his opposition to [[racial profiling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfr.org/publication/14820/democratic_debate_transcript_las_vegas_nevada.html?breadcrumb=%2Fbios%2F1451%2Fjoseph_r_biden_jr |title=Democratic Debate Transcript, Las Vegas, Nevada \u2013 Council on Foreign Relations|accessdate=August 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn the [[War on Terror]], Biden voted in favor of the [[Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Iraq Resolution of 2002]] and the [[Patriot Act]] of 2001.<ref name=\"PATRIOTT01\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/107-2002/s237|title=H.J.Res. 114 (107th): Authorization for Use of Military Force Against ... -- Senate Vote #237 -- Oct 11, 2002|website=GovTrack.us|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=107&session=1&vote=00313|title=U.S. Senate: U.S. Senate Roll Call Votes 107th Congress - 1st Session|website=[[senate.gov]]|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\n====Senate====\nWhile in the Senate, Biden voted in favor of the [[Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986|1986 immigration bill]] (which passed) and the [[Comprehensive Immigration Reform Act of 2007|2007 comprehensive immigration reform bill]] (which failed).<ref>Amy Sherman, [https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2019/jul/12/weston-pagano/fact-checking-attack-joe-biden-about-immigration-d/ Fact-checking an attack on Joe Biden about immigration deportation, detention votes], ''PolitiFact'' (July 12, 2019).</ref> In a 2007 Democratic presidential primary debate, Biden said that it would be impractical and expensive to deport every unauthorized immigrant in the U.S. and proposed an earned [[path to citizenship]], saying: \"Get a background check on all of them, take out the criminals, get them back, and provide for a means by which we allow earned citizenship over the next decade or so. Folks, being commander in chief requires you to occasionally be practical.\"<ref name=TranscriptJune2007>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/03/us/politics/03demsdebate_transcript.html Transcript: The Democrats' Second 2008 Presidential Debate], ''New York Times'' (June 3, 2007).</ref> Biden voted for the [[Secure Fence Act of 2006]], which authorized and partially funded the construction of fencing along the Mexican border,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=109&session=2&vote=00262|title=Senate Roll Call Votes 109th Congress - 2nd Session|publisher=United States Senate}}</ref> mostly as a means to combat cross-border [[drug trafficking]].<ref name=TranscriptJune2007/> During the same campaign, Biden said that would not allow sanctuary cities to ignore federal law.<ref name=Sanctuary>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/456638-biden-once-called-for-a-ban-on-sanctuary-cities-where-does-he-stand-now|title=Biden once called for a ban on sanctuary cities; Where does he stand now?|first=Rafael|last=Nam|date=August 8, 2019|website=The Hill}}</ref> In 2007, Biden said that illegal immigration would not stop unless U.S. employers stopped hiring undocumented workers, saying: \"All the rest is window dressing.\"<ref>Ilene Rosenblum, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/nation/documents/immigration_primer_060807.html Issues and Influentials in the Immigration Reform Debate], ''Washington Post'' (June 28, 2007).</ref>\n\n====Vice presidency====\nAs vice president, Biden supported the [[Border Security, Economic Opportunity, and Immigration Modernization Act of 2013|2013 bipartisan comprehensive immigration reform bill]], a bill crafted by the [[Gang of Eight (immigration)|Gang of Eight]] (four Democratic, four Republican senators) that would have created a 13-year pathway to citizenship for unauthorized immigrants with security checks, devoted unprecedented resources to border security, created a new work visa program, and established a mandatory employment verification system to ensure that persons hired are authorized to work in the U.S.  As [[president of the Senate]], Biden personally presided over the Senate when the bill passed 68&ndash;32.<ref>Seung Min Kim, [https://www.politico.com/story/2013/06/immigration-bill-2013-senate-passes-093530 Senate passes immigration bill], ''Politico'' (June 27, 2013).</ref><ref>Matt Vasilogambros, [https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2013/06/with-joe-biden-at-the-senate-immigration-reform-is-passed/438090/ With Joe Biden at the Senate, Immigration Reform Is Passed], ''The Atlantic''/''National Journal'' (June 27, 2013).</ref> The legislation failed, however, in the Republican-controlled House of Representatives.<ref>Alec MacGillis, [https://www.propublica.org/article/washington-congress-immigration-reform-failure How Washington Blew Its Best Chance to Fix Immigration], ''ProPublica'' (September 15, 2016).</ref>\n\n====2020 proposals====\nDuring his 2020 presidential campaign, Biden issued his \"Biden Plan for Securing Our Values as [[a Nation of Immigrants]],\" in which he pledged to \"secure our border, while ensuring the dignity of migrants and upholding their legal [[Right to asylum|right to seek asylum]]. ... enforce our laws without targeting communities, violating due process, or tearing apart families,\" \"ensure our values are squarely at the center of our immigration and enforcement policies,\" and create a \"fair and humane immigration system.\"<ref name=BidenImmigration>[https://joebiden.com/immigration/ The Biden Plan for Securing Our Values as a Nation of Immigrants], Biden for President (accessed April 15, 2020).</ref> Biden's proposals would undo Trump's immigration policies,<ref name=KaplanGlueck>Thomas Kaplan & Katie Glueck, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/11/us/politics/joe-biden-immigration.html Joe Biden Calls for Immigration Overhaul, Acknowledging 'Pain' From Deportations], ''New York Times'' (December 11, 2019).</ref><ref name=NagleImmigration>Molly Nagle, [https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/biden-seeks-undo-trumps-immigration-policies-100-days/story?id=67663203 Biden seeks to undo several Trump immigration policies in first 100 days in new immigration proposal], ABC News (December 12, 2019).</ref> which Biden has criticized as immoral, inhumane, ineffective, economically damaging, and unconstitutional.<ref name=BidenImmigration/>  He pledged a reversal of the Trump administration's [[Trump administration family separation policy|family separation policy]], travel/refugee bans, and severe restrictions on [[Right to asylum|asylum]],<ref name=BidenImmigration/><ref name=NagleImmigration/> calling these policies \"cruel and senseless\" and \"un-American.\"<ref name=BidenImmigration/> If elected, he pledges to reverse Trump's [[public charge rule]] and \"so-called [[National Emergency Concerning the Southern Border of the United States|National Emergency]],\" which diverted money from the [[Defense Department]] to construct a [[Trump wall|wall on the U.S.-Mexico border]].<ref name=BidenImmigration/>  Biden criticized Trump's promotion of a wall solution to border security, noting that smuggling through legal [[Ports of entry|ports of entry]], rather than simple illicit border-crossing, is the dominant method by which [[Illegal drug trade|illicit drugs]] enter the U.S., and that \"sophisticated criminal organizations\" can easily that circumvent physical barriers through \"border tunnels, semi-submersible vessels, and aerial technology.\"<ref name=BidenImmigration/> Biden has called for better security along the border and at ports of entry through technology and infrastructure (such as \"cameras, sensors, large-scale x-ray machines, and fixed towers\") as well as through improved coordination between federal agencies, as well as Mexican and Canadian authorities.<ref name=BidenImmigration/>  \n\nDuring his 2020 campaign, Biden proposed a \"surge\" of humanitarian resources to the border and restoration of the [[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals]] (DACA) program for [[Undocumented youth in the United States|undocumented youth raised in the United States]] (the \"[[DREAM Act|Dreamers]]\").<ref name=BidenImmigration/> As a longer-term goal, Biden said he supported a [[path to citizenship]] for undocumented immigrants currently in the United States.<ref name=KaplanGlueck/><ref name=NagleImmigration/> Biden also pledged to create a program to allow U.S. military veterans deported by the Trump Administration to return to the United States.<ref name=BidenImmigration/> He supports evidence-based alternatives to prolonged [[immigration detention]],<ref name=BidenImmigration/> and a ban on for-profit detention centers.<ref name=KaplanGlueck/> Biden does not support abolition of [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] (ICE), as some on the left wing have called for, but said that his administration would ensure that ICE and [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] officers \"abide by professional standards and are held accountable for inhumane treatment.\"<ref name=KaplanGlueck/> Biden does not support the decriminalization of [[Illegal entry|unauthorized border-crossing]],<ref name=KaplanGlueck/> but pledged to restore \"sensible enforcement priorities\" that focus deportation and other enforcement efforts on persons convicted of serious crimes.<ref name=NagleImmigration/><ref name=BidenImmigration/> rather than people \"who have lived, worked, and contributed to our economy and our communities for decades.\"<ref name=BidenImmigration/> To address a backlog in the immigration courts, Biden proposed a doubling of the number of [[Immigration Judge (United States)|immigration judges]] and interpreters.<ref name=KaplanGlueck/> Biden also opposes Trump's attempts to withhold federal grant funding from sanctuary cities.<ref name=Sanctuary/>\n\nRegarding [[Migrant crisis|migrant crises]], Biden's 2020 immigration policy emphasized a need to address the root causes of migration from the  [[Central America]]'s [[Northern Triangle]] of [[El Salvador]], [[Guatemala]], and [[Honduras]], such as endemic instability, corruption, gang violence and gender-based violence, and a lack of the [[rule of law]]. Biden pledged to update the [[Central American Minors Program]] and advance humanitarian aid, stability, and economic development in the region. He also stated that he would use the [[Temporary Protected Status]] program for persons whose countries of origin suffer from violence or unsafe conditions.<ref name=BidenImmigration/><ref name=NagleImmigration/>\n\n===Internet privacy and file sharing===\nIn 2006, in its Technology Issues Voter's Guide, [[CNET]].com gave Biden a score of 37.5% on his Senate voting record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/2009-1040-6130830.html?hhTest=1|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120711015612/http://news.cnet.com/2009-1040-6130830.html?hhTest=1|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-07-11|title=Technology voter guide 2006 \u2013 Mapping Congress' voting records | publisher= CNET News.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Overview of Senate voting scores |url=http://i.i.com.com/cnwk.1d//i/ne/sr06/tech_vote_guide_06/senate-by-score.xls |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111114023657/http://i.i.com.com/cnwk.1d//i/ne/sr06/tech_vote_guide_06/senate-by-score.xls |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-11-14 |work=Cnet |format=xls}}</ref> Biden was a co-sponsor of the [[Platform Equality and Remedies for Rights Holders in Music Act of 2007]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/senators-aim-to-restrict-net-satellite-radio-recording/|title=Senators aim to restrict Net, satellite radio recording|first=Anne|last=Broache|website=CNET}}</ref> \n\nBiden also sponsored two bills, the [http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d102:s.00266: Comprehensive Counter-Terrorism Act] (SB 266) and the [http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d102:s.00618: Violent Crime Control Act] (SB 618), both of which contained language seen as effectively banning [[encryption]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/cnet/20080824/tc_cnet/83011357831002416338 |title=Joe Biden's pro-RIAA, pro-FBI tech voting record \u2013 Yahoo! News |accessdate=August 25, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828193707/http://news.yahoo.com/s/cnet/20080824/tc_cnet/83011357831002416338 |archivedate=August 28, 2008 }}</ref> ''Crypto'' notes Biden wrote that language into the text of SB 266.<ref>{{cite book | last=Levy | first=Steven | authorlink=Steven Levy | title=Crypto: How the Code Rebels Beat the Government, Saving Privacy in the Digital Age | year=2001 | publisher=Viking | location=New York | isbn=0-670-85950-8 | page=195}}</ref> [[Phil Zimmermann]], the creator of [[Pretty Good Privacy]], has said it was SB 266 that \"led [him] to publish PGP electronically for free that year, shortly before the measure was defeated after vigorous protest by civil libertarians and industry groups.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philzimmermann.com/EN/essays/index.html |title=Phil Zimmermann on PGP |accessdate=August 25, 2008}}</ref> He later stated in a ''Slashdot'' article that he was not specifically criticizing Biden, that he would consider the Senator's \"whole body of work\" when considering whether to vote for him on the Democratic ticket in 2008, and that \"considering the disastrous erosion in our privacy and civil liberties under the (Bush) administration, I feel positively nostalgic about Biden's quaint little non-binding resolution of 1991\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=08/08/26/2126214 |title=Phil Zimmermann on Sen. Biden and 2008 Democratic ticket |accessdate=June 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===LGBTQ issues===\nWhile in the Senate, Biden voted in 1993 for a broad defense bill that included the \"[[don't ask, don't tell]]\" law on [[Sexual orientation in the United States military|LGBT service in the U.S. military]], after voting to remove the amendment.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=Becker>{{Cite news|agency=Reuters|title=Biden's LGBTQ record draws scrutiny at Iowa presidential forum|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-biden/bidens-lgbtq-record-draws-scrutiny-at-iowa-presidential-forum-idUSKBN1W603A|authors=Amanda Becker & Trevor Hunnicutt|date=September 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Epstein|first=Reid J.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/us/politics/lgbt-forum-2020.html|title=Joe Biden Has Tense Exchange Over L.G.B.T.Q. Record|date=2019-09-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|last2=Lerer|first2=Lisa|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> As vice president, Biden supported the [[Don't Ask, Don't Tell Repeal Act of 2010]], which repealed the prohibition on open service by gay, lesbian, and bisexual people in the U.S. military.<ref name=Becker/>\n\nIn 1996, Biden voted in favor of the [[Defense of Marriage Act]] which prohibited the federal government from recognizing any same-sex marriage, barring individuals in such marriages from equal protection under federal law, and allowing states to do the same.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=104&session=2&vote=00280|title=U.S. Senate: U.S. Senate Roll Call Votes 104th Congress - 2nd Session|website=senate.gov|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref> In the Senate, Biden was an outspoken critic of congressional Republicans' efforts in 2000s to adopt a [[Federal Marriage Amendment|constitutional amendment to prohibit same-sex marriage]]; in arguing against the proposal in 2004, Biden cited his position that same-sex marriage was an issue for states to decide.<ref name=\":0\" /> In a May 2012 ''[[Meet the Press]]'' interview, Vice President Biden reversed his previous position and publicly supported [[marriage equality]], saying he was \"absolutely comfortable with the fact that men marrying men, women marrying women, and heterosexual men and women marrying another are entitled to the same exact rights, all the civil rights, all the civil liberties. And quite frankly, I don't see much of a distinction beyond that.\"<ref name=\"Stein0506\">{{cite news |last=Stein |first=Sam |title=Joe Biden Tells 'Meet The Press' He's 'Comfortable' With Marriage Equality |publisher=Huffington Post |date=May 6, 2012 |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/06/vice-president-biden-gay-marriage_n_1489235.html |accessdate=Aug 20, 2012}}</ref> Prior to Biden's statement on ''Meet the Press'', the Obama administration endorsed [[civil union]]s, but not same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Barbaro|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/07/us/politics/biden-expresses-support-for-same-sex-marriages.html|newspaper=New York Times|title=A Scramble as Biden Backs Same-Sex Marriage|date=May 7, 2012}}</ref> Biden's decision reportedly forced Obama's hand, pressuring Obama to accelerate his own public shift to support same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news|title=W.H.: Biden forced Obama's hand|author=Glenn Thrush & Jennifer Epstein|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2012/05/obama-expected-to-speak-on-gay-marriage-076103|newspaper=Politico|date=May 10, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Edward-Isaac Dovere|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2014/04/joe-biden-gay-marriage-white-house-response-105744|title=Book: W.H. scrambled after Biden gay marriage comments|newspaper=Politico|date=April 16, 2014}}</ref> In 2013, Section 3 of DOMA was ruled unconstitutional and partially struck down in ''[[United States v. Windsor]]''. The Obama Administration did not defend the law and congratulated Windsor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/supreme-court/2013/06/26/f0039814-d9ab-11e2-a016-92547bf094cc_story.html|title=Supreme Court strikes down key part of Defense of Marriage Act|last=Barnes|first=Robert|date=June 26, 2013|website=The Washington Post|access-date=}}{{paywall}}</ref> \n\nBiden supported the U.S. Supreme Court's 5&ndash;4 ruling in ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' (2015), which held that same-sex couples have a federal constitutional right to marry. Biden issued a statement saying that the ruling reflected a principle that \"all people should be treated with respect and dignity\u2014and that all marriages, at their root, are defined by unconditional love.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2015/06/26/statement-vice-president-supreme-court-decision-obergefell-v-hodges|title=Statement by the Vice President on the Supreme Court Decision in Obergefell v. Hodges|date=June 26, 2015|publisher=White House Office of the Vice President}}</ref> In an event with the group [[Freedom to Marry]], Biden described the decision as \"the civil rights movement of our generation\" and as consequential as ''[[Brown v. Board of Education]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/247482-biden-compares-gay-marriage-ruling-to-brown-v-board-of-education|newspaper=The Hill|date=July 10, 2015|title=Biden compares gay marriage ruling to 'Brown v. Board of Education'|author=Jordan Fabian}}</ref> \n[[Jim Obergefell]], the lead plaintiff in the case, endorsed Biden's 2020 presidential run, as did other LGBT leaders.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonblade.com/2020/03/02/jim-obergefell-lead-plaintiff-in-marriage-case-latest-to-endorse-joe-biden/|title=Jim Obergefell, lead plaintiff in marriage case, latest to endorse Joe Biden|date=March 2, 2020|newspaper=Washington Blade}}</ref> \n\nBiden supports the [[Equality Act (United States)|Equality Act]], proposed federal legislation that would extend the nondiscrimination protections of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]] to cover discrimination \"on the basis of sex, sexual orientation, gender identity, or pregnancy, childbirth, or a related medical condition of an individual, as well as because of sex-based stereotypes.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/joe-biden-matthew-shepard-mom-civil-rights-act-includes-lgbtq_n_5d9fc151e4b087efdbab8bd9|work=HuffPost|date=October 10, 2019|author=Sanjana Karanth}}</ref> \n\nDuring his 2020 presidential campaign, Biden vowed to support legislation and action to prohibit [[transgender inequality|discrimination against transgender people]] and to combat [[hate crimes]] targeting LGBT persons, including [[Violence against LGBT people|violence and harassment against transgender people]].<ref name=HRC>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrc.org/resources/joe-biden-on-lgbtq-issues|title=Presidential Candidate Joe Biden on LGBTQ Issues|publisher=Human Rights Campaign}}</ref><ref name=Kelly>{{Cite news|author=Caroline Kelly|title=Biden: Fastest way to end transgender violence 'is to end the Trump administration'|publisher=CNN|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/01/politics/biden-lgbtq-comments-hrc-speech/index.html|date=June 1, 2019}}</ref> He has criticized Republicans, and particularly Vice President [[Mike Pence]], for using \"religious freedom as an excuse to license discrimination.\"<ref name=HRC/><ref name=Kelly/> He supports the Safe Schools Improvement Act, a proposed anti-bullying law.<ref name=HRC/>\n\n===Religious faith ===\nAt a November 2011 campaign event, in response to a question about how Biden viewed Mitt Romney's Mormon faith in November 2011, Biden said, \"I find it preposterous that in 2011 we're debating whether or not a man is qualified or worthy of your vote based on whether or not his religion ... is a disqualifying provision.  It is not. It is embarrassing and we should be ashamed, anyone who thinks that way.\"<ref name=Defends>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/11/04/us-usa-campaign-biden-romney-idUSTRE7A371Q20111104|title=Biden defends Romney's Mormon faith|agency=Reuters|date=November 4, 2011}}</ref> Biden cited the anti-Catholic prejudice encountered by [[John F. Kennedy]] in the [[1960 United States presidential election|1960 presidential election]].<ref name=Defends/>\n\n===Women's rights===\nIn 1994, Biden drafted the [[Violence Against Women Act]]. This law provided $1.6 billion to enhance investigation and prosecution of the violent crime perpetrated against women, increased pre-trial detention of the accused, provided for automatic and mandatory restitution of those convicted, and allowed civil redress in cases prosecutors chose to leave unprosecuted.\n\nThe [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] struck down portions of the VAWA on Constitutional grounds in ''[[United States v. Morrison]]''.\n\nBiden has said, \"I consider the Violence Against Women Act the single most significant legislation that I've crafted during my 35-year tenure in the Senate. Indeed, the enactment of the Violence Against Women Act in 1994 was the beginning of a historic commitment to women and children victimized by [[domestic violence]] and [[sexual assault]]. Our nation has been rewarded for this commitment. Since the Act's passage in 1994, domestic violence has dropped by almost 50%.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://biden.senate.gov/issues/issue/?id=975b0cf4-ce25-42cc-b63d-072fb81e8618 |title=Senator Joe Biden \u2013 Senator for Delaware: Issues \u2013 Domestic Violence |accessdate=September 8, 2008 |publisher=US Senate |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822144642/http://biden.senate.gov/issues/issue/?id=975b0cf4-ce25-42cc-b63d-072fb81e8618 |archivedate=August 22, 2008}}</ref> He has also said that the Act \"empower[s] women to make changes in their lives, and by training police and prosecutors to arrest and convict abusive husbands instead of telling them to take a walk around the block\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://biden.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/BidenRecordWomen.pdf |title=Senator Joe Biden Stands Up For Women |accessdate=September 8, 2008 |publisher=US Senate |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080730224418/http://biden.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/BidenRecordWomen.pdf |archivedate=July 30, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Biden told a group of students that having sex with a woman while she is drunk, is rape.<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/video_and_audio/headlines/39734868/ex-vp-joe-biden-tells-students-if-she-s-drunk-it-s-rape</ref>\n\nThere has been controversy regarding then-Senator Biden's actions during the [[Anita Hill]] hearings of 1991. At the time Biden was serving as chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]] during the nomination of Republican judge [[Clarence Thomas]] who was nominated by then-President [[George H. W. Bush]]. During the nomination process, Judge Thomas was accused of a consistent pattern of sexual harassment.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dovere |first1=Edward-Isaac |title=Biden's 'Anita' problem |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2015/09/biden-anita-hill-women-senate-clarence-thomas-213864 |accessdate=9 January 2019 |work=POLITICO |language=en}}</ref> During the hearing, Biden referred to the accusations by Hill as being \"he said, she said\"<ref>{{cite news |title=How Joe Biden's 1991 comments about the FBI and Anita Hill are now being used against Democrats \u2014 and Biden's response in 2018 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/history/2018/09/26/how-joe-bidens-comments-about-fbi-anita-hill-are-now-being-used-against-democrats |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref> and as a \"character assassination\".<ref>{{cite news |title=As he considers 2020, Joe Biden airs regrets of Anita Hill hearings |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2018/09/21/considers-joe-biden-airs-regrets-anita-hill-hearings/6JjWMfOg2Dr6lLqip5XmJI/story.html |work=The Boston Globe |language=en}}</ref> In 2017, Biden issued an apology to Anita Hill, stating: \"Let\u2019s get something straight here, I believed Anita Hill. I voted against Clarence Thomas... I am so sorry that she had to go through what she went through. Think of the courage that it took for her to come forward.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2017/11/anita-hill-responds-to-joe-bidens-apology.html|title=Anita Hill Responds to Joe Biden's Apology|first=Madeleine Aggeler|last=The Cut|website=The Cut}}</ref>\n\n====Abortion ====\n\n; ''Roe v. Wade''\n\nAccording to Jamal Brown, Biden's press secretary, said that when Biden arrived in the Senate in 1973 he thought ''[[Roe v. Wade]]'' was wrongly decided, but now \"firmly believes that ''Roe v. Wade'' is the law of the land and should not be overturned\". In 1981, he voted for a failed constitutional amendment allowing states to overturn ''Roe v. Wade''. In 1982, he voted against the same failed constitutional amendment allowing states to overturn ''Roe'', and in 2006, he stated in an interview that \"I do not view abortion as a choice and a right. I think it's always a tragedy[.]\"<ref name=\"USA Today\" /> He now says he would consider codifying the ''Roe'' precedent into federal law in case the ruling is overturned by the United States Supreme Court.<ref name=\"Bidenabortion\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/biden-s-long-evolution-abortion-rights-still-holds-surprises-n1013846|title=Biden's long evolution on abortion rights still holds surprises|publisher=NBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"Overnight Health Care\">{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/overnights/447190-overnight-health-care-trump-admin-cutting-services-for-migrant|title=Overnight Health Care: Biden infuriates abortion-rights groups with stance on Hyde Amendment - Trump tightens restrictions on fetal tissue research - Democrats plan event to scrutinize Trump's mental health|first=Peter|last=Sullivan|date=June 5, 2019|website=The Hill}}</ref> He pledged that he would appoint [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] justices who shared his beliefs in upholding ''Roe''.<ref name=\"prochoiceamerica\">{{cite web |url=http://www.prochoiceamerica.org/elections/statements/biden.html |title=Senator Joe Biden (D-DE) |work=[[NARAL Pro-Choice America]] |accessdate=October 1, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213210038/http://www.prochoiceamerica.org/elections/statements/biden.html |archivedate=December 13, 2007}}</ref>\n\n; Federal abortion funding\n\nFrom 1976 to June 5, 2019, Biden supported the [[Hyde Amendment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/05/us/politics/biden-hyde-amendment.html|title=Biden Still Backs Hyde Amendment, Which Bans Federal Funds for Abortions|first=Katie|last=Glueck|date=June 5, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/94-1976/s962|title=TO AMEND H.R. 14232... -- Senate Vote #962 Jun 28, 1976|website=GovTrack.us}}</ref> On June 6, 2019, Biden reversed his support and now supports repealing the Hyde Amendment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/06/us/politics/joe-biden-hyde-amendment.html|title=Joe Biden Denounces Hyde Amendment, Reversing His Position|first=Katie|last=Glueck|date=June 6, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> In 1981, he voted to end federal funding for abortion for victims of rape and incest.<ref name=\"Bidenabortion\"/> Biden previously supported the [[Mexico City policy]], but now supports repealing it.<ref name=\"Overnight Health Care\"/>\n\n; Post-viability abortion\n\nIn 2003, Biden voted for the \"[[Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=108&session=1&vote=00402|title=U.S. Senate: U.S. Senate Roll Call Votes 108th Congress - 1st Session|website=senate.gov}}</ref> In 2007, he opposed the [[United States Supreme Court]] ruling in the case of ''[[Gonzales v. Carhart]]'' which upheld the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003. He defended his opposition, saying he opposed the court's reasoning for the ruling, not the decision itself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ontheissues.org/2020/Joe_Biden_Abortion.htm|title=Joe Biden on Abortion|website=ontheissues.org}}</ref>\n\n==Economic issues==\n[[File:Joe Biden - World Economic Forum Annual Meeting Davos 2005 Portrait.jpg|thumb|Joe Biden at the [[World Economic Forum]] in [[Davos]], [[Switzerland]]]]\n\n===Agriculture and rural issues===\nBiden supported the [[Food, Conservation, and Energy Act of 2008|2008 farm bill]], calling it a \"responsible compromise.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828213948/http://biden.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/BidenOnAgriculture.pdf |title=Senator Joe Biden on Agriculture|publisher=United States Senate, Office of Senator Joe Biden}}</ref> When he chaired the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, Biden identified agricultural development and global [[food prices]] as major issues.<ref name=BidenAgSenate/>\n\nWhile in the Senate, Biden called for strong action against [[invasive species]], citing the economic and environmental risks associated with them, including displacement of native shipping, introduction of disease, and interference with shipping.<ref name=BidenAgSenate/>\n\nIn the Senate, Biden paid particular attention to issues affecting the [[poultry industry]], which is economically important to Delaware, especially in the [[Delmarva peninsula]].<ref name=BidenAgSenate/> In the 1990s, Biden criticized the Russian government for threatening to ban imported U.S. chicken,<ref name=BidenAgSenate/> and in 2008 criticized the Russian government for banning imports of chicken from 19 poultry processing plants in the United States, Biden stated that \"Russia is once again using [[Non-tariff barriers to trade|non-tariff barriers]] as an excuse to close its markets to American poultry. ... Russia has repeatedly shown that it is not ready to abide by the rules of international trade.\"<ref name=Chicken>{{cite press release|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080902034113/http://biden.senate.gov/press/press_releases/release/?id=844009C2-8BBD-4DE9-888B-5CC6FF071114|title=Biden Issues Statement on News of Russia's Ban on Chicken Imports|date=August 30, 2008|publisher=United States Senate, Office of Senator Joe Biden}}</ref> Biden described the Russian action as \"part of a bigger picture in which Russia has failed to behave as a responsible member in the [[international community]]\" can called for the U.S. to block Russia's application to join the [[World Trade Organization]].<ref name=Chicken/> Biden also worked to promote funding to research [[avian influenza]].<ref name=BidenAgSenate/>\n\nDuring his 2020 presidential campaign, Biden has outlined a rural and agricultural policies broadly similar to those of the Obama administration. The plan aims to obtain net-zero emissions for agriculture (making the U.S. the first nation to do so) via incentives and permitting farmers to join [[carbon market]]s. The plan also calls for changes in trade policy to encourage U.S. agriculture exports; expansion of [[broadband Internet]] in rural areas; [[renewable energy]] investment; promotion of [[local food|local]] and regional food; and an expansion of the USDA Conservation Stewardship Program to encourage farmers to adopt [[carbon sequestration]] and other environmental practices.<ref name=Evich>{{Cite news|author=Helena Bottemiller Evich|newspaper=Politico|title=How Joe Biden would address agriculture and rural issues|date=July 17, 2019|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/07/17/joe-biden-agriculture-rural-2020-1598121}}</ref>\n\n===Banking===\nDuring the 2000s, Biden sponsored bankruptcy legislation, which was sought by [[MBNA]], one of Delaware's largest companies and Biden's largest contributor in the late 1990s,<ref name=usatoday09302015 /> and other credit card issuers.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\">''Almanac of American Politics'' 2008, p. 364.</ref> He fought for certain amendments to the bill that would indirectly protect homeowners and forbid felons from using bankruptcy to discharge fines.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\" /> He also worked to defeat amendments which would have protected members of the military and those who are pushed into bankruptcy by medical debt. Critics expressed concern that the law would force those seeking bankruptcy protection to hire lawyers to process the required paperwork and would make it more difficult for students to execute education-related debt.<ref name=usatoday09302015>{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2015/09/30/joe-biden-senate-record-2016-campaign/73045484/ | title=Joe Biden's record could pose difficulties for 2016 White House bid | author=Przybyla, Heidi | publisher=USA Today | date=September 30, 2015 | accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> The overall bill was vetoed by President [[Bill Clinton]] in 2000, but then finally passed as the [[Bankruptcy Abuse Prevention and Consumer Protection Act]] in 2005, with Biden supporting it.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\" />\n\n===Energy and environment===\nBiden has been credited with introducing the first climate change bill in Congress.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|author=John Kruzel|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2019/may/08/joe-biden/was-joe-biden-climate-change-pioneer-congress-hist/|title=Yes, Joe Biden was a climate change pioneer in Congress|website=PolitiFact|date=May 8, 2019}}</ref> Biden's initial bill, the Global Climate Protection Act, was introduced in 1986; it died in the Senate, but a version was included in a bill signed into law by President Reagan as an amendment to the Foreign Relations Authorization Act in December 1987.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2008, Biden was the lead sponsor of a \"Sense of the Senate\" resolution calling on the U.S. to be a part of the United Nations climate change negotiations, and was a cosponsor of the [[Barbara Boxer|Boxer]]-[[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]] [[Global Warming Pollution Reduction Act]], at the time the most stringent climate bill in the Senate. The legislation would have created a [[cap-and-trade]] system for [[greenhouse-gas emissions]] and required a reduction in U.S. emissions to 1990 levels by 2020, and to 80% below 1990 levels by 2050.<ref name=Grist>[https://grist.org/article/biden_factsheet/ A look at the environmental record of Joe Biden, Barack Obama\u2019s running mate], ''Grist'' (August 30, 2007, updated August 23, 2008).</ref> He strongly opposed [[Arctic Refuge drilling controversy|opening the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge to oil drilling]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anwr.org/Politics/Presidential-Candidates-views-on-ANWR-The-Democrats.php |title=Arctic Power \u2013 Arctic National Wildlife Refuge \u2013 Presidential Candidates views on ANWR, The Democrats |accessdate=August 25, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080807162357/http://www.anwr.org/Politics/Presidential-Candidates-views-on-ANWR-The-Democrats.php |archivedate=August 7, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/17/politics/senate-votes-to-allow-drilling-in-arctic-reserve.html|newspaper=New York Times|date=March 17, 2005|title=Senate Votes to Allow Drilling in Arctic Reserve|author=Sheryl Gay Stolberg}}</ref>  In 2007&ndash;2008, during his presidential camoaign, Biden called for a gradual increase in automobile fuel-economy standards to 40 miles per gallon by 2017,<ref name=Grist/> called for increase production of [[renewable energy]],<ref name=Grist/> and identified [[energy security]] and resolving the [[energy crisis]] as key priorities.<ref>Amanda Little, [https://grist.org/article/biden/ An interview with Joe Biden about energy and the environment], ''Grist'' (August 30, 2007)</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|Biden's presidential campaign]] unveiled a $1.7 trillion climate policy plan aimed at eliminate U.S. net greenhouse gas emissions by 2050. The proposal incorporated elements of the [[Green New Deal]] proposal.<ref name=CNNClimatePlan>{{cite web|authors=Eric Bradner & Arlette Saenz|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/04/politics/joe-biden-2020-climate-plan/index.html|title=Joe Biden's climate plan targets net-zero emissions by 2050|date=June 4, 2019|publisher=CNN}}</ref> Biden's plan would eliminate fossil fuel subsidies; halt issuance of new permits for oil and gas extraction on public land and water; step up [[Clean Air Act of 1963|Clean Air Act]] enforcement; strengthen [[Fuel economy in automobiles|fuel economy]] standards to promote a shift to [[electric vehicle]]s; regulate [[methane pollution]]; and create \"aggressive\" [[Efficient energy use|energy efficiency]] standards for appliances and buildings.<ref name=CNNClimatePlan/> Biden also promised that he would re-enter the [[Paris Agreement]] (from [[United States withdrawal from the Paris Agreement|which Trump pulled the U.S.]]) on his first day in the White House and called for \"a major diplomatic push to raise the ambitions of countries' climate targets.\"<ref name=CNNClimatePlan/> To pressure countries failing to meet their climate obligations, Biden also called for \"carbon adjustment fees\" to be levied on goods imported from countries that failed to meet emissions targets.<ref name=CNNClimatePlan/>\n\n===Transportation===\nDuring the Obama administration, Biden was the lead figure promoting the administration's proposal to spend $53 billion over six years toward construction of a national intercity [[high-speed rail]] network, in furtherance of Obama's goal (outlined in the [[2011 State of the Union Address]]) to extend high-speed rail access to 80% of the American population over a quarter-century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2011/02/08/vice-president-biden-announces-six-year-plan-build-national-high-speed-r|title=Vice President Biden Announces Six Year Plan to Build National High-Speed Rail Network|publisher=White House Office of the Vice President|date=February 8, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2011/POLITICS/02/08/biden.rail.network/index.html|author=Tanya Snyder|publisher=CNN|title=Biden announces $53 billion high-speed rail plan|date=February 8, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704364004576132091951242426|title=Biden Announces $53 Billion Rail-Funding Plan|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|date=February 8, 2011|author=Jared A. Favole & Josh Mitchell}}</ref> Republicans in Congress rejected the proposal, which did not advance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/2011/0208/GOP-critic-calls-Joe-Biden-s-53-billion-high-speed-rail-plan-insanity|title=GOP critic calls Joe Biden's $53 billion high-speed rail plan 'insanity'|newspaper=Christian Science Monitor|date=February 8, 2011|author=Daniel B. Wood}}</ref><ref name=DejaVu>{{cite web|author=Tanya Snyder|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/14/joe-biden-infrastructure-plan-070977|newspaper=Politico|date=November 14, 2019|title=Joe Biden's infrastructure deja vu}}</ref> \n\nDuring his 2020 presidential campaign, Biden has released a $1.3 trillion [[infrastructure]] improvement plan, which would follow up on Obama administration priorities.<ref name=SnyderInfrastructurePlan>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/14/biden-releases-13-trillion-infrastructure-plan-070848|title=Biden releases $1.3 trillion infrastructure plan|date=November 14, 2019|newspaper=Politico|author=Tanya Snyder}}</ref> The plan calls for $50 billion investment in repairs to existing roads and bridges in his first year in office; $10 billion over a decade to transit construction in high-poverty parts of the U.S.; doubling funding for [[Transportation Investment Generating Economic Recovery|BUILD]] and INFRA grants, and more funds for the [[U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]].<ref name=SnyderInfrastructurePlan/> The plan also includes proposals for investments in high-speed rail, public transit, and bicycling,<ref name=DejaVu/> as well as school construction, replacement of water pipes and other water infrastructure, and expansion of rural broadband.<ref name=Pramuk>{{cite web|author=Jacob Pramuk|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/14/joe-biden-releases-infrastructure-plan-and-criticizes-trump.html|title=Joe Biden proposes $1.3 trillion infrastructure overhaul \u2014 and swipes at Trump for inaction|publisher=CNBC|date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> The plan also specifically calls for the rebuilding of the [[North River Tunnels|Hudson River Tunnel]] and the expansion of the [[Northeast Corridor]], as well as rail investments in California and the Midwest and West.<ref name=DejaVu/> Biden proposed funding the plan through tax increases on high-income Americans and corporations; the campaign stated that \"reversing the excesses of the Trump tax cuts for corporations; reducing incentives for tax havens, evasion, and outsourcing; ensuring corporations pay their fair share; closing other loopholes in our tax code that reward wealth, not work; and ending subsidies for fossil fuels\" would provide the revenue for the plan, making it deficit-neutral.<ref name=Pramuk/>\n\n===Trade policy===\nIn the Senate, Biden had a mixed record on [[trade policy]],<ref name=Gussert>{{cite news|author=Andrew Gussert|title=Biden's Record on Trade|url=https://www.iatp.org/news/bidens-record-on-trade|publisher=Institute for Agriculture and Trade Policy/Citizens Trade Campaign|date=September 17, 2008}}</ref><ref name=O'Neill>{{cite news|author=Kevin O'Neill, L. Charles Landgraf, Amy Budner Smith, David J.M. Skillman & Marne Marotta|title=Trading \"America First\" for American Leadership in Trade Policy|date=February 21, 2020|url=https://www.arnoldporter.com/en/perspectives/publications/2020/02/trading-america-first-for|publisher=[[Arnold & Porter]]}}</ref> but consistently supported \"a U.S.-led, [[rules-based international order]] with an emphasis on reducing [[trade barrier]]s and setting global trade standards.\"<ref name=CSISTrade>{{cite news|authors=Jack Caporal & John Hoffner|publisher=Center for Strategic and International Studies|title=What Is Former Vice President Biden's Policy on Trade?|url=https://www.csis.org/analysis/what-former-vice-president-bidens-policy-trade|date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> He voted in favor of the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] (NAFTA), [[Australia\u2013United States Free Trade Agreement|Australia-U.S. Free Trade Agreement]], and [[Morocco\u2013United States Free Trade Agreement|Morocco-U.S. Free Trade Agreement]], but voted against free-trade agreements with [[Singapore\u2013United States Free Trade Agreement|Singapore]], [[Chile\u2013United States Free Trade Agreement|Chile]], the [[Oman\u2013United States Free Trade Agreement|Oman]], and [[Dominican Republic\u2013Central America Free Trade Agreement|the Dominican Republic and Central America]] (CAFTA), viewing their labor and environmental protections as insufficient.<ref name=Gussert/><ref name=O'Neill/> He voted in favor of [[Fast track (trade)|fast track trade promotion authority]] in 1998 and in favor of [[permanent normal trade relations]] with China in 2000.<ref name=Gussert/><ref name=O'Neill/> During the [[Obama administration]], Biden was a strong advocate for the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/267420-biden-coaxes-dems-on-obama-trade-deal|title=Biden coaxes Dems on Obama trade deal|author=Mike Lillis|date=January 28, 2016|website=The Hill}}</ref> arguing that the U.S. withdrawal from the TPP \"put China in the driver's seat\" by allowing it to \"write the [[International trade law|rules of the road]] for the world\" in the absence of U.S. participation.<ref name=O'Neill/>\n\nBiden has been critical of Chinese trade tactics, including \"[[Dumping (pricing policy)|dumping]]\" of steel and Chinese theft of U.S. [[intellectual property]].<ref name=O'Neill/>  He has criticized the [[Trump trade war]] with China for failing to \"resolve the issues at the heart of the dispute\";<ref name=O'Neill/> for the trade war's negative effect on U.S. agriculture and manufacturing;<ref name=O'Neill/> and for Trump's unilateral approach.<ref name=CSISTrade/> Biden also criticized Trump for labeling Canada and the European Union as \"national security threats,\"<ref name=O'Neill/> and has arguing that this undercuts multilateral efforts with allies to combat Chinese trade abuses.<ref name=O'Neill/><ref name=CSISTrade/> He supports pressuring China on environmental issues and supports the [[United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement]].<ref name=O'Neill/>\n\n===Healthcare===\nBiden is a staunch supporter of the [[Affordable Care Act]] (ACA), the Obama administration's signature [[health care reform]] legislation.<ref name=ACA20>Dan Diamond, [https://www.politico.com/story/2019/07/15/joe-biden-health-care-plan-1415850 Biden unveils health care plan: Affordable Care Act 2.0], ''Politico'' (July 15, 2019).</ref><ref>Bill Barrow, [https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/biden-aggressively-defends-the-affordable-care-act Biden aggressively defends the Affordable Care Act], Associated Press (July 15, 2019).</ref> He has condemned the Trump administration's attempts to strike down the ACA in court.<ref name=ACA20/> During his 2020 presidential campaign, Biden has promoted a plan to expand and build upon the ACA, paid for by revenue gained from reversing some Trump administration tax cuts.<ref name=ACA20/> Biden's plan is to create a [[public health insurance option|public option]] for health insurance, with the aim of expanding health insurance coverage to 97% of Americans.<ref name=ACA20/> He does not support [[single-payer health care]] proposals such as [[Medicare for All]].<ref>Katie Glueck, Shane Goldmacher & Glenn Thrush, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/08/us/politics/biden-sanders-campaign-policy.html Now Comes the Hard Part for Joe Biden], ''New York Times'' (April 8, 2020).</ref> Under Biden's proposal, \"no one would be required to pay more than 8.5 percent of their income toward health insurance premiums.\"<ref>Julie Rovner, [https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2019/07/20/743248732/radical-or-incremental-whats-really-in-joe-bidens-health-plan Radical Or Incremental? What's Really In Joe Biden's Health Plan], NPR (July 20, 2019).</ref> Under Biden's plan, all those on the [[Individually purchased health insurance|individual insurance market]] would qualify for tax credits on premiums (a change from existing law, which caps premium tax credits at four times the federal poverty level, or under $50,000 for an independent). To reduce [[Prescription drug prices in the United States|prescription drug prices]], Biden proposes allowing import of prescription drugs and authorizing Medicare to directly negotiate drug prices.<ref name=ACA20/>\n\n===Labor unions===\nBiden was given an 85% lifetime approval rating from [[AFL\u2013CIO]].<ref name=aflcio>{{cite web|title=AFL-CIO Democratic Forum|url=http://www.factcheck.org/elections-2008/afl-cio_democratic_forum.html|publisher=Annenberg Public Policy Center|work=FactCheck|accessdate=4 April 2013|date=August 8, 2007|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130615051059/http://www.factcheck.org/elections-2008/afl-cio_democratic_forum.html|archivedate=June 15, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nBiden was a [[sponsor (legislative)|cosponsor]] of the [[Employee Free Choice Act]].<ref>{{cite web |title=S.1041 - Employee Free Choice Act of 2007 |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/110th-congress/senate-bill/1041/cosponsors |website=Congress.gov |accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Tax===\nBiden opposed the [[Bush tax cuts|George W. Bush administration's tax cuts]] enacted mostly in 2001 and 2003, noting that most of the benefits of the tax cuts went to the very wealthiest U.S. families, and arguing that the cuts did not help working-class and middle-class Americans.<ref name=Umhoefer>{{cite web|author=Dave Umhoefer|url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2012/sep/09/joe-biden/biden-says-500-billion-bush-tax-cuts-wealthy-would/|title=Biden says $500 billion of Bush tax cuts for wealthy would go to 120,000 families|work=PolitiFact|date=September 9, 2012}}</ref> The Obama/Biden administrator advocated keeping the cuts in place for 98% of U.S. taxpayers but letting them expire on income over $250,000 earned by couples (or income over $200,000 for individuals).<ref name=Umhoefer/>\n\nAfter the [[United States elections, 2012|Republicans took control of Congress in the 2010 election]], Biden was designated as the administrator's chief negotiator with Republican&mdash;specifically, [[Senate Majority Leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]]&mdash;regarding the Bush tax cuts, which were about to expire.<ref name=Grunwald>{{cite web|author=Michael Grunwald|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2019/04/30/biden-bipartisan-dealmaking-backfire-226758|date=April 30, 2019|title=Joe Biden Actually Is a Dealmaker. And That Could Be a Problem in 2020|work=Politico Magazine|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The administration opposed extending Bush tax cuts for the wealthy, but also did not want to trigger tax cuts for non-wealthy Americans when the economy was continuing to recover from the [[Great Recession]].<ref name=Grunwald/> The result was a deal: \"Biden and McConnell hashed out a deal that extended all the Bush tax cuts until after the 2012 election, while injecting another $300 billion as an economic stimulus, including a new [[payroll tax]] cut for workers, extended unemployment benefits for victims of the recession and expanded [[tax credit]]s for college students and the poor. By reopening the Senate, the deal also enabled the historic vote to repeal the ban on gays in the military.\"<ref name=Grunwald/>\n\n===Welfare===\nBiden opposes the privatization of [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] and was given an 89% approval rating from the [[Alliance for Retired Americans]] (ARA), reflecting a pro-[[Old age|senior citizen]] voting record. He voted in support of welfare [[Block grant (United States)|block grants]] and supports [[welfare reform]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/Economic/Joe_Biden_Welfare_+_Poverty.htm |title=Joe Biden on Welfare & Poverty |publisher=Ontheissues.org |accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref>{{which|date=March 2019}}\n\n==Foreign policy==\n[[File:Hashim Thaci Joe Biden Fatmir Sejdiu with Declaration of Independence of Kosovo.JPG|thumb|250px|Former rebel leader [[Hashim Tha\u00e7i]] and Biden with [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|Declaration of Independence of Kosovo]]]]\n\n===Africa===\nBiden favored an American deployment of troops to [[Darfur]] during the [[war in Darfur]], saying that 2,500 U.S. troops could stop the violence in the region.<ref name=CFR>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080206202245/http://www.cfr.org/bios/1451/joseph_r_biden_jr.html|title=Joseph R. Biden, Jr. \u2013 Council on Foreign Relations|accessdate=August 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\nBiden opposed to U.S. government funding of [[abstinence-only sex education]] programs in Africa, and in 2007, cosponsored the HIV Prevention Act which would end President [[George W. Bush]]'s mandate that one-third of all funds be earmarked to abstinence-only programs.<ref name=CFR/>\n\n===Middle East===\n==== Iran ====\nAs chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|Senate Foreign Relations Committee]], Sen. Biden has been a prominent voice calling for \"hard-headed diplomacy\" with [[Iran]]. In July 2008, Biden should first engage directly with Iran in the context of talks with the Permanent Five Members of the UN Security Council and Germany, and \"ultimately country-to-country, just as we did with [[North Korea]].\" He also has called for the implementation of \"coordinated [[Sanctions against Iran|international sanction]]s\" on Iran, adding \"we should complement this pressure by presenting a detailed, positive vision for [[Iran\u2013United States relations|U.S.\u2013Iran relations]] if Iran does the right thing.\"<ref name=CFR/>\n\nIn 2007, Biden voted against a measure to declare the [[Iranian Revolutionary Guard Corps]] a terrorist organization. He wrote in December 2007 that \"War with Iran is not just a bad option. It would be a disaster.\" Biden threatened to initiate impeachment proceedings against President Bush if he had started a war with Iran without Congressional approval.<ref name=CFR/> In an interview in September 2008, Biden stated that the Iranian Revolutionary Guard Corps was a terrorist organization and that the Bush administration already had the power to designate it as one. He stated that he voted against the measure out of concern that the Bush administration would misuse the measure to justify a military attack against Iran.<ref name=JTA932008/>\n\nIn early April 2009, Biden told [[CNN]] that he believed that [[Israel]] would not launch a unilateral strike against Iran's nuclear facilities. Biden stated that \"I think (Israel) would be ill-advised to do that. And so my level of concern is no different than it was a year ago.\"<ref>[http://jta.org/news/article/2009/04/07/1004327/biden-israel-wont-hit-iran Biden: Israel won\u2019t hit Iran] by Ron Kampeas, Jewish Telegraphic Agency (JTA), April 7, 2009.</ref>\n\n==== Iraq ====\n[[File:Senator Joe Biden speaks to SEIU 2.jpg|thumb|Joe Biden speaking]]\n\nIn 1990, after [[Ba'athist Iraq|Iraq]] under [[Saddam Hussein]] invaded [[Kuwait]], Biden voted against the first [[Gulf War]], asking: \"What vital interests of the United States justify sending Americans to their deaths in the sands of [[Saudi Arabia]]?\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122049148440397625|title=Biden Was Wrong On the Cold War|last=Wehner|first=Peter|work=The Wall Street Journal|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006022121/http://online.wsj.com/public/article_print/SB122049148440397625.html|archivedate=October 6, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1998, Biden expressed support for the use of force against [[Iraq]] and urged a sustained effort to \"dethrone\" [[Saddam Hussein]] over the long haul.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/inatl/longterm/iraq/stories/iraq111398a.htm | title=Support for U.S. Stance on Iraq Grows | author=Thomas W. Lippman and Bradley Graham |work=The Washington Post | date=November 13, 1998}}</ref> In 2002, as Chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|Senate Foreign Relations Committee]], he stated that Saddam Hussein was \"a long-term threat and a short term threat to our national security\" and that the United States has \"no choice but to eliminate the threat\".<ref name=\"MTP04292007\">{{cite news | url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/18381961 | title=MTP Transcript for April 29, 2007 | author=Tim Russert | publisher=[[NBC News]] | date=April 29, 2007 |page=2| author-link=Tim Russert }}</ref> He also said, \"I think Saddam either has to be separated from his weapons or taken out of power.\"<ref>Meet the Press August 2002 interview with Tim Russert http://www.michaelmoore.com/mustread/index.php?id=1040</ref> Biden also supported a failed resolution authorizing military action in Iraq only after the exhaustion of diplomatic efforts,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/24/us/politics/24policy.html|title=New York Times \u2013 A Democratic Leader on Foreign Policy, In Iraq and the Balkans | work=The New York Times | first=Michael R. | last=Gordon | date=August 24, 2008 | accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref> Biden argued that Saddam Hussein possessed [[Chemical warfare|chemical]] and [[Biological warfare|biological weapons]] and is seeking [[Nuclear warfare|nuclear weapons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=2002_record&docid=cr10oc02-70|title=Congressional Record, Volume 148 Issue 133 (Thursday, October 10, 2002)|website=frwebgate.access.gpo.gov}}</ref> Biden subsequently voted in favor of authorizing the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]].<ref name=\"PATRIOTT01\"/>\n\nIn 2006, about three years into the war in Iraq, Biden believed the original authorization on the use of military force in Iraq in 2002 had been a mistake because [[President Bush (2000)|President Bush]] \"used his congressional authority unwisely.\" Biden argued that the 2002 resolution needed revision because Saddam Hussein had since been deposed and executed, and because the [[Weapon of mass destruction|weapons of mass destruction]] that the Iraq regime supposedly had stockpiled \u2014 a principal justification by the Bush administration for going to war \u2014 were never found. Biden opposed increasing troops in Iraq while favoring the training of Iraqi soldiers to maintain the security of their own country and said U.S. troops should \"responsibly draw down\" and not stay in Iraq indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/cq/2007/02/15/cq_2284.html|title=Biden Favors Revised Iraq War Resolution, Promotes Partition Plan|newspaper=The New York Times|last=Giroux|first=Greg|date=February 15, 2007|access-date=September 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2007, Biden and Sen. [[Sam Brownback]], (R-KS), introduced a [[non-binding resolution]] (originally drafted with [[Leslie H. Gelb]]) to the U.S. Senate regarding Iraq's political future. The measure proposed \"a decentralized Iraqi government based upon the principles of [[federalism]] and advocates for a relatively weak central government with strong [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]], [[Shia Islam|Shiite]], and [[Iraqi Kurdistan|Kurdish]] regional administrations.\"<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/backgrounder/plans-iraqs-future-federalism-separatism-and-partition|title=Plans for Iraq's Future: Federalism, Separatism, and Partition|website=Council on Foreign Relations|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\nKey points include:\n\n#Giving Iraq's major groups a measure of [[autonomy]] in their own regions. A central government would be left in charge of interests such as defending the borders and distributing [[Iraq oil law (2007)|oil revenues]].\n#Guaranteeing Sunnis\u2014who have no oil rights\u2014a proportionate share of oil revenue and reintegrating those who have not fought against Coalition forces.\n#Increase, not end, reconstruction assistance but insist that [[Arab states of the Persian Gulf]] fund it and tie it to the creation of a jobs program and to the protection of [[Ethnic group|minority]] rights.\n#Initiate a diplomatic offensive to enlist the support of the major powers and neighboring countries for a political settlement in Iraq and create an Oversight Contact Group to enforce regional commitments.\n#Begin the phased redeployment of U.S. forces in 2007 and withdraw most of them by 2008, leaving a small follow-on force for security and policing actions.\n\nThe bill passed the Senate by a 75 to 23 margin. Reception from Iraqi politicians and the divided [[Iraqi governments after 2003|Iraqi government]] was mixed. The [[United Iraqi Alliance]] denounced the resolution \"as a U.S. attempt to meddle in Iraqi sovereignty.\" The [[U.S. Embassy in Iraq]] warned that it \"would produce extraordinary suffering and bloodshed.\" President of Iraq [[Jalal Talabani]], who was Kurdish, supported the resolution.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> The Iraqi people did not view the resolution favorably. According to a 2007 poll conducted by the [[BBC]], 9% of the Iraqi people believed in a partitioned Iraq, 28% believed in a combination of regional governments and a federal government, and 62% believed in a unified Iraq with a centralized government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/bsp/hi/pdfs/10_09_07_iraqpoll.pdf|title=Iraq Poll September 2007|last=|first=|date=2007|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, in conversation with [[Katie Couric]], Biden disagreed with President Bush's position on Iraq as the primary war in the War on Terror.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/event/conversation-joseph-r-biden|title=A Conversation with Joseph R. Biden|website=Council on Foreign Relations|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=[The Afghanistan-Pakistan border] is where we must, in my view, urgently shift our focus to the real central front on the so-called war on terrorism, using the totality of America's strength... The original sin was starting a war of choice [the intervention in Iraq] before we finished a war of necessity [the war in Afghanistan]. And we're paying a terrible price for diverting our forces and resources to Iraq from Afghanistan.|sign=Sen. Joe Biden|source=\"A Conversation with Joseph R. Biden\"}}\n\nIn a 2016 interview with [[Richard N. Haass]], President of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]], Biden spoke about changing \"the fundamental approach [America] had to the Middle East\", and that the lesson learned from Iraq is \"the use of force with large standing armies in place was extremely costly, [and] would work until the moment we left.\"<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/event/future-us-foreign-policy-conversation-vice-president-joe-biden|title=The Future of U.S. Foreign Policy: A Conversation With Vice President Joe Biden|website=Council on Foreign Relations|language=en|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n==== Israel ====\nBiden is a self-described [[Zionist]].<ref name=CFR/> During an interview conducted by the U.S. Jewish television cable network [[Jewish Broadcasting Service|Shalom TV]], Biden said, \"I am a Zionist. You don't have to be a Jew to be a Zionist.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ynet.co.il/english/articles/0,7340,L-3586542,00.html |title=Biden in 2007 interview: I am a Zionist \u2013 Israel News, Ynetnews |publisher=Ynet.co.il |date=June 20, 1995 |accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe is highly supportive of the state of [[Israel]] and views Israel as a strategic ally in the Middle East.<ref name=\"NuclearIran\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gulfnews.com/region/Middle_East/10241824.html|title=Israel must come to terms with nuclear Iran}}</ref> He stated that \"the Arab nations have known that there is no daylight between us and Israel.\"<ref>Jennifer Siegel: [http://www.forward.com/articles/presidential-hopeful-slams-bush-for-stance-on-syri/ Presidential Hopeful Slams Bush for Stance on Syria] [[The Jewish Daily Forward]], March 21, 2007.</ref> Regarding support for Israel within the Democratic Party, Biden has stated that the Democrats' support for Israel \"comes from our gut, moves through our heart, and ends up in our head. It's almost genetic.\"<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/pages/ShArt.jhtml?itemNo=755798 Joseph Biden, Democrat], profile at [[Haaretz]], October 23, 2006.</ref> In September 2008, Biden stated \"A strong America is a strong Israel. I have a 35-year record of supporting Israel, and Israel's security is enhanced the stronger America is.\"<ref>[http://www.jewishexponent.com/article/17064/ Candidate Biden: U.S., Israel Joined at the Hip] by Aaron Passman, The Jewish Exponent, September 11, 2008.</ref>\n[[File:Biden at economic forum 2003 crop.jpg|thumb|left|Joe Biden at the [[World Economic Forum]] in Jordan in 2003]]\n\nIn a speech to several hundred older [[American Jews]] at a Florida retirement community, Biden stressed that he and Barack Obama are strongly pro-Israel. Biden stated \"I am chairman of the Foreign Relations Committee. I give you my word as a Biden, I would not have given up that job to be Barack Obama's vice president if I didn't in my gut and in my heart and in my head know that Barack Obama is exactly where I am on Israel. And he is ... I promise you ... we will make [Israel] more secure.\" Biden also criticized the presidency of [[George W. Bush]], stating that \"By any objective fact, Israel is less secure today in the world than it was eight years ago.\"<ref>[http://www.jta.org/cgi-bin/iowa/breaking/110185.html Biden reassures Florida Jews on Israel], Jewish Telegraph Agency (JTA), September 2, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/local/palmbeach/sfl-flpbiden0903pnsep03,0,5617985.story Sen. Joe Biden reiterates support for Israel at two South Florida rallies] by Mark Hollis and Juan Ortega, South Florida Sun-Sentinel, September 3, 2008.</ref>\n\nDuring a conference call to members of the Jewish media on September 3, 2008, Biden stated, in regard to a potential [[Iran\u2013Israel relations|Israeli military strike on Iranian nuclear facilities]], that it \"is not a question for us to tell the Israelis what they can and cannot do, I have faith in the democracy of Israel. They will arrive at the right decision that they view as being in their own interests.\" However, Biden stated that additional diplomatic efforts should be made to help avert the potential need for military action.<ref name=\"JTA932008\">[https://www.jta.org/2008/09/03/culture/biden-on-the-line-israel-needs-to-decide-on-iran-aipac-does-not-represent-the-entire-jewish-commun Biden on the line: Israel needs to decide on Iran, AIPAC does not represent the entire Jewish commun], Jewish Telegraph Agency (JTA), September 3, 2008</ref>\n\nIn September 2008, Biden spoke at the Washington Conference of the [[National Jewish Democratic Council]] (NJDC). Biden stated that \"I've spent 35 years of my career dealing with issues relating to Israel. My support for Israel begins in my stomach, goes to my heart and ends up in my head.\" Regarding Barack Obama's stance on Israel, Biden stated that \"I guarantee you, I would not have joined Barack Obama as his vice president if I had any doubt, even the slightest doubt, that he shares the same commitment to Israel I share.\" Biden also harshly denied a claim by the [[Republican Jewish Coalition]] (RJC) that he once attempted to cut off aid to Israel.<ref>[http://www.jta.org/cgi-bin/iowa/breaking/110520.html Biden at NJDC: Obama supports Israel], Jewish Telegraph Agency (JTA), September 24, 2008.</ref> NJDC director [[Ira Forman]] has praised Biden, stating that \"There is no one you could possibly pick who knows the issues, who is committed to Israel's security and knows Israeli leaders, as much as Joe Biden.\"<ref name=jsf1/>\n\nDuring the [[2008 United States vice-presidential debate|2008 vice-presidential debate]], Biden stated \"no one in the United States Senate has been a better friend to Israel than Joe Biden. I would have never, ever joined this ticket were I not absolutely sure Barack Obama shared my passion.\"<ref name=transcript1>[http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/10/02/debate.transcript/index.html Transcript of Palin, Biden debate], [[CNN]], October 2, 2008.</ref>\n\nIn November 2010, Biden served as the keynote speaker at the General Assembly (GA) of [[Jewish Federations of North America]], where he stated that \"This government will stand with Israel. It's in our own self-interest, beyond it being an absolute moral necessity.\" He also renewed his support for peace talks with the Palestinians, stating that \"There is no substitute for direct face-to-face negotiations leading eventually to states for two people secured\u2014the Jewish State of Israel and the viable independent state of Palestine. That is the only path to the Israeli people's decades-long quest for security, and the only path to the Palestinian people's legitimate aspirations for nationhood.\"<ref>[http://www.cjnews.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=20247&Itemid=86 U.S. VP stresses country\u2019s support for Israel] by Frances Kraft, Staff Reporter, Canadian Jewish News, November 11, 2010.</ref>\n\n===== American Israel Public Affairs Committee =====\nRegarding the [[American Israel Public Affairs Committee]] (AIPAC), Biden defended his right to oppose some AIPAC-backed measures. Biden stated that \"AIPAC does not speak for the entire American Jewish community. There's other organizations as strong and as consequential.\" Biden further stated that AIPAC does not speak for Israel. However, Biden added that \"I've never disagreed with AIPAC on the objective. Whenever I've had disagreement with AIPAC it has always been a tactical disagreement, not a substantive disagreement.\" Following this interview, an AIPAC spokesman praised Biden's leadership efforts on several fronts and stated that \"We look forward to continuing to work with him in the Senate or in the White House.\"\n<ref name=JTA932008/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.com/news/nation/elections/65667|title=Joe Biden: AIPAC doesn't speak for all Jews|last=|first=|date=2008-09-03|website=JewishJournal.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2008, Biden spoke with AIPAC leaders in a conference call. Following the meeting, an AIPAC spokesman stated that \"We had a very warm conversation with Senator Biden today, as we have many times throughout the years, about the importance of the U.S\u2013Israel relationship, and we look forward to continuing to work with him in the future. We had an opportunity to express our appreciation for his strong leadership in support of the U.S.\u2013Israel relationship, and we were pleased to hear Senator Biden reaffirm his desire to maintain his close relationship with AIPAC as we work together to strengthen the special friendship between the two democracies over many years to come.\" An adviser to the presidential campaign of Barack Obama stated that \"Senator Biden expressed his appreciation for AIPAC's important work supporting Israel's security and the U.S.\u2013Israel relationship, and that he looks forward to continuing to work with them as partners on these issues in the future as he has in the past.\"<ref>[http://www.jta.org/cgi-bin/iowa/breaking/110442.html Biden, AIPAC clear the air], Jewish Telegraph Agency (JTA), September 19, 2008.</ref>\n\n===== Israeli-Palestinian conflict =====\n[[File:Vice President Biden is Greeted by Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu (11936086646).jpg|thumb|Biden with Israeli Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]], January 2014]]\nBiden has stated he supports a [[two-state solution]] to the [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian conflict]]. Biden cosponsored the Palestinian Anti-Terrorism Act of 2006 which expressed U.S. support for a two-state solution.<ref name=CFR/><ref>[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/record.xpd?id=109-20060623-38#sMonofilemx003Ammx002Fmmx002Fmmx002Fmhomemx002Fmgovtrackmx002Fmdatamx002Fmusmx002Fm109mx002Fmcrmx002Fms20060623-38.xmlElementm4m0m0m \u201cMr. President, I support the Palestinian Anti-Terrorism Act of 2006...\u201d] ''govtrack.us''.</ref> During the [[2008 United States vice-presidential debate|2008 vice-presidential debate]], Biden stated that the Bush administration's policy with regard to the Middle East had been \"an abject failure\" and pledged that, if elected, he and Barack Obama would \"change this policy with thoughtful, real, live diplomacy that understands that you must back Israel in letting them negotiate, support their negotiation, and stand with them, not insist on policies like this administration has.\"<ref name=transcript1/>\n\nIn a March 2007 interview, Biden was asked about the failure to achieve peace between Israel and the Palestinians. Biden stated that \"Israel's a democracy and they make mistakes. But the notion that somehow if Israel just did the right thing, [the peace process] would work ... give me a break.\" He also stated that \"The responsibility rests on those who will not acknowledge the [[Israel's right to exist|right of Israel to exist]], will not play fair, will not deal, will not renounce terror.\"<ref name=jsf1>[http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/35942/format/html/displaystory.html Joe Biden and Israel are friends who fight] by Eric Fingerhut and Ron Kampeas, Jewish Telegraph Agency (JTA) (reprinted by the Jewish Weekly News of Northern California), August 29, 2008 (retrieved on November 1, 2008).</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Biden spoke at the AIPAC conference where he stated that Israel \"has to work towards a two-state solution\" and called on Israel to \"dismantle existing outposts and allow Palestinians freedom of movement.\" He also called on the Palestinians to \"combat terror and incitement against Israel.\"<ref>[https://nationalpost.com/news/world/story.html?id=1566212 U.S. presses Israel on two-state solution, settlements] by Matt Spetalnick and David Alexander, Reuters (reprinted by the National Post), May 5, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Biden addressed [[J Street]] with a rebuke of [[Netanyahu]]'s leadership in Israel. He said Israeli actions in promoting and expanding [[Israeli settlement|settlements]], legalization of [[Israeli outpost|outposts]], and land seizures are moving Israel toward a \"one-state reality\" and that reality is dangerous. He also said he had opposed Israeli settlements for more than three decades and believed that they are counterproductive to Israel's security. He cited Israeli settlements, as well as Palestinian recourse to the [[International Criminal Court]] as \"damaging moves that only take us further from the path toward peace\". In response to several terrorist attacks on Israeli civilians at the time, Biden called out [[Mahmoud Abbas|President Abbas]] for failing to condemn them. These comments were made while the Obama Administration was negotiating a multi-billion dollar defense deal with Israel, as the U.S. reaffirmed its commitment to the security of its closest Middle Eastern ally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/biden-admits-overwhelming-frustration-with-israeli-govt/|title=Biden admits to 'overwhelming frustration' with Israeli gov't|last=Stoil|first=Rebecca Shimoni|last2=AP|website=timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-israel-statement-idUSKCN11K2CI|title=U.S., Israel sign $38 billion military aid package|date=2016-09-15|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-06-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Libya ====\nIn an event in [[New Hampshire]], Biden spoke about the [[2011 intervention in Libya]]: \"NATO got it right. In this case, America spent $2 billion and didn't lose a single life. This is more the prescription for how to deal with the world as we go forward than it has in the past.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/oct/20/news/la-pn-santorum-kadafi-20111020|title=Kadafi death: Joe Biden says 'NATO got it right' in Libya|last=Memoli|first=Michael A.|date=October 20, 2011|via=LA Times}}</ref> Five years later, in an interview with [[Charlie Rose]], Biden stated he was \"strongly against going to Libya\" due to the instability it would cause within the country. He said, \"My question was, 'OK, tell me what happens.' He's gone. What happens? Doesn't the country disintegrate? What happens then? Doesn't it become a place where it becomes a [[petri dish]] for the growth of extremism? And it has.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/06/21/politics/joe-biden-hillary-clinton-libya/index.html|title=Biden says he predicted Libya instability|last=Producer|first=Kevin Liptak, CNN White House|website=CNN|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n==== Syria ====\n{{Main|Syrian Civil War}}\nIn a 2018 conversation for ''[[Foreign Affairs]]'', Biden described [[Syria]] as \"a classic example of the biggest conundrum that we have to deal with.\" He sees America's current situation in Syria as having \"lost the notion among our European friends that we know what we're doing, that we have a plan.\" He emphasized the necessity of stabilizing Syria, especially in major cities like [[Raqqa]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/event/foreign-affairs-issue-launch-former-vice-president-joe-biden|title=Foreign Affairs Issue Launch with Former Vice President Joe Biden|website=Council on Foreign Relations|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref> Raqqa is in ruins after lengthy battles between [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] and Kurdish forces, the [[Syrian Democratic Forces|SDF]], with assistance from the [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve|U.S.-led coalition]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/10/26/658142688/u-s-plan-to-stabilize-raqqa-and-stop-return-of-isis-doesnt-appear-to-be-working|title='This Is Not Liberation': Life In The Rubble Of Raqqa, Syria|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref> Biden said a multi-billion dollar investment is required to rebuild the city. He believes Iran, not Russia, will be the biggest beneficiaries in the short term, if Syria remains a battlefield. President [[Bashar al-Assad]] will also need to be removed from power, otherwise Syria will never have peace or security.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n{{Quote|text=The nonstarter is, for Russia, the idea that Assad stays in power and continues to control means there\u2019s a guarantee that there will never be peace or security in that country, because so many\u2014so many, you know, bottles have been broken here, man. I mean, there\u2019s no way he can put that together.|sign=Joe Biden|source=\"Foreign Affairs Issue Launch with Former Vice President Joe Biden\"}}\nBiden said there is no uniting principle in Syria, unlike Iraq, hence only certain safe harbors can be established in the region to reduce the number of displaced people and deaths.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n==== Saudi Arabia ====\nBiden criticized U.S. involvement in the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]] and Trump administration's policies toward [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref name=\"foreign-policy\"/> \n\n=== East Asia ===\n\n==== China ====\n[[File:Biden Raises a Toast in Honor of Chinese President Xi.jpg|thumbnail|Biden and China\u2019s leader [[Xi Jinping]] raised a toast at a State Dinner in September 2015]]\n\nIn August 2011, Biden said he\u2019d been impressed with the country since he traveled there decades ago after the two countries normalized relations. \u201cAs I was talking with some of your leaders, you share a similar concern here in China. You have no safety net. Your policy has been one, which I fully understand and I\u2019m not second-guessing, of one child per family, ... it is in our self-interest that China continues to prosper.\u201d Biden said. <ref>https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/joe-biden-has-a-big-china-problem-trump-preps-campaign-assault-on-fall-foe</ref>\n\nIn 2011 and 2012, Biden spent several days with [[Xi Jinping]] and told him U.S. Only Supports Human Rights As \"Political Imperative\".<ref>https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/04/06/born-red Born Red\nHow Xi Jinping, an unremarkable provincial administrator, became China\u2019s most authoritarian leader since Mao.</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Biden described the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]] as an agreement that was as much about [[geopolitics]] as economics. Being part of the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]], he supported the agreement in an attempt to \"rebalance towards Asia\" against a stronger and bolder [[Foreign policy of China|Chinese foreign policy]] in the region.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nIn 2018, Biden said he had spent more time in private meetings with [[Paramount leader]] [[Xi Jinping]] than any other world leader. He believes Xi thinks of [[Russia]] as \"an occasional foil\", and neither countries will come together in an alliance, but both can use each other for benefits relative to America.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nIn May 2019, Biden said in Iowa City, Iowa that \"They\u2019re not bad folks, folks. \u2026 They\u2019re not competition for us.\" \"China is going to eat our lunch? Come on, man,\" the former vice president said in Iowa, drawing the ire of lawmakers like Bernie Sanders and Mitt Romney. <ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/biden-s-comments-downplaying-china-threat-u-s-fires-pols-n1001236</ref>\n\nOn June 4, 2019, Biden tweeted that \"China\u2019s continuing oppression of its own people, especially the abuse and [[Xinjiang re-education camps|internment]] of more than one million [[Uyghurs]], is one of the worst [[Human rights in China|human rights]] crises in the world today. It can\u2019t be ignored.\"<ref name=\"foreign-policy\">{{cite news |title=The Democratic candidates on foreign policy |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020-election/ |work=[[Foreign Policy]]}}</ref> He expressed support for [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|Hong Kong's protests]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Hong Kong protesters are brave 'and the world is watching,' US democrat Joe Biden tells China |url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/06/15/hong-kong-protesters-brave-world-watching-us-democrat-joe-biden-tells-china/ |work=Hong Kong Free Press |date=June 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn June 11, 2019, Biden criticized [[Donald Trump]]'s \"damaging\" [[China\u2013United States trade war|trade war with China]].<ref name=\"foreign-policy\"/> \n\n==== North Korea ====\nBiden favors open dialogue with [[North Korea]] and describes them as a \"[[paper tiger]]\", unable to directly cause harm to America. However, in a June 2007 Democratic debate, he called the situation one of \"the three most important things that the next president is going to have to deal with\", along with [[Iran]] and [[Iraq]].<ref name=CFR/>\n\n=== Europe ===\n==== Russia ====\n[[File:Biden, berlusconi and medvedev.jpeg|thumb|Biden, Russia's President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] and Italy's Prime Minister [[Silvio Berlusconi]] meeting in Italy in June 2011]]\n[[File:VP Biden shakes hands with Petro Poroshenko June 7, 2014.jpg|thumb|Biden shakes hands with Ukrainian President [[Petro Poroshenko]], June 7, 2014]]\nIn 1999, Biden cosponsored a draft resolution condemning Russia's [[Second Chechen War|military campaign]] to crush a [[Chechen Republic of Ichkeria|Chechen separatist insurgency]], the use of indiscriminate force by the Russian army against civilians and violations of the [[Geneva Conventions|Geneva Convention]], and urged a peaceful resolution of the conflict.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.watchdog.cz/?show=000000&lang=1|title=Prague Watchdog - Crisis in Chechnya - www.watchdog.cz|website=watchdog.cz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=sr106-223|title=A resolution condemning the violence in Chechnya. (1999 - S.Res. 223)|website=GovTrack.us}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Biden cosponsored a Senate resolution criticizing Russia for failing to uphold its commitments at the 1999 [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]] (OSCE) Summit, which included agreements on a completed [[14th Army involvement in Transnistria|Russian military withdrawal]] from [[Moldova]]'s breakaway, pro-Russian region of [[Transnistria]]. That resolution also expressed disapproval of Russia's demand for the closure of the OSCE Border Monitoring Operation (BMO), which served to observe border crossings between Georgia and the Russian republics of [[Chechnya]], [[Dagestan]], and [[Ingushetia]]. That bill passed in the Senate.<ref name=CFR/>\n\nBiden introduced legislation in July 2008 urging members of the Group of Eight to \"work toward a more constructive relationship with Russia\", and encouraging Russia to behave according to the [[Group of Eight|G-8]]'s \"objectives of protecting global security, economic stability, and democracy.\" The resolution also called on Russian and U.S. leaders to increase cooperation and funding for the [[Nunn-Lugar program]] and other nonproliferation initiatives. It also emphasized the need for a successor to the [[START I|1991 Strategic Arms Reductions Treaty]]. The resolution passed.<ref name=CFR/>\n\nBiden has voiced concerns about Russia alleged [[democratic backsliding|backsliding on democratic reforms]]. In August 2008, Biden criticized Russia's [[Russo-Georgian War|military action in Georgia]] in support of [[South Ossetia]]n separatists. \"By acting disproportionately with a full-scale attack on [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and seeking the ouster of Georgia's democratically elected President [[Mikheil Saakashvili]], Moscow is jeopardizing its standing in Europe and the broader international community\u2014and risking very real practical and political consequences\", Biden wrote in a ''[[Financial Times]]'' op-ed. Biden urged Russia to abide by the negotiated cease-fire.<ref name=CFR/>\n\nIn a 2018 ''[[Foreign Affairs]]'' op-ed co-written with Michael Carpenter,<ref group=note>Former Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense and Senior Director for the [[Penn Biden center for Diplomacy and Global Engagement]]</ref> Biden described Russia as a [[Kleptocracy|kleptocratic]], [[Right-wing populism|nationalist-populist]] state that considers [[Western democracy]] its existential threat. He acknowledged that the [[Kremlin]] launched coordinated attacks across many domains\u2014military, political, economic, informational\u2014against various Western democratic countries, including [[cyberattack]]s on the [[2016 United States presidential election]] and [[2017 French presidential election]]. As a result of Russia's threat, Biden supports a \"strong response\" with cooperation from America's allies and campaign finance reform that will prohibit foreign donations from flowing into domestic elections.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/2017-12-05/how-stand-kremlin|title=How to Stand Up to the Kremlin|last=Biden|first=Joseph R.|date=2019-04-25|access-date=2019-06-12|last2=Jr|issue=January/February 2018|language=en-US|issn=0015-7120|last3=Carpenter|first3=Michael}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=Western democracies must also address glaring vulnerabilities in their electoral systems, financial sectors, cyber-infrastructure, and media ecosystems. The U.S. campaign finance system, for example, needs to be reformed to deny foreign actors\u2014from Russia and elsewhere\u2014the ability to interfere in American elections. Authorities can no longer turn a blind eye to the secretive bundling of donations that allows foreign money to flow to U.S. organizations (such as \u201cghost corporations\u201d) that in turn contribute to super PACs and other putatively independent political organizations, such as trade associations and so-called 501(c)(4) groups. Congress must get serious about campaign finance reform now; doing so should be a matter of bipartisan consensus since this vulnerability affects Democrats and Republicans in equal measure.|sign=Joe Biden, Michael Carpenter|source=\"How to Stand Up to the Kremlin\"}}\n\nHe also accused [[President trump|President Trump]] of \"[equivocating] on whether [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russia interfered]] in the 2016 election, even after he received briefings from top intelligence officials on precisely how Moscow did it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/2017-12-05/how-stand-kremlin|title=How to Stand Up to the Kremlin|last=Biden|first=Joseph R.|date=2019-04-25|access-date=2019-06-11|last2=Jr|issue=January/February 2018|language=en-US|issn=0015-7120|last3=Carpenter|first3=Michael}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2019 [[Munich Security Conference]], Biden reiterated his opposition to Russian interference in elections and their actions against European neighbors, saying, \"We have to be explicit in our response and make clear to Russia that there's a price to pay for these transgressions of international norms\", and that the U.S. needs to continue to support its [[NATO]] allies, as well as [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and [[Ukraine]] who are not part of NATO, by \"establishing virtually continuous air, land and sea presence on NATO's eastern perimeter.\" He also expressed explicit concern of Russian influence on [[American Politics|American politics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.securityconference.de/en/media-library/munich-security-conference-2019/video/statement-by-joseph-r-biden-jr-followed-by-qa/|title=Statement by Joseph R. Biden Jr. followed by Q&A|website=securityconference.de|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n===The Americas===\n\n==== Central America ====\nAs part of the Obama Administration, Biden supported the Central America Regional Security Initiative (CARSI) to combat [[drug cartel]]s and strengthen law enforcement in [[Central America]]. Between 2008 and 2011, the [[Department of State]] provided $361.5 million to Central American countries. The State Department stated five main goals to CARSI:\n\n# Create safe streets for the citizens in the region.\n# Disrupt the movement of criminals and contraband within and between the nations of Central America.\n# Support the development of strong, capable and accountable Central American governments.\n# Re-establish effective state presence and security in communities at risk.\n# Foster enhanced levels of security and rule of law coordination and cooperation between the nations of the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insightcrime.org/uncategorized/central-america-regional-security-initiative/|title=Central America Regional Security Initiative (CARSI)|last=Crime|first=InSight|date=2011-10-18|website=InSight Crime|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\nWhen Biden met with Central American leaders in [[Honduras]] in 2012, he reiterated the Obama Administration's pledge of $107 million in aid for the region. The Administration would work with Congress to provide the funds under CARSI. These initiatives were part of a larger effort for institutional reform in the region to counter [[Illegal drug trade|drug trafficking]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insightcrime.org/news/brief/no-new-aid-promises-from-biden-in-honduras/|title=No New Aid Promises from Biden in Honduras|last=Looft|first=Christopher|date=2012-03-07|website=InSight Crime|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2012/03/06/world/americas/honduras-biden/index.html|title=Biden visits Honduras amid drug legalization debate|last=Staff|first=By the CNN Wire|website=CNN|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2014 American immigration crisis|2014 Central American child-migrant crisis]], Biden supported a $1 billion economic aid package to affected Central American countries. In an op-ed for ''[[The New York Times]]'', he wrote, \"the security and prosperity of Central America are inextricably linked with our own.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/30/opinion/joe-biden-a-plan-for-central-america.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Joe Biden: A Plan for Central America|last=Jr|first=Joseph R. Biden|date=2015-01-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He also supported further institutional reforms to combat corruption in those countries, so they can provide their people with safer living conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2015/01/vice-president-joe-biden-central-america-aid-package-114755.html|title=Biden urges support for Central America aid package|last=Shutt|first=Jennifer|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\n====Cuba====\nPrior to the [[Cuban thaw]], Biden strongly opposed the [[Fidel Castro]] and [[Raul Castro]] government in [[Cuba]] and supported the continuation of the [[trade embargo]], as well as the democratization of the island in the post-Castro era. In 2006, Biden stated, \"We should be putting together a plan as to how we are going to play a positive role in moving that country, after the Castros are gone, to\u2014more toward democratization and liberalization in their society.\"<ref name=CFR/> However, Biden's support for the trade embargo ended on December 17, 2014, when then President [[Barack Obama]] announced reestablishment of [[Cuba\u2013United States relations|United States\u2013Cuba relations]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Political positions of Barack Obama]]\n* [[Political positions of Mitt Romney]]\n* [[Political positions of Paul Ryan]]\n* [[Political positions of John McCain]]\n* [[Political positions of Sarah Palin]]\n* [[Political positions of Bernie Sanders]]\n* [[Political positions of Donald Trump]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ontheissues.org/Joe_Biden.htm Joe Biden on the Issues]\n*[http://www.4biden.com/ Joe Biden \u2013 democratic candidate 2008]\n*[http://www.4biden.com/news/iraq-a-way-forward/ Iraq: A way forward]\n*[http://whereistand.com/JoeBiden Joe Biden's opinions \u2013 whereIstand.com]\n*[http://www.statesurge.com/members/903-joseph-r-jr-biden-federal Full list of Joe Biden's Legislation \u2013 statesurge.com]\n*[http://www.cfr.org/bios/1451/joseph_r_biden_jr.html Biden's 's position on top foreign policy issues]\n{{Joe Biden}}\n{{United States presidential election, 2008 navigation}}\n{{2020 United States presidential election}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biden, Joe}}\n[[Category:Political positions of the 2008 United States presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:Political positions of the 2020 United States presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:Political positions of United States senators]]\n[[Category:Joe Biden|Political positions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Policies of US politician Joe Biden}}\n{{Joe Biden series}}\n\n[[Joe Biden]] served as the [[Vice President of the United States]] from 2009 to 2017 and in the [[United States Senate]] from 1973 until 2009. He made his [[Joe Biden 2008 presidential campaign|second run]] for [[President of the United States]] in the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 presidential election]] as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], later being announced as Democratic presidential nominee [[Barack Obama]]'s [[running mate]] on August 23, 2008 and elected Vice President on November 4, 2008. On April 25, 2019, Biden announced his [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|third run]] for President of the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/25/us/politics/joe-biden-2020-announcement.html|title=Joe Biden Announces 2020 Run for President, After Months of Hesitation|last=Burns|first=Alexander|date=2019-04-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-12|last2=Martin|first2=Jonathan|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nBiden announced support for a [[public health insurance option]] that would allow Americans to buy into Medicare.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/2020-candidate-joe-biden-backs-medicare-all-policy-you-all-should-have-choice-1409332|title=2020 CANDIDATE JOE BIDEN BACKS MEDICARE PUBLIC OPTION: 'YOU ALL SHOULD HAVE A CHOICE'|website=Newsweek News|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19|date=April 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.advisory.com/daily-briefing/2019/04/30/biden-public-option | title=Biden just weighed in on 'Medicare for All'}}</ref>\n\nBiden has supported [[Campaign finance reform in the United States|campaign finance reform]] including the McCain-Feingold [[Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act]] and banning contributions of issue ads and gifts;<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden on Government Reform|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/joe_biden.htm#Government_Reform|work=Joe Biden on the Issues|publisher=OnTheIssues.org|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> the 1994 [[Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden on Crime|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/joe_biden.htm#Crime|work=Joe Biden on the Issues|publisher=OnTheIssues.org|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]];<ref>{{cite news|last=Biden|first=Joe|title=Assessing the Recovery Act: 'The best is yet to come'|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/op-ed-vice-president-joe-biden-todays-usa-today|accessdate=5 April 2013|newspaper=USA Today|date=February 17, 2010}}</ref><ref name=pbs27jan11>{{cite news|last=Biden|first=Joe|title=Biden: Mubarak Is Not a Dictator, But People Have a Right to Protest|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/politics/jan-june11/biden_01-27.html|accessdate=5 April 2013|newspaper=PBS Newshour|date=January 27, 2011}}</ref> [[tax credit]]s for students;<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden on Education|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/joe_biden.htm#Education|work=Joe Biden on the Issues|publisher=OnTheIssues.org|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> [[Carbon emission trading|carbon emissions cap and trade]];<ref name=energyandoil>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden on Energy & Oil Reform|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/joe_biden.htm#Energy_+_Oil|work=Joe Biden on the Issues|publisher=OnTheIssues.org|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> the increased [[infrastructure]] spending proposed by the Obama administration;<ref name=pbs27jan11/> [[Public transport|mass transit]], supporting [[Amtrak]], bus, and subway subsidies for decades;<ref>{{cite news|last=Hockenberry|first=John|title=Vice President Joe Biden pushes mass transit spending|url=http://www.thetakeaway.org/2009/apr/23/amtrak-joes-new-portfolio/|accessdate=5 April 2013|newspaper=The TakeAway|date=April 23, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130719151247/http://www.thetakeaway.org/2009/apr/23/amtrak-joes-new-portfolio/|archivedate=July 19, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[renewable energy]] subsidies;<ref name=energyandoil/> [[Public Service Loan Forgiveness (PSLF)|student loan forgiveness]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Ensuring That Student Loans are Affordable|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/issues/education/higher-education/ensuring-that-student-loans-are-affordable|work=Issue Fact Sheet|publisher=The White House|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref>{{dead link|date=April 2020}} increased [[progressive tax|taxation of the wealthy]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden on Tax Reform|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/joe_biden.htm#Tax_Reform|work=Joe Biden on the Issues|publisher=OnTheIssues.org|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref> and expanding upon the Affordable Care Act, rather than establishing a Medicare for All system. He supports [[Decriminalization of non-medical cannabis in the United States|decriminalizing cannabis]] on a Federal level and supports a state's right to [[Legalization of cannabis|legalize]] it on a state level,<ref>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden supports decriminalizing marijuana, stops short of calling for legalization|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/16/politics/joe-biden-marijuana-decriminalization/index.html|publisher=cnn.com|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref> and prefers the reduced military spending proposed in the Obama administration's fiscal year 2014 budget.<ref>{{cite web|last=Biden|first=Joe|title=Statement by Vice President Biden On the Bipartisan Debt Talks|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2011/06/23/statement-vice-president-biden-bipartisan-debt-talks|work=Press Release|publisher=The White House|accessdate=6 April 2013|date=June 23, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hellman|first=Chris|title=Competing Visions: President Obama, Rep. Paul Ryan, Sen. Patty Murray, and House Progressives Release Budget Proposals for 2014|url=http://nationalpriorities.org/en/analysis/2013/budget-proposals-2014/|publisher=National Priorities Project|accessdate=3 June 2013|author2=Mattea Kramer|date=April 10, 2013}}</ref> Biden has been publicly in favor of legalizing same-sex marriage since 2012 when he preempted Obama on the subject,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/henrygomez/joe-biden-gay-marriage-equality|title=Marriage Equality Is Joe Biden\u2019s Legacy. He Had To Evolve To Get There.|work=BuzzFeed News|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en}}</ref> and also supports [[abortion rights]], stating that ''[[Roe v. Wade]]'' is the \"law of the land\".<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/10/29/joe-biden-denied-communion/2494025001/|title=Catholic priest says he denied Joe Biden Holy Communion at Mass in South Carolina because of abortion views|author=William Cummings|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=October 19, 2019|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Lifetime ratings==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable floatcenter\"\n|+ Joe Biden's lifetime ratings<ref name=\"Joe Biden, Jr.'s Ratings and Endorsements\">{{Cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Vote Smart}}</ref><ref>[{{cite web|url=http://scorecard.lcv.org/sites/scorecard.lcv.org/files/LCV_Scorecard_2008.pdf |title=LCV Scorecard 2008]}}</ref><ref>[{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2008/08/obama-veep-wa-1/ |title=Obama VP Pick Joe Biden: Good on Civil Liberties, Friendly to Hollywood]|first=Sarah Lai|last=Stirland|date=August 23, 2008|via=wired.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://acuratings.conservative.org/acu-federal-legislative-ratings/?year1=2008&chamber=13&state1=21&sortable=1 |title=ACU Ratings|website=ACU Ratings| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708151908/http://acuratings.conservative.org/acu-federal-legislative-ratings/?year1=2008&chamber=13&state1=21&sortable=1 |archive-date=July 8, 2019 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n! Date\n! Organization\n! Advocacy\n! Lifetime rating\n|-\n| 2008 || [[Alliance for Retired Americans]] || Retirees || 96%\n|-\n| 2008 || [[American Civil Liberties Union]] || [[Civil liberties]] || 86%\n|-\n| 1995 ||[[American Conservative Union]]||[[Conservatism]]|| 13%\n|-\n| 2008 || American Conservative Union ||Conservatism|| 12.67%\n|-\n| 2008-2009 || [[American Federation of Labor and Congress of Industrial Organizations]] || [[Industrial unionism|Unionism]] || 86%\n|-\n| 2008 || [[American Federation of State, County & Municipal Employees]] || [[Public-sector trade union]]s || 86%\n|-\n| 1988-2008 || [[Brady Campaign to Prevent Gun Violence]] || Gun violence prevention || 96%\n|-\n| 2008 || [[Council for Citizens Against Government Waste]] || [[Fiscal conservatism]] || 22%\n|-\n| 2001-2002 || [[Information Technology Industry Council]] || [[Information and communications technology]] || 73%\n|-\n| 2008 || [[League of Conservation Voters]] || [[Environmentalism]] || 83%\n|-\n| 1989-2013 || [[NumbersUSA]] || [[Anti-immigration]] || 21%\n|-\n| 1993-2014 || [[The Lugar Center]] || [[Government operations]] || 58%\n|-\n| 2008 || [[United States Chamber of Commerce]] || [[Business]] || 36%\n|-\n|2002\n|[[National Rifle Association]]\n|[[Gun Rights|Gun rights]]\n|8%<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Vote Smart|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n|-\n|2020\n|National Rifle Association\n|Gun rights\n|D-<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/major-gun-safety-group-endorses-joe-bidens-presidential-69479272|title=Major gun safety groups endorse Joe Biden's presidential bid|last=Jaffe|first=Alexandra|date=March 9, 2020|website=ABC News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Social issues==\n===Affirmative action===\nBiden has supported [[Affirmative action in the United States|affirmative action]] policies.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/18/us/politics/18biden.html Biden\u2019s Record on Race Is Scuffed by 3 Episodes]</ref>\n\n===Capital punishment===\nSince June 20, 2019, Biden opposes capital punishment. Biden supports legislation to eliminate the capital punishment at the federal level, and incentivize states to abolish capital punishment. He supports individuals on death row instead serving life sentences without probation or parole.<ref>[https://joebiden.com/Justice/ Justice]</ref><ref>[https://www.politico.com/story/2019/06/20/joe-biden-death-penalty-1371932 Biden appears to be softening his stance on the death penalty]</ref> Prior to July 20, 2019, he had supported capital punishment. He originally wrote the [[Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act of 1994]]. The Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act of 1994 included Title VI, the Federal Death Penalty Act, creating 60 new death penalty offenses under 41 federal capital statutes,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Federal Death Penalty Act of 1994|url=http://www.justice.gov/usao/eousa/foia_reading_room/usam/title9/crm00069.htm|work=Office of the United States Attorneys|publisher=Department of Justice|accessdate=17 May 2013}}</ref> for crimes related to acts of [[terrorism]], [[murder]] of a federal law enforcement officer, [[civil rights]]-related murders, [[drive-by shooting]]s resulting in death, the use of [[weapons of mass destruction]] resulting in death, and [[carjacking]]s resulting in death. However, he voted against limiting appeals in capital cases and also opposed rejecting racial statistics in death penalty appeals.\n\n===Crime===\nBiden wrote the [[Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act]], which deployed more police officers, increased prison sentences, and built more prisons.  The bill created a financial incentive for jailing people and keeping them there for longer periods of time which had a disproportionate impact on minorities.<ref name=usatoday09302015 />\n\n===Drugs===\nBiden earned a reputation for being a \"drug warrior\", leading efforts in the [[war on drugs]].<ref name=\"RollingStoneDrugs\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-features/joe-biden-weed-war-drugs-candidate-2020-827319/|title=Why Weed Advocates Aren't Happy About Joe Biden's Candidacy|last=Dickson|first=E. J.|date=2019-04-25|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref> During the 1980s [[Crack epidemic in the United States|crack epidemic]] when both Democrats and Republicans were \"tough on crime\", Biden was the head of the [[Senate Judiciary Committee]] that passed numerous punitive measures against drug offenders. In 1986, Biden sponsored and co-wrote the [[Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986|Anti-Drug Abuse Act]] which caused a large disparity between the sentencing of [[crack cocaine]] and [[Cocaine|powder cocaine]] users. Black drug users were more likely than whites to use crack and hence were incarcerated in larger numbers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/4/25/18282870/joe-biden-criminal-justice-war-on-drugs-mass-incarceration|title=Joe Biden didn't just support the war on drugs. He wrote much of the legislation behind it.|last=Lopez|first=German|date=2019-04-25|website=Vox|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/99th-congress/senate-bill/2878|title=S.2878 - 99th Congress (1985-1986): Anti Drug Abuse Act of 1986|last=Dole|first=Robert J.|date=1986-10-17|website=[[congress.gov]]|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref> In 1982, he advocated for the creation of a [[drug czar]], a government official overseeing all anti-drug operations. This led to the establishment of the [[Office of National Drug Control Policy]] by the [[Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988]].<ref name=\"RollingStoneDrugs\"/>\n\nBiden favored increased funding for anti-drug efforts. He frequently criticized President Reagan in this regard,<ref name=\"incarceration\">{{cite news |last1=Stein |first1=David |title=The Untold Story: Joe Biden Pushed Ronald Reagan To Ramp Up Incarceration \u2014 Not The Other Way Around |url=https://theintercept.com/2019/09/17/the-untold-story-joe-biden-pushed-ronald-reagan-to-ramp-up-incarceration-not-the-other-way-around/ |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |work=The Intercept |date=September 17, 2019}}</ref> stating in 1982 that the administration's \"commitment is minuscule in terms of dollars\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Maitland |first1=Leslie |title=U.S. Plans A New Drive On Narcotics |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/10/09/us/us-plans-a-new-drive-on-narcotics.html |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=October 9, 1982}}</ref> He also criticized President George H. W. Bush's anti-drug strategy as \"not tough enough, bold enough or imaginative enough\",<ref name=\"marijuana\">{{cite news |last1=Jaeger |first1=Kyle |title=Where Presidential Candidate Joe Biden Stands On Marijuana |url=https://www.marijuanamoment.net/where-presidential-candidate-joe-biden-stands-on-marijuana/ |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |work=Marijuana Moment |date=April 25, 2019}}</ref> stating that \"what we need is another D-Day, not another Vietnam, not a limited war, fought on the cheap\".<ref name=\"incarceration\" />\n\nBiden advocated for increased use of [[Civil forfeiture in the United States|civil asset forfeiture]] by law enforcement agencies.<ref name=\"marijuana\" /> Biden played a key part in the passage of the Comprehensive Forfeiture Act in 1983, partnering with [[Strom Thurmond]], a conservative Republican. A ''Washington Post'' article described Biden's role in the negotiations: \"He got the Democrats to agree to strengthen forfeiture laws and allow judges to hold more defendants without bail; he persuaded the Republicans to drop such controversial provisions as a federal death penalty, and he made sure Thurmond got most of the credit. Civil liberties groups said the measure could have been far worse without Biden.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=[[Howard Kurtz]]|title=Sen Biden May Try to Talk His Way Into the White House|date=July 28, 1986|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1986/07/28/sen-biden-may-try-to-talk-his-way-into-the-white-house/a19e4497-0d36-4536-95b7-abb38cc17888/|newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Biden supported increased penalties against those caught selling drugs within 1,000&nbsp;feet of schools.<ref name=\"OTI2008\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/2008/Joe_Biden_Drugs.htm|title=Joe Biden on Drugs|website=ontheissues.org|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref> \n\nIn the early 2000s, Biden was critical of [[rave]]s, describing most of them as \"havens\" for use of [[MDMA|ecstasy]] and other illegal drugs.<ref name=Montgomery>David Montgomery, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/2002/07/18/ravers-against-the-machine/d5f8d828-ce3c-471f-a06a-26055a1a8ada/ Ravers Against the Machine], ''Washington Post'' (July 18, 2002).</ref> He was the sponsor of the bipartisan [[Reducing Americans' Vulnerability to Ecstasy Act|Reducing Americans' Vulnerability to Ecstasy (RAVE) Act]] in 2002; the bill's successor, the [[Illicit Drug Anti-Proliferation Act]], was later enacted as part of a [[PROTECT Act|broader 2003 crime bill]] that became law.<ref name=Montgomery/><ref name=Anderson2003>Nick Anderson, [https://web.archive.org/web/20200416045136/https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2003-apr-17-na-rave17-story.html Rave Crackdown Targets Drugs, Not Music, Biden Says], ''Los Angeles Times'' (April 17, 2003).</ref> The legislation, an expansion of the existing 1986 federal anti-\"[[crack house]]\" statute, provided for civil and criminal penalties for event promoters and property owners/managers who [[knowingly]] allowed their property to be used for sale or consumption of drugs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lopez |first1=German |title=How the war on drugs made raves more dangerous |url=https://www.vox.com/2014/10/3/6880715/RAVE-Act-joe-biden-molly-mdma-ecstasy-party-drugs-risks |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |work=Vox |date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> The legislation was opposed by the [[American Civil Liberties Union|ACLU]] and [[electronic dance music]] enthusiasts who viewed it as overly broad.<ref name=Anderson2003/><ref>[https://www.foxnews.com/story/anti-drug-provision-in-amber-alert-concerns-some-businesses Associated Press: Anti-Drug Provision in Amber Alert Concerns Some Businesses], Associated Press (April 30, 2003).</ref>  Responding to criticism, Biden said that the statute would not target law-abiding promoters, saying on the Senate floor: \"The reason I introduced this bill was not to ban dancing, kill 'the rave scene' or silence electronic music&mdash;all things of which I have been accused. In no way is this bill aimed at stifling any type of music or expression. It is only trying to deter illicit drug use and protect kids.\"<ref name=Anderson2003/> Although the law has been rarely used, advocates such as [[Drug Policy Alliance]] and [[DanceSafe]] argue that it discourages event producers from engaging in [[harm reduction]] efforts, and have sought to clarify the law.<ref>[https://www.drugpolicy.org/blog/vice-president-biden-fix-your-rave-act-law-and-save-lives Vice President Biden: Fix Your RAVE Act Law and Save Lives], Drug Policy Alliance (June 14, 2016).</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2008 Democratic Party presidential debates and forums|2007 Democratic primary]] debate at [[Howard University]], Biden acknowledged the consequences of the drug laws he authored and supported in the 1980s. He said there is a need to close the disparity in punishment between crack and powder cocaine users and a \"diversion out of the [[American prison system|prison system]]\" and into treatment.<ref name=\"OTI2008\"/> In 2010, Biden supported the [[Fair Sentencing Act]] which aimed to reduce the disparity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/111th-congress/senate-bill/1789|title=S.1789 - 111th Congress (2009-2010): Fair Sentencing Act of 2010|last=Durbin|first=Richard J.|date=2010-08-03|website=congress.gov|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref>\n\nBiden has a history of opposing [[Legality of cannabis|marijuana legalization]]. As a young senator in 1974 he opposed legalization in contrast to his other more liberal views.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/1974/06/01/joe-biden-kitty-kelley-1974-profile-death-and-the-all-american-boy/|title=Death and the All-American Boy {{!}} Washingtonian (DC)|date=1974-06-01|website=Washingtonian|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref> In 2010 he maintained this position, stating: \"I still believe it's a [[Gateway drug effect|gateway drug]]. I've spent a lot of my life as chairman of the Judiciary Committee dealing with this. I think it would be a mistake to legalize.\"<ref name=\"marijuana\" /> In a 2014 interview, Biden said \"I think the idea of focusing significant resources on interdicting or convicting people for smoking marijuana is a waste of our resources\" but said \"Our policy for our Administration is still not legalization.\"<ref>{{Cite web|author=Zeke J. Miller|url=https://time.com/5330/marijuana-legalization-joe-biden-pot/|title=Vice President Joe Biden Not High on Marijuana Legalization|website=Time|date=February 6, 2014}}</ref> In 2019 a spokesperson for the Biden campaign stopped short of endorsing federal legalization, but said that Biden supports decriminalizing cannabis, expunging prior criminal convictions, allowing states to legalize without federal interference, and [[Removal of cannabis from Schedule I of the Controlled Substances Act|reclassifying cannabis as a Schedule II drug]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Saenz |first1=Arlette |title=Joe Biden supports decriminalizing marijuana, stops short of calling for legalization |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/16/politics/joe-biden-marijuana-decriminalization/index.html |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |work=CNN |date=May 16, 2019}}</ref> On February 6, 2020, Biden's campaign stated his position hasn't changed, and that while Biden would support reclassification, he still would not support lifting the federal ban on marijuana.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/06/joe-biden-legalize-marijuana-111642|title=oe Biden kinda, sorta, almost endorses legalizing marijuana|publisher=Politico|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs Vice President, Biden actively engaged with Central American leaders on issues of drug cartels, drug trafficking, and migration to the U.S. caused by insecurity and drug violence. (See [[Political positions of Joe Biden#Central America|Central America]] below.)\n\n===Education===\nBiden was a major author of the [[Gun-Free School Zones Act of 1990]]<ref name=EdWeek>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.edweek.org/edweek/campaign-k-12/2019/05/Biden-Education-Plan-Title-!.html|newspaper=Education Week|title=Joe Biden's Education Plan: Triple Title I to Boost Teacher Pay and Student Supports|author=Evie Blad|date=May 28, 2019}}</ref> and voted in favor of the [[Improving America's Schools Act of 1994]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/103rd-congress/house-bill/6/all-actions|publisher=Congress.gov|title=H.R.6 - Improving America's Schools Act of 1994, 103rd Congress (1993-1994)}}</ref> He voted in favor of the 2001 [[No Child Left Behind Act]], but in 2007 called for the legislation to be scrapped or overhauled.<ref name=2007Transcript>{{cite news|title=Part I: CNN/YouTube Democratic presidential debate transcript |url=https://www.cnn.com/2007/POLITICS/07/23/debate.transcript/index.html|publisher=CNN |date=July 24, 2007}}</ref> He supports [[class size]] reductions and investment in [[early childhood education]].<ref name=2007Transcript/> During his 2020 presidential campaign, Biden has proposed tripling [[Elementary and Secondary Education Act#Title I|Title I]] funds (which go to low-income schools) to pay for increases in student supports and teacher salaries; doubling the number of school [[School counselor|guidance counselors]], [[school psychologists|psychologists]], [[school social worker|social workers]], and [[school nurses|nurses]]; providing for [[universal prekindergarten]], and fully funding the [[Individuals with Disabilities Education Act]] within a decade.<ref name=EdWeek/> Biden also supports federal infrastructure legislation providing funding for school buildings; allowing high school students to use [[Pell Grant]]s for [[dual enrollment]]; and expanding [[career education|career]] and [[technical education]] through school/[[community college]]/employer partnerships.<ref name=EdWeek/> Biden opposes federal funding for [[for-profit school|for-profit]] [[Charter schools in the United States|charter schools]].<ref name=Glueck/> Biden's plans have been praised by the [[National Education Association]] and [[American Federation of Teachers]],<ref name=Glueck>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden Debuts Education Plan, Then Touts It to Teachers' Union|author=Katie Glueck|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/28/us/politics/biden-education-plan-2020.html|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 28, 2019}}</ref> the major U.S. teachers' unions, which both endorsed Biden in 2020.<ref name=StraussAFT>{{cite web|author=Valerie Strauss|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2020/03/22/aft-countrys-second-largest-teachers-union-endorses-biden-democratic-presidential-nominee/|title=AFT, country's second-largest teachers union, endorses Biden as Democratic presidential nominee|date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=StraussNEA>{{cite web|author=Valerie Strauss|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2020/03/15/national-education-association-nations-largest-union-endorses-joe-biden-president/|newspaper=Washington Post|date=March 15, 2020|title=National Education Association, nation\u2019s largest union, endorses Joe Biden for president}}</ref>  The NEA calling Biden \"a tireless advocate for students, educators, and strong public schools.\"<ref name=StraussNEA/>\n\n===Gun policy===\nThroughout his career, Biden has supported [[gun control]] measures.<ref name=TIME08>{{cite web|title=Joe Biden on Gun Control|website=Time|date=2008|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1849140_1849287_1849789,00.html}}</ref> Although he voted for the 1986 [[Firearm Owners Protection Act]], a bill supported by the [[National Rifle Association]] (NRA) that passed the Senate 79&ndash;15, Biden also authored the 1993 [[federal assault weapons ban]], and is a longtime supporter of [[universal background checks]], and received \"F\" ratings from the NRA while he was in Congress.<ref name=\"NBC News\">{{cite web | title=Biden Voted with NRA When Senate and Nation were Very Different|publisher=NBC News|date=April 24, 2019|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/biden-voted-nra-when-senate-nation-were-very-different-n997311|author=Alex Seitz-Wald}}</ref> \n\nBiden supported the 1993 [[Brady Handgun Violence Prevention Act]], which established five-day waiting periods for handgun purchases and background checks.<ref name=\"NYT93\">{{cite web | title=Senate Roll-Call on the Brady Bill|website=The New York Times|date=November 21, 1993|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/21/us/senate-roll-call-on-the-brady-bill.html}}</ref> He had a central role in the passage of the [[Federal Assault Weapons Ban]] of 1994, which banned the  manufacture, transfer, or possession of certain firearms classified as [[assault weapon]]s (with a [[grandfather clause]] excepting guns owned prior to its implementation).<ref name=\"NPR13\">{{cite web|title=Key Player In '94 Assault Weapons Ban: 'It's Going To Be Much More Difficult' Now|publisher=NPR|date=January 18, 2013|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/itsallpolitics/2013/01/29/169551103/banning-assault-weapons-now-much-more-difficult-than-94-aides-say|work=Morning Edition}}</ref> After the ban expired in 2004, Biden voted in favor of renewing it in a 2007 Senate vote.<ref name=TIME08/> The Obama/Biden administration also unsuccessfully pressed for renewal of the ban.<ref name=\"NPR13\"/> Biden voted against the [[Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act]] (PLCAA) of 2005, which immunizes firearm manufacturers from lawsuits based on gun violence.<ref name=\"TIME08\"/>\n\nAfter the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School massacre]] in 2012, Obama named Biden to lead a task force on gun violence and community safety; the administration proposed [[universal background checks]], resumption of [[Dickey Amendment|public health research on gun violence]], reinstatement of the federal assault weapons ban, but proposals requiring legislative action were killed in the Republican-controlled Congress.<ref>Alan Yuhas & Nicky Woolf, [https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/dec/04/what-happened-president-obama-joe-biden-plan-reduce-gun-violence-sandy-hook-san-bernardino What happened to President Obama's plan to reduce gun violence?], ''The Guardian'' (December 4, 2015).</ref><ref name=UPI2020>[https://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2019/12/14/Joe-Biden-announces-gun-safety-plan-on-anniversary-of-Sandy-Hook-shooting/9761576345302/ Joe Biden announces gun safety plan on anniversary of Sandy Hook shooting], UPI (December 14, 2019).</ref><ref>Matt Viser & Felicia Sonmez, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/joe-biden-releases-gun-plan-that-would-reinstate-assault-weapons-ban-and-establish-a-voluntary-buyback-program/2019/10/01/53d10e28-e4ac-11e9-a6e8-8759c5c7f608_story.html Joe Biden releases gun plan that would reinstate assault weapons ban and establish a voluntary buyback program], ''Washington Post'' (October 1, 2019).</ref> During his 2020 presidential campaign, Biden's proposals on gun violence include universal background checks for gun sales, repeal of PLCAA, reinstatement of the assault weapons ban and a [[High-capacity magazine ban|ban on high-capacity magazines]], and incentives for states to adopt [[red flag law]]s.<ref name=UPI2020/>\n\n===Homeland security===\nAfter the [[Oklahoma City bombing]] on April 19, 1995, a domestic terrorist bomb attack that destroyed the [[Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building]], Biden drafted [[Omnibus Counterterrorism Act of 1995|anti-terrorist legislation]], which was ultimately defeated<!-- This is not the case. \u2018\u2018The Omnibus Counterterrorism Act of 1995\u2019\u2019 was read in the Senate of the United States (twice) on February 10, 1995. This was nearly two months prior to the Oklahoma City bombing which took place April 19, 1995. This was drafted prior to this domestic attack. It was later found to be unconstitutional and invaded upon civil liberties. However, it served as a foundation of the formation of the Patriot Act of 2001. -->. He later claimed publicly on several occasions that the [[Patriot Act|USA PATRIOT Act]], which eased restrictions on the [[Executive (government)|Executive branch]] in the surveillance and detention of those suspected of terrorism or facilitating it, was essentially a duplicate of the [[Omnibus Counterterrorism Act of 1995|anti-terrorist legislation]] he had drafted years earlier.<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://www.tnr.com/article/politics/rhetorical-question | title = Rhetorical Question | journal = The New Republic | author=Michael Crowley | date = October 22, 2001 | accessdate =August 25, 2008}}</ref> Biden supported the PATRIOT Act but voted to limit [[Telephone tapping|wiretapping]] on the bill. He supports implementing the [[9/11 Commission]]'s recommendations to fight terrorists but voted to preserve [[habeas corpus]] rights to the alleged terror suspects serving in [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay]]. In the 1990s, he voted in favor of 36 vetoed military projects and supports efforts to prevent [[nuclear proliferation]]. He was given a 60% approval rating from the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) reflecting a mixed voting record on [[civil rights]] issues. During a debate on November 15, 2007, Biden clarified the PATRIOT Act's effect and his continued support for it and his opposition to [[racial profiling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfr.org/publication/14820/democratic_debate_transcript_las_vegas_nevada.html?breadcrumb=%2Fbios%2F1451%2Fjoseph_r_biden_jr |title=Democratic Debate Transcript, Las Vegas, Nevada \u2013 Council on Foreign Relations|accessdate=August 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn the [[War on Terror]], Biden voted in favor of the [[Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Iraq Resolution of 2002]] and the [[Patriot Act]] of 2001.<ref name=\"PATRIOTT01\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/107-2002/s237|title=H.J.Res. 114 (107th): Authorization for Use of Military Force Against ... -- Senate Vote #237 -- Oct 11, 2002|website=GovTrack.us|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=107&session=1&vote=00313|title=U.S. Senate: U.S. Senate Roll Call Votes 107th Congress - 1st Session|website=[[senate.gov]]|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\n====Senate====\nWhile in the Senate, Biden voted in favor of the [[Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986|1986 immigration bill]] (which passed) and the [[Comprehensive Immigration Reform Act of 2007|2007 comprehensive immigration reform bill]] (which failed).<ref>Amy Sherman, [https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2019/jul/12/weston-pagano/fact-checking-attack-joe-biden-about-immigration-d/ Fact-checking an attack on Joe Biden about immigration deportation, detention votes], ''PolitiFact'' (July 12, 2019).</ref> In a 2007 Democratic presidential primary debate, Biden said that it would be impractical and expensive to deport every unauthorized immigrant in the U.S. and proposed an earned [[path to citizenship]], saying: \"Get a background check on all of them, take out the criminals, get them back, and provide for a means by which we allow earned citizenship over the next decade or so. Folks, being commander in chief requires you to occasionally be practical.\"<ref name=TranscriptJune2007>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/03/us/politics/03demsdebate_transcript.html Transcript: The Democrats' Second 2008 Presidential Debate], ''New York Times'' (June 3, 2007).</ref> Biden voted for the [[Secure Fence Act of 2006]], which authorized and partially funded the construction of fencing along the Mexican border,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=109&session=2&vote=00262|title=Senate Roll Call Votes 109th Congress - 2nd Session|publisher=United States Senate}}</ref> mostly as a means to combat cross-border [[drug trafficking]].<ref name=TranscriptJune2007/> During the same campaign, Biden said that would not allow sanctuary cities to ignore federal law.<ref name=Sanctuary>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/456638-biden-once-called-for-a-ban-on-sanctuary-cities-where-does-he-stand-now|title=Biden once called for a ban on sanctuary cities; Where does he stand now?|first=Rafael|last=Nam|date=August 8, 2019|website=The Hill}}</ref> In 2007, Biden said that illegal immigration would not stop unless U.S. employers stopped hiring undocumented workers, saying: \"All the rest is window dressing.\"<ref>Ilene Rosenblum, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/nation/documents/immigration_primer_060807.html Issues and Influentials in the Immigration Reform Debate], ''Washington Post'' (June 28, 2007).</ref>\n\n====Vice presidency====\nAs vice president, Biden supported the [[Border Security, Economic Opportunity, and Immigration Modernization Act of 2013|2013 bipartisan comprehensive immigration reform bill]], a bill crafted by the [[Gang of Eight (immigration)|Gang of Eight]] (four Democratic, four Republican senators) that would have created a 13-year pathway to citizenship for unauthorized immigrants with security checks, devoted unprecedented resources to border security, created a new work visa program, and established a mandatory employment verification system to ensure that persons hired are authorized to work in the U.S.  As [[president of the Senate]], Biden personally presided over the Senate when the bill passed 68&ndash;32.<ref>Seung Min Kim, [https://www.politico.com/story/2013/06/immigration-bill-2013-senate-passes-093530 Senate passes immigration bill], ''Politico'' (June 27, 2013).</ref><ref>Matt Vasilogambros, [https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2013/06/with-joe-biden-at-the-senate-immigration-reform-is-passed/438090/ With Joe Biden at the Senate, Immigration Reform Is Passed], ''The Atlantic''/''National Journal'' (June 27, 2013).</ref> The legislation failed, however, in the Republican-controlled House of Representatives.<ref>Alec MacGillis, [https://www.propublica.org/article/washington-congress-immigration-reform-failure How Washington Blew Its Best Chance to Fix Immigration], ''ProPublica'' (September 15, 2016).</ref>\n\n====2020 proposals====\nDuring his 2020 presidential campaign, Biden issued his \"Biden Plan for Securing Our Values as [[a Nation of Immigrants]],\" in which he pledged to \"secure our border, while ensuring the dignity of migrants and upholding their legal [[Right to asylum|right to seek asylum]]. ... enforce our laws without targeting communities, violating due process, or tearing apart families,\" \"ensure our values are squarely at the center of our immigration and enforcement policies,\" and create a \"fair and humane immigration system.\"<ref name=BidenImmigration>[https://joebiden.com/immigration/ The Biden Plan for Securing Our Values as a Nation of Immigrants], Biden for President (accessed April 15, 2020).</ref> Biden's proposals would undo Trump's immigration policies,<ref name=KaplanGlueck>Thomas Kaplan & Katie Glueck, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/11/us/politics/joe-biden-immigration.html Joe Biden Calls for Immigration Overhaul, Acknowledging 'Pain' From Deportations], ''New York Times'' (December 11, 2019).</ref><ref name=NagleImmigration>Molly Nagle, [https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/biden-seeks-undo-trumps-immigration-policies-100-days/story?id=67663203 Biden seeks to undo several Trump immigration policies in first 100 days in new immigration proposal], ABC News (December 12, 2019).</ref> which Biden has criticized as immoral, inhumane, ineffective, economically damaging, and unconstitutional.<ref name=BidenImmigration/>  He pledged a reversal of the Trump administration's [[Trump administration family separation policy|family separation policy]], travel/refugee bans, and severe restrictions on [[Right to asylum|asylum]],<ref name=BidenImmigration/><ref name=NagleImmigration/> calling these policies \"cruel and senseless\" and \"un-American.\"<ref name=BidenImmigration/> If elected, he pledges to reverse Trump's [[public charge rule]] and \"so-called [[National Emergency Concerning the Southern Border of the United States|National Emergency]],\" which diverted money from the [[Defense Department]] to construct a [[Trump wall|wall on the U.S.-Mexico border]].<ref name=BidenImmigration/>  Biden criticized Trump's promotion of a wall solution to border security, noting that smuggling through legal [[Ports of entry|ports of entry]], rather than simple illicit border-crossing, is the dominant method by which [[Illegal drug trade|illicit drugs]] enter the U.S., and that \"sophisticated criminal organizations\" can easily that circumvent physical barriers through \"border tunnels, semi-submersible vessels, and aerial technology.\"<ref name=BidenImmigration/> Biden has called for better security along the border and at ports of entry through technology and infrastructure (such as \"cameras, sensors, large-scale x-ray machines, and fixed towers\") as well as through improved coordination between federal agencies, as well as Mexican and Canadian authorities.<ref name=BidenImmigration/>  \n\nDuring his 2020 campaign, Biden proposed a \"surge\" of humanitarian resources to the border and restoration of the [[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals]] (DACA) program for [[Undocumented youth in the United States|undocumented youth raised in the United States]] (the \"[[DREAM Act|Dreamers]]\").<ref name=BidenImmigration/> As a longer-term goal, Biden said he supported a [[path to citizenship]] for undocumented immigrants currently in the United States.<ref name=KaplanGlueck/><ref name=NagleImmigration/> Biden also pledged to create a program to allow U.S. military veterans deported by the Trump Administration to return to the United States.<ref name=BidenImmigration/> He supports evidence-based alternatives to prolonged [[immigration detention]],<ref name=BidenImmigration/> and a ban on for-profit detention centers.<ref name=KaplanGlueck/> Biden does not support abolition of [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] (ICE), as some on the left wing have called for, but said that his administration would ensure that ICE and [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] officers \"abide by professional standards and are held accountable for inhumane treatment.\"<ref name=KaplanGlueck/> Biden does not support the decriminalization of [[Illegal entry|unauthorized border-crossing]],<ref name=KaplanGlueck/> but pledged to restore \"sensible enforcement priorities\" that focus deportation and other enforcement efforts on persons convicted of serious crimes.<ref name=NagleImmigration/><ref name=BidenImmigration/> rather than people \"who have lived, worked, and contributed to our economy and our communities for decades.\"<ref name=BidenImmigration/> To address a backlog in the immigration courts, Biden proposed a doubling of the number of [[Immigration Judge (United States)|immigration judges]] and interpreters.<ref name=KaplanGlueck/> Biden also opposes Trump's attempts to withhold federal grant funding from sanctuary cities.<ref name=Sanctuary/>\n\nRegarding [[Migrant crisis|migrant crises]], Biden's 2020 immigration policy emphasized a need to address the root causes of migration from the  [[Central America]]'s [[Northern Triangle]] of [[El Salvador]], [[Guatemala]], and [[Honduras]], such as endemic instability, corruption, gang violence and gender-based violence, and a lack of the [[rule of law]]. Biden pledged to update the [[Central American Minors Program]] and advance humanitarian aid, stability, and economic development in the region. He also stated that he would use the [[Temporary Protected Status]] program for persons whose countries of origin suffer from violence or unsafe conditions.<ref name=BidenImmigration/><ref name=NagleImmigration/>\n\n===Internet privacy and file sharing===\nIn 2006, in its Technology Issues Voter's Guide, [[CNET]].com gave Biden a score of 37.5% on his Senate voting record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/2009-1040-6130830.html?hhTest=1|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120711015612/http://news.cnet.com/2009-1040-6130830.html?hhTest=1|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-07-11|title=Technology voter guide 2006 \u2013 Mapping Congress' voting records | publisher= CNET News.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Overview of Senate voting scores |url=http://i.i.com.com/cnwk.1d//i/ne/sr06/tech_vote_guide_06/senate-by-score.xls |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111114023657/http://i.i.com.com/cnwk.1d//i/ne/sr06/tech_vote_guide_06/senate-by-score.xls |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-11-14 |work=Cnet |format=xls}}</ref> Biden was a co-sponsor of the [[Platform Equality and Remedies for Rights Holders in Music Act of 2007]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/senators-aim-to-restrict-net-satellite-radio-recording/|title=Senators aim to restrict Net, satellite radio recording|first=Anne|last=Broache|website=CNET}}</ref> \n\nBiden also sponsored two bills, the [http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d102:s.00266: Comprehensive Counter-Terrorism Act] (SB 266) and the [http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d102:s.00618: Violent Crime Control Act] (SB 618), both of which contained language seen as effectively banning [[encryption]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/cnet/20080824/tc_cnet/83011357831002416338 |title=Joe Biden's pro-RIAA, pro-FBI tech voting record \u2013 Yahoo! News |accessdate=August 25, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828193707/http://news.yahoo.com/s/cnet/20080824/tc_cnet/83011357831002416338 |archivedate=August 28, 2008 }}</ref> ''Crypto'' notes Biden wrote that language into the text of SB 266.<ref>{{cite book | last=Levy | first=Steven | authorlink=Steven Levy | title=Crypto: How the Code Rebels Beat the Government, Saving Privacy in the Digital Age | year=2001 | publisher=Viking | location=New York | isbn=0-670-85950-8 | page=195}}</ref> [[Phil Zimmermann]], the creator of [[Pretty Good Privacy]], has said it was SB 266 that \"led [him] to publish PGP electronically for free that year, shortly before the measure was defeated after vigorous protest by civil libertarians and industry groups.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philzimmermann.com/EN/essays/index.html |title=Phil Zimmermann on PGP |accessdate=August 25, 2008}}</ref> He later stated in a ''Slashdot'' article that he was not specifically criticizing Biden, that he would consider the Senator's \"whole body of work\" when considering whether to vote for him on the Democratic ticket in 2008, and that \"considering the disastrous erosion in our privacy and civil liberties under the (Bush) administration, I feel positively nostalgic about Biden's quaint little non-binding resolution of 1991\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=08/08/26/2126214 |title=Phil Zimmermann on Sen. Biden and 2008 Democratic ticket |accessdate=June 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===LGBTQ issues===\nWhile in the Senate, Biden voted in 1993 for a broad defense bill that included the \"[[don't ask, don't tell]]\" law on [[Sexual orientation in the United States military|LGBT service in the U.S. military]], after voting to remove the amendment.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=Becker>{{Cite news|agency=Reuters|title=Biden's LGBTQ record draws scrutiny at Iowa presidential forum|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-biden/bidens-lgbtq-record-draws-scrutiny-at-iowa-presidential-forum-idUSKBN1W603A|authors=Amanda Becker & Trevor Hunnicutt|date=September 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Epstein|first=Reid J.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/us/politics/lgbt-forum-2020.html|title=Joe Biden Has Tense Exchange Over L.G.B.T.Q. Record|date=2019-09-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|last2=Lerer|first2=Lisa|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> As vice president, Biden supported the [[Don't Ask, Don't Tell Repeal Act of 2010]], which repealed the prohibition on open service by gay, lesbian, and bisexual people in the U.S. military.<ref name=Becker/>\n\nIn 1996, Biden voted in favor of the [[Defense of Marriage Act]] which prohibited the federal government from recognizing any same-sex marriage, barring individuals in such marriages from equal protection under federal law, and allowing states to do the same.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=104&session=2&vote=00280|title=U.S. Senate: U.S. Senate Roll Call Votes 104th Congress - 2nd Session|website=senate.gov|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref> In the Senate, Biden was an outspoken critic of congressional Republicans' efforts in 2000s to adopt a [[Federal Marriage Amendment|constitutional amendment to prohibit same-sex marriage]]; in arguing against the proposal in 2004, Biden cited his position that same-sex marriage was an issue for states to decide.<ref name=\":0\" /> In a May 2012 ''[[Meet the Press]]'' interview, Vice President Biden reversed his previous position and publicly supported [[marriage equality]], saying he was \"absolutely comfortable with the fact that men marrying men, women marrying women, and heterosexual men and women marrying another are entitled to the same exact rights, all the civil rights, all the civil liberties. And quite frankly, I don't see much of a distinction beyond that.\"<ref name=\"Stein0506\">{{cite news |last=Stein |first=Sam |title=Joe Biden Tells 'Meet The Press' He's 'Comfortable' With Marriage Equality |publisher=Huffington Post |date=May 6, 2012 |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/06/vice-president-biden-gay-marriage_n_1489235.html |accessdate=Aug 20, 2012}}</ref> Prior to Biden's statement on ''Meet the Press'', the Obama administration endorsed [[civil union]]s, but not same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Barbaro|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/07/us/politics/biden-expresses-support-for-same-sex-marriages.html|newspaper=New York Times|title=A Scramble as Biden Backs Same-Sex Marriage|date=May 7, 2012}}</ref> Biden's decision reportedly forced Obama's hand, pressuring Obama to accelerate his own public shift to support same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news|title=W.H.: Biden forced Obama's hand|author=Glenn Thrush & Jennifer Epstein|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2012/05/obama-expected-to-speak-on-gay-marriage-076103|newspaper=Politico|date=May 10, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Edward-Isaac Dovere|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2014/04/joe-biden-gay-marriage-white-house-response-105744|title=Book: W.H. scrambled after Biden gay marriage comments|newspaper=Politico|date=April 16, 2014}}</ref> In 2013, Section 3 of DOMA was ruled unconstitutional and partially struck down in ''[[United States v. Windsor]]''. The Obama Administration did not defend the law and congratulated Windsor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/supreme-court/2013/06/26/f0039814-d9ab-11e2-a016-92547bf094cc_story.html|title=Supreme Court strikes down key part of Defense of Marriage Act|last=Barnes|first=Robert|date=June 26, 2013|website=The Washington Post|access-date=}}{{paywall}}</ref> \n\nBiden supported the U.S. Supreme Court's 5&ndash;4 ruling in ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' (2015), which held that same-sex couples have a federal constitutional right to marry. Biden issued a statement saying that the ruling reflected a principle that \"all people should be treated with respect and dignity\u2014and that all marriages, at their root, are defined by unconditional love.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2015/06/26/statement-vice-president-supreme-court-decision-obergefell-v-hodges|title=Statement by the Vice President on the Supreme Court Decision in Obergefell v. Hodges|date=June 26, 2015|publisher=White House Office of the Vice President}}</ref> In an event with the group [[Freedom to Marry]], Biden described the decision as \"the civil rights movement of our generation\" and as consequential as ''[[Brown v. Board of Education]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/247482-biden-compares-gay-marriage-ruling-to-brown-v-board-of-education|newspaper=The Hill|date=July 10, 2015|title=Biden compares gay marriage ruling to 'Brown v. Board of Education'|author=Jordan Fabian}}</ref> \n[[Jim Obergefell]], the lead plaintiff in the case, endorsed Biden's 2020 presidential run, as did other LGBT leaders.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonblade.com/2020/03/02/jim-obergefell-lead-plaintiff-in-marriage-case-latest-to-endorse-joe-biden/|title=Jim Obergefell, lead plaintiff in marriage case, latest to endorse Joe Biden|date=March 2, 2020|newspaper=Washington Blade}}</ref> \n\nBiden supports the [[Equality Act (United States)|Equality Act]], proposed federal legislation that would extend the nondiscrimination protections of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]] to cover discrimination \"on the basis of sex, sexual orientation, gender identity, or pregnancy, childbirth, or a related medical condition of an individual, as well as because of sex-based stereotypes.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/joe-biden-matthew-shepard-mom-civil-rights-act-includes-lgbtq_n_5d9fc151e4b087efdbab8bd9|work=HuffPost|date=October 10, 2019|author=Sanjana Karanth}}</ref> \n\nDuring his 2020 presidential campaign, Biden vowed to support legislation and action to prohibit [[transgender inequality|discrimination against transgender people]] and to combat [[hate crimes]] targeting LGBT persons, including [[Violence against LGBT people|violence and harassment against transgender people]].<ref name=HRC>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrc.org/resources/joe-biden-on-lgbtq-issues|title=Presidential Candidate Joe Biden on LGBTQ Issues|publisher=Human Rights Campaign}}</ref><ref name=Kelly>{{Cite news|author=Caroline Kelly|title=Biden: Fastest way to end transgender violence 'is to end the Trump administration'|publisher=CNN|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/01/politics/biden-lgbtq-comments-hrc-speech/index.html|date=June 1, 2019}}</ref> He has criticized Republicans, and particularly Vice President [[Mike Pence]], for using \"religious freedom as an excuse to license discrimination.\"<ref name=HRC/><ref name=Kelly/> He supports the Safe Schools Improvement Act, a proposed anti-bullying law.<ref name=HRC/>\n\n===Religious faith ===\nAt a November 2011 campaign event, in response to a question about how Biden viewed Mitt Romney's Mormon faith in November 2011, Biden said, \"I find it preposterous that in 2011 we're debating whether or not a man is qualified or worthy of your vote based on whether or not his religion ... is a disqualifying provision.  It is not. It is embarrassing and we should be ashamed, anyone who thinks that way.\"<ref name=Defends>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/11/04/us-usa-campaign-biden-romney-idUSTRE7A371Q20111104|title=Biden defends Romney's Mormon faith|agency=Reuters|date=November 4, 2011}}</ref> Biden cited the anti-Catholic prejudice encountered by [[John F. Kennedy]] in the [[1960 United States presidential election|1960 presidential election]].<ref name=Defends/>\n\n===Women's rights===\nIn 1994, Biden drafted the [[Violence Against Women Act]]. This law provided $1.6 billion to enhance investigation and prosecution of the violent crime perpetrated against women, increased pre-trial detention of the accused, provided for automatic and mandatory restitution of those convicted, and allowed civil redress in cases prosecutors chose to leave unprosecuted.\n\nThe [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] struck down portions of the VAWA on Constitutional grounds in ''[[United States v. Morrison]]''.\n\nBiden has said, \"I consider the Violence Against Women Act the single most significant legislation that I've crafted during my 35-year tenure in the Senate. Indeed, the enactment of the Violence Against Women Act in 1994 was the beginning of a historic commitment to women and children victimized by [[domestic violence]] and [[sexual assault]]. Our nation has been rewarded for this commitment. Since the Act's passage in 1994, domestic violence has dropped by almost 50%.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://biden.senate.gov/issues/issue/?id=975b0cf4-ce25-42cc-b63d-072fb81e8618 |title=Senator Joe Biden \u2013 Senator for Delaware: Issues \u2013 Domestic Violence |accessdate=September 8, 2008 |publisher=US Senate |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822144642/http://biden.senate.gov/issues/issue/?id=975b0cf4-ce25-42cc-b63d-072fb81e8618 |archivedate=August 22, 2008}}</ref> He has also said that the Act \"empower[s] women to make changes in their lives, and by training police and prosecutors to arrest and convict abusive husbands instead of telling them to take a walk around the block\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://biden.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/BidenRecordWomen.pdf |title=Senator Joe Biden Stands Up For Women |accessdate=September 8, 2008 |publisher=US Senate |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080730224418/http://biden.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/BidenRecordWomen.pdf |archivedate=July 30, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Biden told a group of students that having sex with a woman while she is drunk, is rape.<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/video_and_audio/headlines/39734868/ex-vp-joe-biden-tells-students-if-she-s-drunk-it-s-rape</ref>\n\nThere has been controversy regarding then-Senator Biden's actions during the [[Anita Hill]] hearings of 1991. At the time Biden was serving as chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]] during the nomination of Republican judge [[Clarence Thomas]] who was nominated by then-President [[George H. W. Bush]]. During the nomination process, Judge Thomas was accused of a consistent pattern of sexual harassment.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dovere |first1=Edward-Isaac |title=Biden's 'Anita' problem |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2015/09/biden-anita-hill-women-senate-clarence-thomas-213864 |accessdate=9 January 2019 |work=POLITICO |language=en}}</ref> During the hearing, Biden referred to the accusations by Hill as being \"he said, she said\"<ref>{{cite news |title=How Joe Biden's 1991 comments about the FBI and Anita Hill are now being used against Democrats \u2014 and Biden's response in 2018 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/history/2018/09/26/how-joe-bidens-comments-about-fbi-anita-hill-are-now-being-used-against-democrats |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref> and as a \"character assassination\".<ref>{{cite news |title=As he considers 2020, Joe Biden airs regrets of Anita Hill hearings |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2018/09/21/considers-joe-biden-airs-regrets-anita-hill-hearings/6JjWMfOg2Dr6lLqip5XmJI/story.html |work=The Boston Globe |language=en}}</ref> In 2017, Biden issued an apology to Anita Hill, stating: \"Let\u2019s get something straight here, I believed Anita Hill. I voted against Clarence Thomas... I am so sorry that she had to go through what she went through. Think of the courage that it took for her to come forward.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2017/11/anita-hill-responds-to-joe-bidens-apology.html|title=Anita Hill Responds to Joe Biden's Apology|first=Madeleine Aggeler|last=The Cut|website=The Cut}}</ref>\n\n====Abortion ====\n\n; ''Roe v. Wade''\n\nAccording to Jamal Brown, Biden's press secretary, said that when Biden arrived in the Senate in 1973 he thought ''[[Roe v. Wade]]'' was wrongly decided, but now \"firmly believes that ''Roe v. Wade'' is the law of the land and should not be overturned\". In 1981, he voted for a failed constitutional amendment allowing states to overturn ''Roe v. Wade''. In 1982, he voted against the same failed constitutional amendment allowing states to overturn ''Roe'', and in 2006, he stated in an interview that \"I do not view abortion as a choice and a right. I think it's always a tragedy[.]\"<ref name=\"USA Today\" /> He now says he would consider codifying the ''Roe'' precedent into federal law in case the ruling is overturned by the United States Supreme Court.<ref name=\"Bidenabortion\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/biden-s-long-evolution-abortion-rights-still-holds-surprises-n1013846|title=Biden's long evolution on abortion rights still holds surprises|publisher=NBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"Overnight Health Care\">{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/overnights/447190-overnight-health-care-trump-admin-cutting-services-for-migrant|title=Overnight Health Care: Biden infuriates abortion-rights groups with stance on Hyde Amendment - Trump tightens restrictions on fetal tissue research - Democrats plan event to scrutinize Trump's mental health|first=Peter|last=Sullivan|date=June 5, 2019|website=The Hill}}</ref> He pledged that he would appoint [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] justices who shared his beliefs in upholding ''Roe''.<ref name=\"prochoiceamerica\">{{cite web |url=http://www.prochoiceamerica.org/elections/statements/biden.html |title=Senator Joe Biden (D-DE) |work=[[NARAL Pro-Choice America]] |accessdate=October 1, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213210038/http://www.prochoiceamerica.org/elections/statements/biden.html |archivedate=December 13, 2007}}</ref>\n\n; Federal abortion funding\n\nFrom 1976 to June 5, 2019, Biden supported the [[Hyde Amendment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/05/us/politics/biden-hyde-amendment.html|title=Biden Still Backs Hyde Amendment, Which Bans Federal Funds for Abortions|first=Katie|last=Glueck|date=June 5, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/94-1976/s962|title=TO AMEND H.R. 14232... -- Senate Vote #962 Jun 28, 1976|website=GovTrack.us}}</ref> On June 6, 2019, Biden reversed his support and now supports repealing the Hyde Amendment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/06/us/politics/joe-biden-hyde-amendment.html|title=Joe Biden Denounces Hyde Amendment, Reversing His Position|first=Katie|last=Glueck|date=June 6, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> In 1981, he voted to end federal funding for abortion for victims of rape and incest.<ref name=\"Bidenabortion\"/> Biden previously supported the [[Mexico City policy]], but now supports repealing it.<ref name=\"Overnight Health Care\"/>\n\n; Post-viability abortion\n\nIn 2003, Biden voted for the \"[[Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=108&session=1&vote=00402|title=U.S. Senate: U.S. Senate Roll Call Votes 108th Congress - 1st Session|website=senate.gov}}</ref> In 2007, he opposed the [[United States Supreme Court]] ruling in the case of ''[[Gonzales v. Carhart]]'' which upheld the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003. He defended his opposition, saying he opposed the court's reasoning for the ruling, not the decision itself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ontheissues.org/2020/Joe_Biden_Abortion.htm|title=Joe Biden on Abortion|website=ontheissues.org}}</ref>\n\n==Economic issues==\n[[File:Joe Biden - World Economic Forum Annual Meeting Davos 2005 Portrait.jpg|thumb|Joe Biden at the [[World Economic Forum]] in [[Davos]], [[Switzerland]]]]\n\n===Agriculture and rural issues===\nBiden supported the [[Food, Conservation, and Energy Act of 2008|2008 farm bill]], calling it a \"responsible compromise.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828213948/http://biden.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/BidenOnAgriculture.pdf |title=Senator Joe Biden on Agriculture|publisher=United States Senate, Office of Senator Joe Biden}}</ref> When he chaired the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, Biden identified agricultural development and global [[food prices]] as major issues.<ref name=BidenAgSenate/>\n\nWhile in the Senate, Biden called for strong action against [[invasive species]], citing the economic and environmental risks associated with them, including displacement of native shipping, introduction of disease, and interference with shipping.<ref name=BidenAgSenate/>\n\nIn the Senate, Biden paid particular attention to issues affecting the [[poultry industry]], which is economically important to Delaware, especially in the [[Delmarva peninsula]].<ref name=BidenAgSenate/> In the 1990s, Biden criticized the Russian government for threatening to ban imported U.S. chicken,<ref name=BidenAgSenate/> and in 2008 criticized the Russian government for banning imports of chicken from 19 poultry processing plants in the United States, Biden stated that \"Russia is once again using [[Non-tariff barriers to trade|non-tariff barriers]] as an excuse to close its markets to American poultry. ... Russia has repeatedly shown that it is not ready to abide by the rules of international trade.\"<ref name=Chicken>{{cite press release|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080902034113/http://biden.senate.gov/press/press_releases/release/?id=844009C2-8BBD-4DE9-888B-5CC6FF071114|title=Biden Issues Statement on News of Russia's Ban on Chicken Imports|date=August 30, 2008|publisher=United States Senate, Office of Senator Joe Biden}}</ref> Biden described the Russian action as \"part of a bigger picture in which Russia has failed to behave as a responsible member in the [[international community]]\" can called for the U.S. to block Russia's application to join the [[World Trade Organization]].<ref name=Chicken/> Biden also worked to promote funding to research [[avian influenza]].<ref name=BidenAgSenate/>\n\nDuring his 2020 presidential campaign, Biden has outlined a rural and agricultural policies broadly similar to those of the Obama administration. The plan aims to obtain net-zero emissions for agriculture (making the U.S. the first nation to do so) via incentives and permitting farmers to join [[carbon market]]s. The plan also calls for changes in trade policy to encourage U.S. agriculture exports; expansion of [[broadband Internet]] in rural areas; [[renewable energy]] investment; promotion of [[local food|local]] and regional food; and an expansion of the USDA Conservation Stewardship Program to encourage farmers to adopt [[carbon sequestration]] and other environmental practices.<ref name=Evich>{{Cite news|author=Helena Bottemiller Evich|newspaper=Politico|title=How Joe Biden would address agriculture and rural issues|date=July 17, 2019|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/07/17/joe-biden-agriculture-rural-2020-1598121}}</ref>\n\n===Banking===\nDuring the 2000s, Biden sponsored bankruptcy legislation, which was sought by [[MBNA]], one of Delaware's largest companies and Biden's largest contributor in the late 1990s,<ref name=usatoday09302015 /> and other credit card issuers.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\">''Almanac of American Politics'' 2008, p. 364.</ref> He fought for certain amendments to the bill that would indirectly protect homeowners and forbid felons from using bankruptcy to discharge fines.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\" /> He also worked to defeat amendments which would have protected members of the military and those who are pushed into bankruptcy by medical debt. Critics expressed concern that the law would force those seeking bankruptcy protection to hire lawyers to process the required paperwork and would make it more difficult for students to execute education-related debt.<ref name=usatoday09302015>{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2015/09/30/joe-biden-senate-record-2016-campaign/73045484/ | title=Joe Biden's record could pose difficulties for 2016 White House bid | author=Przybyla, Heidi | publisher=USA Today | date=September 30, 2015 | accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref> The overall bill was vetoed by President [[Bill Clinton]] in 2000, but then finally passed as the [[Bankruptcy Abuse Prevention and Consumer Protection Act]] in 2005, with Biden supporting it.<ref name=\"aap08-bio\" />\n\n===Energy and environment===\nBiden has been credited with introducing the first climate change bill in Congress.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|author=John Kruzel|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2019/may/08/joe-biden/was-joe-biden-climate-change-pioneer-congress-hist/|title=Yes, Joe Biden was a climate change pioneer in Congress|website=PolitiFact|date=May 8, 2019}}</ref> Biden's initial bill, the Global Climate Protection Act, was introduced in 1986; it died in the Senate, but a version was included in a bill signed into law by President Reagan as an amendment to the Foreign Relations Authorization Act in December 1987.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2008, Biden was the lead sponsor of a \"Sense of the Senate\" resolution calling on the U.S. to be a part of the United Nations climate change negotiations, and was a cosponsor of the [[Barbara Boxer|Boxer]]-[[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]] [[Global Warming Pollution Reduction Act]], at the time the most stringent climate bill in the Senate. The legislation would have created a [[cap-and-trade]] system for [[greenhouse-gas emissions]] and required a reduction in U.S. emissions to 1990 levels by 2020, and to 80% below 1990 levels by 2050.<ref name=Grist>[https://grist.org/article/biden_factsheet/ A look at the environmental record of Joe Biden, Barack Obama\u2019s running mate], ''Grist'' (August 30, 2007, updated August 23, 2008).</ref> He strongly opposed [[Arctic Refuge drilling controversy|opening the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge to oil drilling]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anwr.org/Politics/Presidential-Candidates-views-on-ANWR-The-Democrats.php |title=Arctic Power \u2013 Arctic National Wildlife Refuge \u2013 Presidential Candidates views on ANWR, The Democrats |accessdate=August 25, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080807162357/http://www.anwr.org/Politics/Presidential-Candidates-views-on-ANWR-The-Democrats.php |archivedate=August 7, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/17/politics/senate-votes-to-allow-drilling-in-arctic-reserve.html|newspaper=New York Times|date=March 17, 2005|title=Senate Votes to Allow Drilling in Arctic Reserve|author=Sheryl Gay Stolberg}}</ref>  In 2007&ndash;2008, during his presidential camoaign, Biden called for a gradual increase in automobile fuel-economy standards to 40 miles per gallon by 2017,<ref name=Grist/> called for increase production of [[renewable energy]],<ref name=Grist/> and identified [[energy security]] and resolving the [[energy crisis]] as key priorities.<ref>Amanda Little, [https://grist.org/article/biden/ An interview with Joe Biden about energy and the environment], ''Grist'' (August 30, 2007)</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|Biden's presidential campaign]] unveiled a $1.7 trillion climate policy plan aimed at eliminate U.S. net greenhouse gas emissions by 2050. The proposal incorporated elements of the [[Green New Deal]] proposal.<ref name=CNNClimatePlan>{{cite web|authors=Eric Bradner & Arlette Saenz|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/04/politics/joe-biden-2020-climate-plan/index.html|title=Joe Biden's climate plan targets net-zero emissions by 2050|date=June 4, 2019|publisher=CNN}}</ref> Biden's plan would eliminate fossil fuel subsidies; halt issuance of new permits for oil and gas extraction on public land and water; step up [[Clean Air Act of 1963|Clean Air Act]] enforcement; strengthen [[Fuel economy in automobiles|fuel economy]] standards to promote a shift to [[electric vehicle]]s; regulate [[methane pollution]]; and create \"aggressive\" [[Efficient energy use|energy efficiency]] standards for appliances and buildings.<ref name=CNNClimatePlan/> Biden also promised that he would re-enter the [[Paris Agreement]] (from [[United States withdrawal from the Paris Agreement|which Trump pulled the U.S.]]) on his first day in the White House and called for \"a major diplomatic push to raise the ambitions of countries' climate targets.\"<ref name=CNNClimatePlan/> To pressure countries failing to meet their climate obligations, Biden also called for \"carbon adjustment fees\" to be levied on goods imported from countries that failed to meet emissions targets.<ref name=CNNClimatePlan/>\n\n===Transportation===\nDuring the Obama administration, Biden was the lead figure promoting the administration's proposal to spend $53 billion over six years toward construction of a national intercity [[high-speed rail]] network, in furtherance of Obama's goal (outlined in the [[2011 State of the Union Address]]) to extend high-speed rail access to 80% of the American population over a quarter-century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2011/02/08/vice-president-biden-announces-six-year-plan-build-national-high-speed-r|title=Vice President Biden Announces Six Year Plan to Build National High-Speed Rail Network|publisher=White House Office of the Vice President|date=February 8, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2011/POLITICS/02/08/biden.rail.network/index.html|author=Tanya Snyder|publisher=CNN|title=Biden announces $53 billion high-speed rail plan|date=February 8, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704364004576132091951242426|title=Biden Announces $53 Billion Rail-Funding Plan|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|date=February 8, 2011|author=Jared A. Favole & Josh Mitchell}}</ref> Republicans in Congress rejected the proposal, which did not advance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/2011/0208/GOP-critic-calls-Joe-Biden-s-53-billion-high-speed-rail-plan-insanity|title=GOP critic calls Joe Biden's $53 billion high-speed rail plan 'insanity'|newspaper=Christian Science Monitor|date=February 8, 2011|author=Daniel B. Wood}}</ref><ref name=DejaVu>{{cite web|author=Tanya Snyder|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/14/joe-biden-infrastructure-plan-070977|newspaper=Politico|date=November 14, 2019|title=Joe Biden's infrastructure deja vu}}</ref> \n\nDuring his 2020 presidential campaign, Biden has released a $1.3 trillion [[infrastructure]] improvement plan, which would follow up on Obama administration priorities.<ref name=SnyderInfrastructurePlan>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/14/biden-releases-13-trillion-infrastructure-plan-070848|title=Biden releases $1.3 trillion infrastructure plan|date=November 14, 2019|newspaper=Politico|author=Tanya Snyder}}</ref> The plan calls for $50 billion investment in repairs to existing roads and bridges in his first year in office; $10 billion over a decade to transit construction in high-poverty parts of the U.S.; doubling funding for [[Transportation Investment Generating Economic Recovery|BUILD]] and INFRA grants, and more funds for the [[U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]].<ref name=SnyderInfrastructurePlan/> The plan also includes proposals for investments in high-speed rail, public transit, and bicycling,<ref name=DejaVu/> as well as school construction, replacement of water pipes and other water infrastructure, and expansion of rural broadband.<ref name=Pramuk>{{cite web|author=Jacob Pramuk|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/14/joe-biden-releases-infrastructure-plan-and-criticizes-trump.html|title=Joe Biden proposes $1.3 trillion infrastructure overhaul \u2014 and swipes at Trump for inaction|publisher=CNBC|date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> The plan also specifically calls for the rebuilding of the [[North River Tunnels|Hudson River Tunnel]] and the expansion of the [[Northeast Corridor]], as well as rail investments in California and the Midwest and West.<ref name=DejaVu/> Biden proposed funding the plan through tax increases on high-income Americans and corporations; the campaign stated that \"reversing the excesses of the Trump tax cuts for corporations; reducing incentives for tax havens, evasion, and outsourcing; ensuring corporations pay their fair share; closing other loopholes in our tax code that reward wealth, not work; and ending subsidies for fossil fuels\" would provide the revenue for the plan, making it deficit-neutral.<ref name=Pramuk/>\n\n===Trade policy===\nIn the Senate, Biden had a mixed record on [[trade policy]],<ref name=Gussert>{{cite news|author=Andrew Gussert|title=Biden's Record on Trade|url=https://www.iatp.org/news/bidens-record-on-trade|publisher=Institute for Agriculture and Trade Policy/Citizens Trade Campaign|date=September 17, 2008}}</ref><ref name=O'Neill>{{cite news|author=Kevin O'Neill, L. Charles Landgraf, Amy Budner Smith, David J.M. Skillman & Marne Marotta|title=Trading \"America First\" for American Leadership in Trade Policy|date=February 21, 2020|url=https://www.arnoldporter.com/en/perspectives/publications/2020/02/trading-america-first-for|publisher=[[Arnold & Porter]]}}</ref> but consistently supported \"a U.S.-led, [[rules-based international order]] with an emphasis on reducing [[trade barrier]]s and setting global trade standards.\"<ref name=CSISTrade>{{cite news|authors=Jack Caporal & John Hoffner|publisher=Center for Strategic and International Studies|title=What Is Former Vice President Biden's Policy on Trade?|url=https://www.csis.org/analysis/what-former-vice-president-bidens-policy-trade|date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> He voted in favor of the [[North American Free Trade Agreement]] (NAFTA), [[Australia\u2013United States Free Trade Agreement|Australia-U.S. Free Trade Agreement]], and [[Morocco\u2013United States Free Trade Agreement|Morocco-U.S. Free Trade Agreement]], but voted against free-trade agreements with [[Singapore\u2013United States Free Trade Agreement|Singapore]], [[Chile\u2013United States Free Trade Agreement|Chile]], the [[Oman\u2013United States Free Trade Agreement|Oman]], and [[Dominican Republic\u2013Central America Free Trade Agreement|the Dominican Republic and Central America]] (CAFTA), viewing their labor and environmental protections as insufficient.<ref name=Gussert/><ref name=O'Neill/> He voted in favor of [[Fast track (trade)|fast track trade promotion authority]] in 1998 and in favor of [[permanent normal trade relations]] with China in 2000.<ref name=Gussert/><ref name=O'Neill/> During the [[Obama administration]], Biden was a strong advocate for the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/267420-biden-coaxes-dems-on-obama-trade-deal|title=Biden coaxes Dems on Obama trade deal|author=Mike Lillis|date=January 28, 2016|website=The Hill}}</ref> arguing that the U.S. withdrawal from the TPP \"put China in the driver's seat\" by allowing it to \"write the [[International trade law|rules of the road]] for the world\" in the absence of U.S. participation.<ref name=O'Neill/>\n\nBiden has been critical of Chinese trade tactics, including \"[[Dumping (pricing policy)|dumping]]\" of steel and Chinese theft of U.S. [[intellectual property]].<ref name=O'Neill/>  He has criticized the [[Trump trade war]] with China for failing to \"resolve the issues at the heart of the dispute\";<ref name=O'Neill/> for the trade war's negative effect on U.S. agriculture and manufacturing;<ref name=O'Neill/> and for Trump's unilateral approach.<ref name=CSISTrade/> Biden also criticized Trump for labeling Canada and the European Union as \"national security threats,\"<ref name=O'Neill/> and has arguing that this undercuts multilateral efforts with allies to combat Chinese trade abuses.<ref name=O'Neill/><ref name=CSISTrade/> He supports pressuring China on environmental issues and supports the [[United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement]].<ref name=O'Neill/>\n\n===Healthcare===\nBiden is a staunch supporter of the [[Affordable Care Act]] (ACA), the Obama administration's signature [[health care reform]] legislation.<ref name=ACA20>Dan Diamond, [https://www.politico.com/story/2019/07/15/joe-biden-health-care-plan-1415850 Biden unveils health care plan: Affordable Care Act 2.0], ''Politico'' (July 15, 2019).</ref><ref>Bill Barrow, [https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/biden-aggressively-defends-the-affordable-care-act Biden aggressively defends the Affordable Care Act], Associated Press (July 15, 2019).</ref> He has condemned the Trump administration's attempts to strike down the ACA in court.<ref name=ACA20/> During his 2020 presidential campaign, Biden has promoted a plan to expand and build upon the ACA, paid for by revenue gained from reversing some Trump administration tax cuts.<ref name=ACA20/> Biden's plan is to create a [[public health insurance option|public option]] for health insurance, with the aim of expanding health insurance coverage to 97% of Americans.<ref name=ACA20/> He does not support [[single-payer health care]] proposals such as [[Medicare for All]].<ref>Katie Glueck, Shane Goldmacher & Glenn Thrush, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/08/us/politics/biden-sanders-campaign-policy.html Now Comes the Hard Part for Joe Biden], ''New York Times'' (April 8, 2020).</ref> Under Biden's proposal, \"no one would be required to pay more than 8.5 percent of their income toward health insurance premiums.\"<ref>Julie Rovner, [https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2019/07/20/743248732/radical-or-incremental-whats-really-in-joe-bidens-health-plan Radical Or Incremental? What's Really In Joe Biden's Health Plan], NPR (July 20, 2019).</ref> Under Biden's plan, all those on the [[Individually purchased health insurance|individual insurance market]] would qualify for tax credits on premiums (a change from existing law, which caps premium tax credits at four times the federal poverty level, or under $50,000 for an independent). To reduce [[Prescription drug prices in the United States|prescription drug prices]], Biden proposes allowing import of prescription drugs and authorizing Medicare to directly negotiate drug prices.<ref name=ACA20/>\n\n===Labor unions===\nBiden was given an 85% lifetime approval rating from [[AFL\u2013CIO]].<ref name=aflcio>{{cite web|title=AFL-CIO Democratic Forum|url=http://www.factcheck.org/elections-2008/afl-cio_democratic_forum.html|publisher=Annenberg Public Policy Center|work=FactCheck|accessdate=4 April 2013|date=August 8, 2007|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130615051059/http://www.factcheck.org/elections-2008/afl-cio_democratic_forum.html|archivedate=June 15, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nBiden was a [[sponsor (legislative)|cosponsor]] of the [[Employee Free Choice Act]].<ref>{{cite web |title=S.1041 - Employee Free Choice Act of 2007 |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/110th-congress/senate-bill/1041/cosponsors |website=Congress.gov |accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Tax===\nBiden opposed the [[Bush tax cuts|George W. Bush administration's tax cuts]] enacted mostly in 2001 and 2003, noting that most of the benefits of the tax cuts went to the very wealthiest U.S. families, and arguing that the cuts did not help working-class and middle-class Americans.<ref name=Umhoefer>{{cite web|author=Dave Umhoefer|url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2012/sep/09/joe-biden/biden-says-500-billion-bush-tax-cuts-wealthy-would/|title=Biden says $500 billion of Bush tax cuts for wealthy would go to 120,000 families|work=PolitiFact|date=September 9, 2012}}</ref> The Obama/Biden administrator advocated keeping the cuts in place for 98% of U.S. taxpayers but letting them expire on income over $250,000 earned by couples (or income over $200,000 for individuals).<ref name=Umhoefer/>\n\nAfter the [[United States elections, 2012|Republicans took control of Congress in the 2010 election]], Biden was designated as the administrator's chief negotiator with Republican&mdash;specifically, [[Senate Majority Leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]]&mdash;regarding the Bush tax cuts, which were about to expire.<ref name=Grunwald>{{cite web|author=Michael Grunwald|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2019/04/30/biden-bipartisan-dealmaking-backfire-226758|date=April 30, 2019|title=Joe Biden Actually Is a Dealmaker. And That Could Be a Problem in 2020|work=Politico Magazine|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The administration opposed extending Bush tax cuts for the wealthy, but also did not want to trigger tax cuts for non-wealthy Americans when the economy was continuing to recover from the [[Great Recession]].<ref name=Grunwald/> The result was a deal: \"Biden and McConnell hashed out a deal that extended all the Bush tax cuts until after the 2012 election, while injecting another $300 billion as an economic stimulus, including a new [[payroll tax]] cut for workers, extended unemployment benefits for victims of the recession and expanded [[tax credit]]s for college students and the poor. By reopening the Senate, the deal also enabled the historic vote to repeal the ban on gays in the military.\"<ref name=Grunwald/>\n\n===Welfare===\nBiden opposes the privatization of [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] and was given an 89% approval rating from the [[Alliance for Retired Americans]] (ARA), reflecting a pro-[[Old age|senior citizen]] voting record. He voted in support of welfare [[Block grant (United States)|block grants]] and supports [[welfare reform]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/Economic/Joe_Biden_Welfare_+_Poverty.htm |title=Joe Biden on Welfare & Poverty |publisher=Ontheissues.org |accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref>{{which|date=March 2019}}\n\n==Foreign policy==\n[[File:Hashim Thaci Joe Biden Fatmir Sejdiu with Declaration of Independence of Kosovo.JPG|thumb|250px|Former rebel leader [[Hashim Tha\u00e7i]] and Biden with [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|Declaration of Independence of Kosovo]]]]\n\n===Africa===\nBiden favored an American deployment of troops to [[Darfur]] during the [[war in Darfur]], saying that 2,500 U.S. troops could stop the violence in the region.<ref name=CFR>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080206202245/http://www.cfr.org/bios/1451/joseph_r_biden_jr.html|title=Joseph R. Biden, Jr. \u2013 Council on Foreign Relations|accessdate=August 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\nBiden opposed to U.S. government funding of [[abstinence-only sex education]] programs in Africa, and in 2007, cosponsored the HIV Prevention Act which would end President [[George W. Bush]]'s mandate that one-third of all funds be earmarked to abstinence-only programs.<ref name=CFR/>\n\n===Middle East===\n==== Iran ====\nAs chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|Senate Foreign Relations Committee]], Sen. Biden has been a prominent voice calling for \"hard-headed diplomacy\" with [[Iran]]. In July 2008, Biden should first engage directly with Iran in the context of talks with the Permanent Five Members of the UN Security Council and Germany, and \"ultimately country-to-country, just as we did with [[North Korea]].\" He also has called for the implementation of \"coordinated [[Sanctions against Iran|international sanction]]s\" on Iran, adding \"we should complement this pressure by presenting a detailed, positive vision for [[Iran\u2013United States relations|U.S.\u2013Iran relations]] if Iran does the right thing.\"<ref name=CFR/>\n\nIn 2007, Biden voted against a measure to declare the [[Iranian Revolutionary Guard Corps]] a terrorist organization. He wrote in December 2007 that \"War with Iran is not just a bad option. It would be a disaster.\" Biden threatened to initiate impeachment proceedings against President Bush if he had started a war with Iran without Congressional approval.<ref name=CFR/> In an interview in September 2008, Biden stated that the Iranian Revolutionary Guard Corps was a terrorist organization and that the Bush administration already had the power to designate it as one. He stated that he voted against the measure out of concern that the Bush administration would misuse the measure to justify a military attack against Iran.<ref name=JTA932008/>\n\nIn early April 2009, Biden told [[CNN]] that he believed that [[Israel]] would not launch a unilateral strike against Iran's nuclear facilities. Biden stated that \"I think (Israel) would be ill-advised to do that. And so my level of concern is no different than it was a year ago.\"<ref>[http://jta.org/news/article/2009/04/07/1004327/biden-israel-wont-hit-iran Biden: Israel won\u2019t hit Iran] by Ron Kampeas, Jewish Telegraphic Agency (JTA), April 7, 2009.</ref>\n\n==== Iraq ====\n[[File:Senator Joe Biden speaks to SEIU 2.jpg|thumb|Joe Biden speaking]]\n\nIn 1990, after [[Ba'athist Iraq|Iraq]] under [[Saddam Hussein]] invaded [[Kuwait]], Biden voted against the first [[Gulf War]], asking: \"What vital interests of the United States justify sending Americans to their deaths in the sands of [[Saudi Arabia]]?\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122049148440397625|title=Biden Was Wrong On the Cold War|last=Wehner|first=Peter|work=The Wall Street Journal|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006022121/http://online.wsj.com/public/article_print/SB122049148440397625.html|archivedate=October 6, 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1998, Biden expressed support for the use of force against [[Iraq]] and urged a sustained effort to \"dethrone\" [[Saddam Hussein]] over the long haul.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/inatl/longterm/iraq/stories/iraq111398a.htm | title=Support for U.S. Stance on Iraq Grows | author=Thomas W. Lippman and Bradley Graham |work=The Washington Post | date=November 13, 1998}}</ref> In 2002, as Chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|Senate Foreign Relations Committee]], he stated that Saddam Hussein was \"a long-term threat and a short term threat to our national security\" and that the United States has \"no choice but to eliminate the threat\".<ref name=\"MTP04292007\">{{cite news | url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/18381961 | title=MTP Transcript for April 29, 2007 | author=Tim Russert | publisher=[[NBC News]] | date=April 29, 2007 |page=2| author-link=Tim Russert }}</ref> He also said, \"I think Saddam either has to be separated from his weapons or taken out of power.\"<ref>Meet the Press August 2002 interview with Tim Russert http://www.michaelmoore.com/mustread/index.php?id=1040</ref> Biden also supported a failed resolution authorizing military action in Iraq only after the exhaustion of diplomatic efforts,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/24/us/politics/24policy.html|title=New York Times \u2013 A Democratic Leader on Foreign Policy, In Iraq and the Balkans | work=The New York Times | first=Michael R. | last=Gordon | date=August 24, 2008 | accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref> Biden argued that Saddam Hussein possessed [[Chemical warfare|chemical]] and [[Biological warfare|biological weapons]] and is seeking [[Nuclear warfare|nuclear weapons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=2002_record&docid=cr10oc02-70|title=Congressional Record, Volume 148 Issue 133 (Thursday, October 10, 2002)|website=frwebgate.access.gpo.gov}}</ref> Biden subsequently voted in favor of authorizing the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]].<ref name=\"PATRIOTT01\"/>\n\nIn 2006, about three years into the war in Iraq, Biden believed the original authorization on the use of military force in Iraq in 2002 had been a mistake because [[President Bush (2000)|President Bush]] \"used his congressional authority unwisely.\" Biden argued that the 2002 resolution needed revision because Saddam Hussein had since been deposed and executed, and because the [[Weapon of mass destruction|weapons of mass destruction]] that the Iraq regime supposedly had stockpiled \u2014 a principal justification by the Bush administration for going to war \u2014 were never found. Biden opposed increasing troops in Iraq while favoring the training of Iraqi soldiers to maintain the security of their own country and said U.S. troops should \"responsibly draw down\" and not stay in Iraq indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/cq/2007/02/15/cq_2284.html|title=Biden Favors Revised Iraq War Resolution, Promotes Partition Plan|newspaper=The New York Times|last=Giroux|first=Greg|date=February 15, 2007|access-date=September 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2007, Biden and Sen. [[Sam Brownback]], (R-KS), introduced a [[non-binding resolution]] (originally drafted with [[Leslie H. Gelb]]) to the U.S. Senate regarding Iraq's political future. The measure proposed \"a decentralized Iraqi government based upon the principles of [[federalism]] and advocates for a relatively weak central government with strong [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]], [[Shia Islam|Shiite]], and [[Iraqi Kurdistan|Kurdish]] regional administrations.\"<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/backgrounder/plans-iraqs-future-federalism-separatism-and-partition|title=Plans for Iraq's Future: Federalism, Separatism, and Partition|website=Council on Foreign Relations|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\nKey points include:\n\n#Giving Iraq's major groups a measure of [[autonomy]] in their own regions. A central government would be left in charge of interests such as defending the borders and distributing [[Iraq oil law (2007)|oil revenues]].\n#Guaranteeing Sunnis\u2014who have no oil rights\u2014a proportionate share of oil revenue and reintegrating those who have not fought against Coalition forces.\n#Increase, not end, reconstruction assistance but insist that [[Arab states of the Persian Gulf]] fund it and tie it to the creation of a jobs program and to the protection of [[Ethnic group|minority]] rights.\n#Initiate a diplomatic offensive to enlist the support of the major powers and neighboring countries for a political settlement in Iraq and create an Oversight Contact Group to enforce regional commitments.\n#Begin the phased redeployment of U.S. forces in 2007 and withdraw most of them by 2008, leaving a small follow-on force for security and policing actions.\n\nThe bill passed the Senate by a 75 to 23 margin. Reception from Iraqi politicians and the divided [[Iraqi governments after 2003|Iraqi government]] was mixed. The [[United Iraqi Alliance]] denounced the resolution \"as a U.S. attempt to meddle in Iraqi sovereignty.\" The [[U.S. Embassy in Iraq]] warned that it \"would produce extraordinary suffering and bloodshed.\" President of Iraq [[Jalal Talabani]], who was Kurdish, supported the resolution.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> The Iraqi people did not view the resolution favorably. According to a 2007 poll conducted by the [[BBC]], 9% of the Iraqi people believed in a partitioned Iraq, 28% believed in a combination of regional governments and a federal government, and 62% believed in a unified Iraq with a centralized government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/bsp/hi/pdfs/10_09_07_iraqpoll.pdf|title=Iraq Poll September 2007|last=|first=|date=2007|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, in conversation with [[Katie Couric]], Biden disagreed with President Bush's position on Iraq as the primary war in the War on Terror.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/event/conversation-joseph-r-biden|title=A Conversation with Joseph R. Biden|website=Council on Foreign Relations|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=[The Afghanistan-Pakistan border] is where we must, in my view, urgently shift our focus to the real central front on the so-called war on terrorism, using the totality of America's strength... The original sin was starting a war of choice [the intervention in Iraq] before we finished a war of necessity [the war in Afghanistan]. And we're paying a terrible price for diverting our forces and resources to Iraq from Afghanistan.|sign=Sen. Joe Biden|source=\"A Conversation with Joseph R. Biden\"}}\n\nIn a 2016 interview with [[Richard N. Haass]], President of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]], Biden spoke about changing \"the fundamental approach [America] had to the Middle East\", and that the lesson learned from Iraq is \"the use of force with large standing armies in place was extremely costly, [and] would work until the moment we left.\"<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/event/future-us-foreign-policy-conversation-vice-president-joe-biden|title=The Future of U.S. Foreign Policy: A Conversation With Vice President Joe Biden|website=Council on Foreign Relations|language=en|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n==== Israel ====\nBiden is a self-described [[Zionist]].<ref name=CFR/> During an interview conducted by the U.S. Jewish television cable network [[Jewish Broadcasting Service|Shalom TV]], Biden said, \"I am a Zionist. You don't have to be a Jew to be a Zionist.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ynet.co.il/english/articles/0,7340,L-3586542,00.html |title=Biden in 2007 interview: I am a Zionist \u2013 Israel News, Ynetnews |publisher=Ynet.co.il |date=June 20, 1995 |accessdate=December 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe is highly supportive of the state of [[Israel]] and views Israel as a strategic ally in the Middle East.<ref name=\"NuclearIran\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gulfnews.com/region/Middle_East/10241824.html|title=Israel must come to terms with nuclear Iran}}</ref> He stated that \"the Arab nations have known that there is no daylight between us and Israel.\"<ref>Jennifer Siegel: [http://www.forward.com/articles/presidential-hopeful-slams-bush-for-stance-on-syri/ Presidential Hopeful Slams Bush for Stance on Syria] [[The Jewish Daily Forward]], March 21, 2007.</ref> Regarding support for Israel within the Democratic Party, Biden has stated that the Democrats' support for Israel \"comes from our gut, moves through our heart, and ends up in our head. It's almost genetic.\"<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/pages/ShArt.jhtml?itemNo=755798 Joseph Biden, Democrat], profile at [[Haaretz]], October 23, 2006.</ref> In September 2008, Biden stated \"A strong America is a strong Israel. I have a 35-year record of supporting Israel, and Israel's security is enhanced the stronger America is.\"<ref>[http://www.jewishexponent.com/article/17064/ Candidate Biden: U.S., Israel Joined at the Hip] by Aaron Passman, The Jewish Exponent, September 11, 2008.</ref>\n[[File:Biden at economic forum 2003 crop.jpg|thumb|left|Joe Biden at the [[World Economic Forum]] in Jordan in 2003]]\n\nIn a speech to several hundred older [[American Jews]] at a Florida retirement community, Biden stressed that he and Barack Obama are strongly pro-Israel. Biden stated \"I am chairman of the Foreign Relations Committee. I give you my word as a Biden, I would not have given up that job to be Barack Obama's vice president if I didn't in my gut and in my heart and in my head know that Barack Obama is exactly where I am on Israel. And he is ... I promise you ... we will make [Israel] more secure.\" Biden also criticized the presidency of [[George W. Bush]], stating that \"By any objective fact, Israel is less secure today in the world than it was eight years ago.\"<ref>[http://www.jta.org/cgi-bin/iowa/breaking/110185.html Biden reassures Florida Jews on Israel], Jewish Telegraph Agency (JTA), September 2, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/local/palmbeach/sfl-flpbiden0903pnsep03,0,5617985.story Sen. Joe Biden reiterates support for Israel at two South Florida rallies] by Mark Hollis and Juan Ortega, South Florida Sun-Sentinel, September 3, 2008.</ref>\n\nDuring a conference call to members of the Jewish media on September 3, 2008, Biden stated, in regard to a potential [[Iran\u2013Israel relations|Israeli military strike on Iranian nuclear facilities]], that it \"is not a question for us to tell the Israelis what they can and cannot do, I have faith in the democracy of Israel. They will arrive at the right decision that they view as being in their own interests.\" However, Biden stated that additional diplomatic efforts should be made to help avert the potential need for military action.<ref name=\"JTA932008\">[https://www.jta.org/2008/09/03/culture/biden-on-the-line-israel-needs-to-decide-on-iran-aipac-does-not-represent-the-entire-jewish-commun Biden on the line: Israel needs to decide on Iran, AIPAC does not represent the entire Jewish commun], Jewish Telegraph Agency (JTA), September 3, 2008</ref>\n\nIn September 2008, Biden spoke at the Washington Conference of the [[National Jewish Democratic Council]] (NJDC). Biden stated that \"I've spent 35 years of my career dealing with issues relating to Israel. My support for Israel begins in my stomach, goes to my heart and ends up in my head.\" Regarding Barack Obama's stance on Israel, Biden stated that \"I guarantee you, I would not have joined Barack Obama as his vice president if I had any doubt, even the slightest doubt, that he shares the same commitment to Israel I share.\" Biden also harshly denied a claim by the [[Republican Jewish Coalition]] (RJC) that he once attempted to cut off aid to Israel.<ref>[http://www.jta.org/cgi-bin/iowa/breaking/110520.html Biden at NJDC: Obama supports Israel], Jewish Telegraph Agency (JTA), September 24, 2008.</ref> NJDC director [[Ira Forman]] has praised Biden, stating that \"There is no one you could possibly pick who knows the issues, who is committed to Israel's security and knows Israeli leaders, as much as Joe Biden.\"<ref name=jsf1/>\n\nDuring the [[2008 United States vice-presidential debate|2008 vice-presidential debate]], Biden stated \"no one in the United States Senate has been a better friend to Israel than Joe Biden. I would have never, ever joined this ticket were I not absolutely sure Barack Obama shared my passion.\"<ref name=transcript1>[http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/10/02/debate.transcript/index.html Transcript of Palin, Biden debate], [[CNN]], October 2, 2008.</ref>\n\nIn November 2010, Biden served as the keynote speaker at the General Assembly (GA) of [[Jewish Federations of North America]], where he stated that \"This government will stand with Israel. It's in our own self-interest, beyond it being an absolute moral necessity.\" He also renewed his support for peace talks with the Palestinians, stating that \"There is no substitute for direct face-to-face negotiations leading eventually to states for two people secured\u2014the Jewish State of Israel and the viable independent state of Palestine. That is the only path to the Israeli people's decades-long quest for security, and the only path to the Palestinian people's legitimate aspirations for nationhood.\"<ref>[http://www.cjnews.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=20247&Itemid=86 U.S. VP stresses country\u2019s support for Israel] by Frances Kraft, Staff Reporter, Canadian Jewish News, November 11, 2010.</ref>\n\n===== American Israel Public Affairs Committee =====\nRegarding the [[American Israel Public Affairs Committee]] (AIPAC), Biden defended his right to oppose some AIPAC-backed measures. Biden stated that \"AIPAC does not speak for the entire American Jewish community. There's other organizations as strong and as consequential.\" Biden further stated that AIPAC does not speak for Israel. However, Biden added that \"I've never disagreed with AIPAC on the objective. Whenever I've had disagreement with AIPAC it has always been a tactical disagreement, not a substantive disagreement.\" Following this interview, an AIPAC spokesman praised Biden's leadership efforts on several fronts and stated that \"We look forward to continuing to work with him in the Senate or in the White House.\"\n<ref name=JTA932008/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.com/news/nation/elections/65667|title=Joe Biden: AIPAC doesn't speak for all Jews|last=|first=|date=2008-09-03|website=JewishJournal.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2008, Biden spoke with AIPAC leaders in a conference call. Following the meeting, an AIPAC spokesman stated that \"We had a very warm conversation with Senator Biden today, as we have many times throughout the years, about the importance of the U.S\u2013Israel relationship, and we look forward to continuing to work with him in the future. We had an opportunity to express our appreciation for his strong leadership in support of the U.S.\u2013Israel relationship, and we were pleased to hear Senator Biden reaffirm his desire to maintain his close relationship with AIPAC as we work together to strengthen the special friendship between the two democracies over many years to come.\" An adviser to the presidential campaign of Barack Obama stated that \"Senator Biden expressed his appreciation for AIPAC's important work supporting Israel's security and the U.S.\u2013Israel relationship, and that he looks forward to continuing to work with them as partners on these issues in the future as he has in the past.\"<ref>[http://www.jta.org/cgi-bin/iowa/breaking/110442.html Biden, AIPAC clear the air], Jewish Telegraph Agency (JTA), September 19, 2008.</ref>\n\n===== Israeli-Palestinian conflict =====\n[[File:Vice President Biden is Greeted by Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu (11936086646).jpg|thumb|Biden with Israeli Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]], January 2014]]\nBiden has stated he supports a [[two-state solution]] to the [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian conflict]]. Biden cosponsored the Palestinian Anti-Terrorism Act of 2006 which expressed U.S. support for a two-state solution.<ref name=CFR/><ref>[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/record.xpd?id=109-20060623-38#sMonofilemx003Ammx002Fmmx002Fmmx002Fmhomemx002Fmgovtrackmx002Fmdatamx002Fmusmx002Fm109mx002Fmcrmx002Fms20060623-38.xmlElementm4m0m0m \u201cMr. President, I support the Palestinian Anti-Terrorism Act of 2006...\u201d] ''govtrack.us''.</ref> During the [[2008 United States vice-presidential debate|2008 vice-presidential debate]], Biden stated that the Bush administration's policy with regard to the Middle East had been \"an abject failure\" and pledged that, if elected, he and Barack Obama would \"change this policy with thoughtful, real, live diplomacy that understands that you must back Israel in letting them negotiate, support their negotiation, and stand with them, not insist on policies like this administration has.\"<ref name=transcript1/>\n\nIn a March 2007 interview, Biden was asked about the failure to achieve peace between Israel and the Palestinians. Biden stated that \"Israel's a democracy and they make mistakes. But the notion that somehow if Israel just did the right thing, [the peace process] would work ... give me a break.\" He also stated that \"The responsibility rests on those who will not acknowledge the [[Israel's right to exist|right of Israel to exist]], will not play fair, will not deal, will not renounce terror.\"<ref name=jsf1>[http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/35942/format/html/displaystory.html Joe Biden and Israel are friends who fight] by Eric Fingerhut and Ron Kampeas, Jewish Telegraph Agency (JTA) (reprinted by the Jewish Weekly News of Northern California), August 29, 2008 (retrieved on November 1, 2008).</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Biden spoke at the AIPAC conference where he stated that Israel \"has to work towards a two-state solution\" and called on Israel to \"dismantle existing outposts and allow Palestinians freedom of movement.\" He also called on the Palestinians to \"combat terror and incitement against Israel.\"<ref>[https://nationalpost.com/news/world/story.html?id=1566212 U.S. presses Israel on two-state solution, settlements] by Matt Spetalnick and David Alexander, Reuters (reprinted by the National Post), May 5, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Biden addressed [[J Street]] with a rebuke of [[Netanyahu]]'s leadership in Israel. He said Israeli actions in promoting and expanding [[Israeli settlement|settlements]], legalization of [[Israeli outpost|outposts]], and land seizures are moving Israel toward a \"one-state reality\" and that reality is dangerous. He also said he had opposed Israeli settlements for more than three decades and believed that they are counterproductive to Israel's security. He cited Israeli settlements, as well as Palestinian recourse to the [[International Criminal Court]] as \"damaging moves that only take us further from the path toward peace\". In response to several terrorist attacks on Israeli civilians at the time, Biden called out [[Mahmoud Abbas|President Abbas]] for failing to condemn them. These comments were made while the Obama Administration was negotiating a multi-billion dollar defense deal with Israel, as the U.S. reaffirmed its commitment to the security of its closest Middle Eastern ally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/biden-admits-overwhelming-frustration-with-israeli-govt/|title=Biden admits to 'overwhelming frustration' with Israeli gov't|last=Stoil|first=Rebecca Shimoni|last2=AP|website=timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-israel-statement-idUSKCN11K2CI|title=U.S., Israel sign $38 billion military aid package|date=2016-09-15|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-06-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Libya ====\nIn an event in [[New Hampshire]], Biden spoke about the [[2011 intervention in Libya]]: \"NATO got it right. In this case, America spent $2 billion and didn't lose a single life. This is more the prescription for how to deal with the world as we go forward than it has in the past.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/oct/20/news/la-pn-santorum-kadafi-20111020|title=Kadafi death: Joe Biden says 'NATO got it right' in Libya|last=Memoli|first=Michael A.|date=October 20, 2011|via=LA Times}}</ref> Five years later, in an interview with [[Charlie Rose]], Biden stated he was \"strongly against going to Libya\" due to the instability it would cause within the country. He said, \"My question was, 'OK, tell me what happens.' He's gone. What happens? Doesn't the country disintegrate? What happens then? Doesn't it become a place where it becomes a [[petri dish]] for the growth of extremism? And it has.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/06/21/politics/joe-biden-hillary-clinton-libya/index.html|title=Biden says he predicted Libya instability|last=Producer|first=Kevin Liptak, CNN White House|website=CNN|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n==== Syria ====\n{{Main|Syrian Civil War}}\nIn a 2018 conversation for ''[[Foreign Affairs]]'', Biden described [[Syria]] as \"a classic example of the biggest conundrum that we have to deal with.\" He sees America's current situation in Syria as having \"lost the notion among our European friends that we know what we're doing, that we have a plan.\" He emphasized the necessity of stabilizing Syria, especially in major cities like [[Raqqa]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/event/foreign-affairs-issue-launch-former-vice-president-joe-biden|title=Foreign Affairs Issue Launch with Former Vice President Joe Biden|website=Council on Foreign Relations|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref> Raqqa is in ruins after lengthy battles between [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] and Kurdish forces, the [[Syrian Democratic Forces|SDF]], with assistance from the [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve|U.S.-led coalition]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/10/26/658142688/u-s-plan-to-stabilize-raqqa-and-stop-return-of-isis-doesnt-appear-to-be-working|title='This Is Not Liberation': Life In The Rubble Of Raqqa, Syria|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref> Biden said a multi-billion dollar investment is required to rebuild the city. He believes Iran, not Russia, will be the biggest beneficiaries in the short term, if Syria remains a battlefield. President [[Bashar al-Assad]] will also need to be removed from power, otherwise Syria will never have peace or security.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n{{Quote|text=The nonstarter is, for Russia, the idea that Assad stays in power and continues to control means there\u2019s a guarantee that there will never be peace or security in that country, because so many\u2014so many, you know, bottles have been broken here, man. I mean, there\u2019s no way he can put that together.|sign=Joe Biden|source=\"Foreign Affairs Issue Launch with Former Vice President Joe Biden\"}}\nBiden said there is no uniting principle in Syria, unlike Iraq, hence only certain safe harbors can be established in the region to reduce the number of displaced people and deaths.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n==== Saudi Arabia ====\nBiden criticized U.S. involvement in the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]] and Trump administration's policies toward [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref name=\"foreign-policy\"/> \n\n=== East Asia ===\n\n==== China ====\n[[File:Biden Raises a Toast in Honor of Chinese President Xi.jpg|thumbnail|Biden and China\u2019s leader [[Xi Jinping]] raised a toast at a State Dinner in September 2015]]\n\nIn 2011 and 2012, Biden spent several days with [[Xi Jinping]] and told him U.S. Only Supports Human Rights As \"Political Imperative\".<ref>https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/04/06/born-red Born Red\nHow Xi Jinping, an unremarkable provincial administrator, became China\u2019s most authoritarian leader since Mao.</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Biden described the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]] as an agreement that was as much about [[geopolitics]] as economics. Being part of the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]], he supported the agreement in an attempt to \"rebalance towards Asia\" against a stronger and bolder [[Foreign policy of China|Chinese foreign policy]] in the region.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nIn 2018, Biden said he had spent more time in private meetings with [[Paramount leader]] [[Xi Jinping]] than any other world leader. He believes Xi thinks of [[Russia]] as \"an occasional foil\", and neither countries will come together in an alliance, but both can use each other for benefits relative to America.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nOn June 4, 2019, Biden tweeted that \"China\u2019s continuing oppression of its own people, especially the abuse and [[Xinjiang re-education camps|internment]] of more than one million [[Uyghurs]], is one of the worst [[Human rights in China|human rights]] crises in the world today. It can\u2019t be ignored.\"<ref name=\"foreign-policy\">{{cite news |title=The Democratic candidates on foreign policy |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020-election/ |work=[[Foreign Policy]]}}</ref> He expressed support for [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests|Hong Kong's protests]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Hong Kong protesters are brave 'and the world is watching,' US democrat Joe Biden tells China |url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/06/15/hong-kong-protesters-brave-world-watching-us-democrat-joe-biden-tells-china/ |work=Hong Kong Free Press |date=June 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn June 11, 2019, Biden criticized [[Donald Trump]]'s \"damaging\" [[China\u2013United States trade war|trade war with China]].<ref name=\"foreign-policy\"/> \n\n==== North Korea ====\nBiden favors open dialogue with [[North Korea]] and describes them as a \"[[paper tiger]]\", unable to directly cause harm to America. However, in a June 2007 Democratic debate, he called the situation one of \"the three most important things that the next president is going to have to deal with\", along with [[Iran]] and [[Iraq]].<ref name=CFR/>\n\n=== Europe ===\n==== Russia ====\n[[File:Biden, berlusconi and medvedev.jpeg|thumb|Biden, Russia's President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] and Italy's Prime Minister [[Silvio Berlusconi]] meeting in Italy in June 2011]]\n[[File:VP Biden shakes hands with Petro Poroshenko June 7, 2014.jpg|thumb|Biden shakes hands with Ukrainian President [[Petro Poroshenko]], June 7, 2014]]\nIn 1999, Biden cosponsored a draft resolution condemning Russia's [[Second Chechen War|military campaign]] to crush a [[Chechen Republic of Ichkeria|Chechen separatist insurgency]], the use of indiscriminate force by the Russian army against civilians and violations of the [[Geneva Conventions|Geneva Convention]], and urged a peaceful resolution of the conflict.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.watchdog.cz/?show=000000&lang=1|title=Prague Watchdog - Crisis in Chechnya - www.watchdog.cz|website=watchdog.cz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=sr106-223|title=A resolution condemning the violence in Chechnya. (1999 - S.Res. 223)|website=GovTrack.us}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Biden cosponsored a Senate resolution criticizing Russia for failing to uphold its commitments at the 1999 [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]] (OSCE) Summit, which included agreements on a completed [[14th Army involvement in Transnistria|Russian military withdrawal]] from [[Moldova]]'s breakaway, pro-Russian region of [[Transnistria]]. That resolution also expressed disapproval of Russia's demand for the closure of the OSCE Border Monitoring Operation (BMO), which served to observe border crossings between Georgia and the Russian republics of [[Chechnya]], [[Dagestan]], and [[Ingushetia]]. That bill passed in the Senate.<ref name=CFR/>\n\nBiden introduced legislation in July 2008 urging members of the Group of Eight to \"work toward a more constructive relationship with Russia\", and encouraging Russia to behave according to the [[Group of Eight|G-8]]'s \"objectives of protecting global security, economic stability, and democracy.\" The resolution also called on Russian and U.S. leaders to increase cooperation and funding for the [[Nunn-Lugar program]] and other nonproliferation initiatives. It also emphasized the need for a successor to the [[START I|1991 Strategic Arms Reductions Treaty]]. The resolution passed.<ref name=CFR/>\n\nBiden has voiced concerns about Russia alleged [[democratic backsliding|backsliding on democratic reforms]]. In August 2008, Biden criticized Russia's [[Russo-Georgian War|military action in Georgia]] in support of [[South Ossetia]]n separatists. \"By acting disproportionately with a full-scale attack on [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and seeking the ouster of Georgia's democratically elected President [[Mikheil Saakashvili]], Moscow is jeopardizing its standing in Europe and the broader international community\u2014and risking very real practical and political consequences\", Biden wrote in a ''[[Financial Times]]'' op-ed. Biden urged Russia to abide by the negotiated cease-fire.<ref name=CFR/>\n\nIn a 2018 ''[[Foreign Affairs]]'' op-ed co-written with Michael Carpenter,<ref group=note>Former Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense and Senior Director for the [[Penn Biden center for Diplomacy and Global Engagement]]</ref> Biden described Russia as a [[Kleptocracy|kleptocratic]], [[Right-wing populism|nationalist-populist]] state that considers [[Western democracy]] its existential threat. He acknowledged that the [[Kremlin]] launched coordinated attacks across many domains\u2014military, political, economic, informational\u2014against various Western democratic countries, including [[cyberattack]]s on the [[2016 United States presidential election]] and [[2017 French presidential election]]. As a result of Russia's threat, Biden supports a \"strong response\" with cooperation from America's allies and campaign finance reform that will prohibit foreign donations from flowing into domestic elections.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/2017-12-05/how-stand-kremlin|title=How to Stand Up to the Kremlin|last=Biden|first=Joseph R.|date=2019-04-25|access-date=2019-06-12|last2=Jr|issue=January/February 2018|language=en-US|issn=0015-7120|last3=Carpenter|first3=Michael}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=Western democracies must also address glaring vulnerabilities in their electoral systems, financial sectors, cyber-infrastructure, and media ecosystems. The U.S. campaign finance system, for example, needs to be reformed to deny foreign actors\u2014from Russia and elsewhere\u2014the ability to interfere in American elections. Authorities can no longer turn a blind eye to the secretive bundling of donations that allows foreign money to flow to U.S. organizations (such as \u201cghost corporations\u201d) that in turn contribute to super PACs and other putatively independent political organizations, such as trade associations and so-called 501(c)(4) groups. Congress must get serious about campaign finance reform now; doing so should be a matter of bipartisan consensus since this vulnerability affects Democrats and Republicans in equal measure.|sign=Joe Biden, Michael Carpenter|source=\"How to Stand Up to the Kremlin\"}}\n\nHe also accused [[President trump|President Trump]] of \"[equivocating] on whether [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russia interfered]] in the 2016 election, even after he received briefings from top intelligence officials on precisely how Moscow did it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/2017-12-05/how-stand-kremlin|title=How to Stand Up to the Kremlin|last=Biden|first=Joseph R.|date=2019-04-25|access-date=2019-06-11|last2=Jr|issue=January/February 2018|language=en-US|issn=0015-7120|last3=Carpenter|first3=Michael}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2019 [[Munich Security Conference]], Biden reiterated his opposition to Russian interference in elections and their actions against European neighbors, saying, \"We have to be explicit in our response and make clear to Russia that there's a price to pay for these transgressions of international norms\", and that the U.S. needs to continue to support its [[NATO]] allies, as well as [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and [[Ukraine]] who are not part of NATO, by \"establishing virtually continuous air, land and sea presence on NATO's eastern perimeter.\" He also expressed explicit concern of Russian influence on [[American Politics|American politics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.securityconference.de/en/media-library/munich-security-conference-2019/video/statement-by-joseph-r-biden-jr-followed-by-qa/|title=Statement by Joseph R. Biden Jr. followed by Q&A|website=securityconference.de|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n===The Americas===\n\n==== Central America ====\nAs part of the Obama Administration, Biden supported the Central America Regional Security Initiative (CARSI) to combat [[drug cartel]]s and strengthen law enforcement in [[Central America]]. Between 2008 and 2011, the [[Department of State]] provided $361.5 million to Central American countries. The State Department stated five main goals to CARSI:\n\n# Create safe streets for the citizens in the region.\n# Disrupt the movement of criminals and contraband within and between the nations of Central America.\n# Support the development of strong, capable and accountable Central American governments.\n# Re-establish effective state presence and security in communities at risk.\n# Foster enhanced levels of security and rule of law coordination and cooperation between the nations of the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insightcrime.org/uncategorized/central-america-regional-security-initiative/|title=Central America Regional Security Initiative (CARSI)|last=Crime|first=InSight|date=2011-10-18|website=InSight Crime|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\nWhen Biden met with Central American leaders in [[Honduras]] in 2012, he reiterated the Obama Administration's pledge of $107 million in aid for the region. The Administration would work with Congress to provide the funds under CARSI. These initiatives were part of a larger effort for institutional reform in the region to counter [[Illegal drug trade|drug trafficking]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insightcrime.org/news/brief/no-new-aid-promises-from-biden-in-honduras/|title=No New Aid Promises from Biden in Honduras|last=Looft|first=Christopher|date=2012-03-07|website=InSight Crime|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2012/03/06/world/americas/honduras-biden/index.html|title=Biden visits Honduras amid drug legalization debate|last=Staff|first=By the CNN Wire|website=CNN|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2014 American immigration crisis|2014 Central American child-migrant crisis]], Biden supported a $1 billion economic aid package to affected Central American countries. In an op-ed for ''[[The New York Times]]'', he wrote, \"the security and prosperity of Central America are inextricably linked with our own.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/30/opinion/joe-biden-a-plan-for-central-america.html|title=Opinion {{!}} Joe Biden: A Plan for Central America|last=Jr|first=Joseph R. Biden|date=2015-01-29|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He also supported further institutional reforms to combat corruption in those countries, so they can provide their people with safer living conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2015/01/vice-president-joe-biden-central-america-aid-package-114755.html|title=Biden urges support for Central America aid package|last=Shutt|first=Jennifer|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\n====Cuba====\nPrior to the [[Cuban thaw]], Biden strongly opposed the [[Fidel Castro]] and [[Raul Castro]] government in [[Cuba]] and supported the continuation of the [[trade embargo]], as well as the democratization of the island in the post-Castro era. In 2006, Biden stated, \"We should be putting together a plan as to how we are going to play a positive role in moving that country, after the Castros are gone, to\u2014more toward democratization and liberalization in their society.\"<ref name=CFR/> However, Biden's support for the trade embargo ended on December 17, 2014, when then President [[Barack Obama]] announced reestablishment of [[Cuba\u2013United States relations|United States\u2013Cuba relations]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Political positions of Barack Obama]]\n* [[Political positions of Mitt Romney]]\n* [[Political positions of Paul Ryan]]\n* [[Political positions of John McCain]]\n* [[Political positions of Sarah Palin]]\n* [[Political positions of Bernie Sanders]]\n* [[Political positions of Donald Trump]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ontheissues.org/Joe_Biden.htm Joe Biden on the Issues]\n*[http://www.4biden.com/ Joe Biden \u2013 democratic candidate 2008]\n*[http://www.4biden.com/news/iraq-a-way-forward/ Iraq: A way forward]\n*[http://whereistand.com/JoeBiden Joe Biden's opinions \u2013 whereIstand.com]\n*[http://www.statesurge.com/members/903-joseph-r-jr-biden-federal Full list of Joe Biden's Legislation \u2013 statesurge.com]\n*[http://www.cfr.org/bios/1451/joseph_r_biden_jr.html Biden's 's position on top foreign policy issues]\n{{Joe Biden}}\n{{United States presidential election, 2008 navigation}}\n{{2020 United States presidential election}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biden, Joe}}\n[[Category:Political positions of the 2008 United States presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:Political positions of the 2020 United States presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:Political positions of United States senators]]\n[[Category:Joe Biden|Political positions]]\n", "name_user": "Harmonyharmo", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Political_positions_of_Joe_Biden"}
